reviewText: iPhone cases seem to come in two different varieties: fashionable lightweights which look nice but provide poor protection and larger cases that add protection along with bulk.  Personally I prefer function over form (Otterbox Defender!) but the Commuter is an excellent compromise that adds style and protection without a great deal of bulk.Unlike it's beefier sibling, the Commuter's rubber sleeve is is banded by a smooth plastic shell, which allows theCommuter to easily slide in and out of one's pocket. The case is actually two parts, a thin rubber piece which wraps over most of thephone, providing shock protection, and then the aforementioned plastic piece, which slides over the back of the phone vertically as a band, providing further protection. Finally, there is a screen protector, which must be manually applied and is prone to bubbling. All together, these provide three layers of protection.In daily use, the case provides fine protection against the usual hazards of iPhone ownership, such as pocket junk, random bangingagainst other objects, and sliding across tables, and it's dual layer protection is superior to the high fashion cases.  Although, I didn't actually test intentionally dropping the phone, based on the construction of the case, I am pretty confident it would survive a short fall onto a hard surface unless you got unlucky enough to have something impact the front glass.  I had enough close encounters with my iPhone 3GS and Commuter to trust Otterbox's design.What are the downsides of the Commuter? Well, just like the Model T, you can have the Commuter in any color you like, as long as it isblack. I was disappointed in the lack of any color options, but this may not be a big deal to many people and I'm sure Otterbox will develop more colors later on. Another negative was the slim flap which protects the dock connection; although a good idea intheory, the flap often comes loose and ends up just being annoying. Finally, the areas where the edges of the rubber of the case touchedthe phone (such as around the screen and the mute switch) seemed to become dust magnets, although to be fair, many rubber cases have the same issue.Overall, the Commuter is a great balance of protection in a lightweight design that easily slides in and out of your pocket.  For my spouse the protection the Commuter offers is "just right" -  more protection than the "free cases" Apple offered, with a minimal amount of bulk.  If the Otterbox iPhone 4 case was a car, the Commuter would be the luxury sedan while the Defender is a tank.  Not everyone wants to drive a tank to work.Pros:  A perfect balance of form and function and superior 3-layer protectionCons:  Lack of color choices, average manual screen protectionRating  4.5 out of 5.0
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Hybrid Case for AT&T and Verizon iPhone 4 (Purple/White) (Doesn't support iPhone 4S)

reviewText: I had good luck w/an Otterbox for my HTC Hero so I bought this one for my iPhone 4S. While the case functions perfectly as protection against bumps/drops, they've really missed some crucial points in the design of this one! The phone is all but unusuable as an iPod w/the case on. I can't get any ear buds or a male-to-male plug (for plugging into my car stereo) plugged in to the device w/o sliding the case off of the device, which is a total nuisance. I've ended up having to modify the case w/scissors but I'd suggest you look for another brand if you plan to use ear buds until such time that Otterbox wakes up and remedies this fatal flaw. If you're just looking for good protection and don't plan to use it as an iPod, it works pretty good. I did have to cut off the parts of the case that cover the earbud plug input and the power input as they both pop out and flop around the case frequently when I remove it from my pocket.

reviewText: I ordered this case for both my phone and my wife's phone. reviewText: Hi, I just got this case yesterday.  It's the third one I've tried with my iPhone 4.  Otterbox makes fine cases so I expected something nice and was not disappointed.  I also had the Commuter and Defender cases for my iPhone 3Gs.Here are some notes for you:- The case provides the best protection of the three I've tried.  The Apple bumper case is nice but the open back leaves a lot of glass exposed.  This one gets the job done while not being too bulky.- Compared to the iPhone 3Gs Commuter case this one exposes more of the hard plastic surface and less of the rubber.  The plastic is textured nicely so gripping is still secure.  In all fairness I think I do prefer the design of the 3G/3Gs version.- The phone will connect (Yeah!) to my Magellan car mount and B&W; speakers with this case.  It would not connect with the thicker Apple bumper case.  I'm also able to get other cables to connect to it that would not connect with the bumper case.  The opening for the thirty pin connector is larger on the Otterbox case.- Putting the screen protector on can be frustrating but I was mostly successful this time.  Dust must be avoided at all cost while applying it.  Hey Intel, can I use your clean room for a few minutes?It's a good compromise between protection and bulk.  If you had the 3G version you might be a little disappointed because the fit on this one doesn't seem quite as good.Update (9/2/2010):  The reviewer(s) that said the case can be uncomfortable on your ear while making calls was right.  If you make a lot of calls this could be rather annoying.  I'll post a picture or two of the offending sharp edge.  I filed the edge on mine with my Leatherman to smooth it out. reviewText: I'll start this review with saying that I really want to love this case, but there are a few issues about this case that I absolutely do not like. I'll start with the good...The case is very well made. It fits the phone pretty well and doesn't add a lot of bulk and weight. I love the textured plastic they use and the fact that their silicone inner layer doesn't grab the insides of my pockets and pick up lint, hair, etc. (the Incipio Silicrylic case is often compared to the OtterBox Commuter, but its silicone layer is very loose-fitting and picks up lint and particles from your pockets, etc.). I like that the buttons are covered and that the case has a lip that extends above the screen to protect against setting the phone down on surfaces (although I have a Zagg InvisiSHIELD on my iPhone so it wouldn't matter).The things I didn't like were that the case is a bit of a bear to get on the phone. The silicone goes on with ease, obviously because it's a stretchy rubber skin. However, the plastic takes some finagling. You have to sort of massage the silicone and plastic shel to get them to sit together seamlessly. Even then, it's not quite as snug as I'd like. Also, the port covers are annoying. This case is not waterproof, nor is it really water resistant so the port covers are a bit useless. The headphone port cover is a bit of a pain to get to go back in the slot (although not as tough as the one for my iPad, seen in another review). Also, the port on the bottom of the phone doesn't allow for larger accessories. I use a Griffin 10' charging cable and an iGo car adapter and neither one fit with this case. My final gripe is that they made a cutout for the Apple logo on the back, but there's no protection there. No clear plastic, no back glass protection film, nothing. They include a front screen protector, but nothing for the exposed logo on the back. The Commuter for iPad, while not my main case (see my review of that for why) has a plastic covering for the logo so it shows through, but remains protected. After just a few days of using this case, I pulled the phone out to switch to a different case and the back was filthy, especially around that hole. Not a good design choice by OtterBox at all. They so tightly covered all of the other ports and buttons, but just left the back wide open. Shame...While this is a good case and offers a lot of protection, it just wasn't for me.PROS:* Good fit (not great, but good)* Good level of protection* Good materials make this case look and feel great* Works great with my Zagg InvisiSHIELD screen protector (and others I'm sure)CONS:* Doesn't fit as snuggly as I'd like and getting the case on takes some finesse* Bottom port doesn't allow for third party chargers and accessories and docks are completely out of the question* Port covers are annoying and since this isn't a water proof/resistant case, they're a little unnecessary and just get in the way* Opening on back panel exposes Apple logo and lets in dirt and debris which is silly considering they went to all the trouble to close everything else up (a back glass protection film would be nice to have)* A little bit too bulky for my taste, but that's subjective so I'll leave that up to you :)
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Hybrid Case for AT&T and Verizon iPhone 4 (Purple/White) (Doesn't support iPhone 4S)

reviewText: I've had this case for about 5 months now and I would not hesitate to get it again. It provides solid protection against bumps, scratches, and simple drops without all the added bulk that the Otterbox Defender brings. My wife, who is more accident prone than I am, has the defender model, so that's my point of comparison. A few pros & cons:PROS:1. It does slide pretty easily in and out of my pocket.2. Covers for the ports are very functional - much more so than the Defender.3. I believe volume buttons are actually easier to push with this case than without a case at all.4. It just works...it does what it is suppose to do without any real inconveniences.5. Comes with a front screen protector (but I didn't use it).6. Easy to take off to clean the phone.CONS:1. As has been pointed out in multiple reviews, I had to get a fingernail file and sand down the plastic cover so it wouldn't bother my ear. It only took a few minutes though, so this isn't really a huge problem for me.2. No rear glass protector is included, which I think is a problem since they leave the Apple logo exposed.3. Dust tends to collect in the speakers and in the noise canceling mic.4. Very difficult to fit in my alarm clock docking station, but it will fit which is more than I can say for my wife's Defender protected phone.5. Somewhat difficult to flip the vibrate/ring switch since it is now recessed in the opening.6. The exposed silicon corners sometimes keep it from sliding with ease in and out of my pocket, but usually this is not an issue.I did not use the included screen protector and instead ordered a front and rear skin from BodyGuardz, so i cannot comment on the quality of the included screen protector.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Hybrid Case for AT&T and Verizon iPhone 4 (Purple/White) (Doesn't support iPhone 4S)

reviewText: First, I need to say that Amazon (and USPS) did everything right on its end.  The packaging was in superb condition when my Otterbox Commuter arrived.  The problem is with the seller, Ross Electronics.  This product did not come in retail packaging as advertised; it came bulk packaged, in a zip lock Baggie with an Avery label on it, and no instructions or warranty information.  Once I opened the Baggie, I came to suspect that this case had either sustained some real damage in a warehouse before being bagged, or it was just plain used.  The silicone sleeve was dusty, and severely damaged on the top left corner:  there was a "chewed" spot by the volume controls and a nasty tear by the headphone jack.  When I tried it on my phone, I saw that the hard plastic part was warped, so that it would not fit correctly on my phone.  I have ordered from Amazon countless times, and have never had a negative experience in the past, even with Marketplace sellers, before.  But Ross is shady.  Be warned.

reviewText: Before I upgraded to the iPhone4 I owned the 3G & 3GS.  Each of those phones were wrapped in the OtterBox Defender which were just plan awesome!  After awhile (we) switched cases to the Switch Easy and Seidio Rugged and found the full open face was very nice (bottom/top screen) not covered, but just not as nice as good ol OtterBox... until now! We ordered ALL 3 OtterBox cases for the iPhone 4 and ALL 3 are HORRIBLE! Since this review is for the COMMUTER CASE, I'll start there.  It is not that it is a bad case, but after two weeks the silicone is already coming loose! No other problem, but REALLY? Silcone losing its hold already... REALLY? Other than that... nice case, but I think I'll be switching to the Seidio Rugged once again... since they have made appropriate changes to CORRECT the problems. Unlike OTTERBOX WHOSE PERFECT CASES NOW SEEMED RUSHED AND FLIMSY!!!!! I miss my old 3G/3GS Defender!!!!! WAKE UP OTTERBOX!

reviewText: I've used Otterbox cases on a number of products and they are top notch.  This case for my Verizon iPhone 4 is no exception.  It comes in two parts, a neoprene sleeve and and a hard case that snaps over it.  Although the materials are quite thin in nature, the case adds a little bulk to the phone, but it's very acceptable and actually makes it easier to hold onto.  The cutout on the rear for the Apple Logo is a nice touch.When attached it protects the entire phone, front back and sides very well.  The phone should easily withstand a drop from 6ft. or so, probably higher, without incurring any damage.  The case fits almost perfectly.  I say "almost" because as others have mentioned the cutout for the mute switch on the side is slightly off.  However that hasn't been a hindrance as the switch is still accessible and can be moved without much problem.  That's the only reason I gave this case four starts instead of five. reviewText: I own both the Defender series and the Commuter series cases.  The Defender case can be rather bulky and hard to pull out of your pockets without taking everything else out at the same time, even the pocket itself!  The Commuter case feels solid and the rubber on the sides give you a secure grip when using your iPhone.  I've dropped it a few times on carpet and on hardwood floor accidentally while walking and my iPhone is fine.  This case is appropriate for folks like me who have to wear dress clothes everyday.  Its easily accessible to and from your pockets in virtually all dress clothes material and never pulls your pockets out.  However, i still use my Defender case when i go out on the weekends with family or jogging, outdoor activities, etc. because I use my iphone to take a lot of pictures.Defender case:Pros:a. Better Protection and more impact resistant than the Commuter and any other case in the market.b. The external rubber case is great for placing your iphone on your car dash or console and it will stay put!c. Rubber case makes it easy to take pictures as the iphone sticks to your hands!Cons:a. It's a little bulky for formal attire and even jeans. the rubber tends to stick on your pockets pulling everything out.b. There are no other cons!Commuter case:Pros:a. Not as bulky and case still feels pretty solid and protects iphone from drops.b. Doesn't cling to pocket sleeve.Cons:a. Not as sturdy as the Defender case.b. Not as easy to grip as the Defender for taking picturesc. Plastic part of the case just above the charging port is very thin and can break easily.  I have seen many complaints in the reviews about this part breaking!Both Cases have horrible screen protectors.  They reduce the retina display quality severely.  Resolution: Remove the Screen protector that comes with the Defender series case and don't install the screen protector that comes with the Commuter case.  If you use your iPhone a lot like me, it is hard to stick with only one case.  I recommend getting both of these cases and you will be set for all situations.  If you take a lot of pictures, get the Defender series.  Otherwise, get the Commuter series.  I hope this review helps. Thanks for reading!

reviewText: Unlike my Incipio Silicrylic iPhone case (which this is replacing), the OtterBox case appears to be almost indestructible...after about six months, the Incipio's silicone lining had torn and the hard plastic exterior had cracked. It's almost a cobalt blue in color.- The cover for the charger slot is hard to open.  None of the picture show a bottom view, but it's snug against the blue plastic outer case and protects the slot a bit too well.- As noted by another reviewer, if you have a right-angle plug on your headphones, it may not seat properly in the jack.  A standard small diameter barrel connector will work fine, as well as right-angle jacks where the metal plug protrudes a bit longer than necessary...see (for example) theStarTech.com MU6MMSRA Slim 3.5mm to Right Angle Stereo Audio Cable - M/M (6 Feet).Otherwise, I have absolutely no complaints about this case and those aren't enough to drop to a 4 star rating.  4.8 maybe, but certainly not below that.Highly recommended!

A big plus for my wife is that the bottom power on button is fully covered. This area is easy to get dirt and debris in so that is a nice touch.And you get a permanent screen cover without having to worry about bubbles or replacements. And the touch has not been negatively effected at all. Last couple of points. GREAT gripiness. Really good. And not only grippy but also soft and comfortable. Underneath is the protective piece. reviewText: This is my third experience with Otterbox, having previously protected my iPod Nano & Blackberry Tour.  When I decided to get the iPhone 4 for Verizon, this was an easy choice for me.  It's ideal for unexpected drops, bumps, and (minor) spills.  With all of their products, you sacrifice sleek and sexy for durable and sensible.  It adds bulk to the device, and covers the attractive edging, but if you're seriously considering an Otterbox, you're likely more concerned about not having to replace the thing when you inevitably drop it in a parking lot somewhere.  Contrary to some earlier reviews, I believe it fits the Verizon iPhone 4 just fine.  I can access the mute button without a problem.  I agree that the alignment is slightly off, but it's hardly a chore to reach it (for me at least).  Touch screen is not effected negatively at all by the built in screen cover (nor the two slots for the camera lenses).  Smudging is inevitable, but easily remedied with a wipe from a clean cloth.  The silicon cover does grip against some pocket materials, so you may find your pocket inside out every now and again when you pull it out.  I am fully confident that my iPhone 4 is safe and sound from the many drops that I will give it over the course of the next 2+ years.  That being said, I did spring for a 2 year protection plan because if you submerge it, or have a major spill, even this case will not be enough to save it.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: I've had the Otterbox Defender, and the AGF Ballistic case.  They both tend to have the bubbles problem, but it's an issue quickly fixed with a quick rub of a dryer sheet on the surfaces.  My Ballistic case is substantially more bulky than the Otterbox, but the Defender also works with all headphone plugs, and charging plugs where the AGF Ballistic protects far better with the extra layers of silicone rubber outside the dual (Rubber and Lexan) inner case.My Otterbox case has been broken several times from falls, and always keeps the phone inside protected from scratches and damage.  However, after less than one year, the holster clip broke off the case, allowing the phone to move around inside a little.  This also opened it up to some dust and dirt getting inside, and little micro scratches have formed.Otterbox doesn't have this color available now, but they are sending me a free replacement under their warrantee terms.If they didn't, I'd still be torn between the Otterbox, and AGF Ballistic.  Clearly, the Ballistic is better protection, but I can always easily find my Otterbox, because it comes in more colors than Black.

reviewText: A friend of mine has an iPhone 3GS and had a Defender case -- not only was it stylish, but with the way he literally abused the phone I could see the value of getting a Defender as soon as possible to protect one of your most valuable possessions - you iPhone!  The Defender was my very first purchase for both my iPhone 4 and my wife's, and so far I haven't been disappointed.  I still like the product 8 months later and would recommend it.Pros:- Very good protection - I've banged mine around a bit by accident and its never shown any issues -- note that I've never purposely tried to drop or abuse it and wouldn't recommend trying that unless you have a spare- Great feel - the rubberized outer protection layer makes this very comfortable to hold and provides a nice grip - I never liked the feel of an iPhone out of the case as it is too small and too slick feeling -- I always felt like I was going to drop it- the clip-on holster is sturdy and is a nice addition for people that don't want to carry their phone in a pocket or purse and is very sturdy (its been the only clip-on case that has ever lasted for more than 3 months for me - well done!)- clip-on holster can also be used as a stand for both portrait and landscape viewing - this is a great feature!- comes with a built-in screen protector - nice that I didn't have to buy/install a screen protector and its very easy to clean and keep clean- easy to install - wasn't near as bad as my initial impression and have done it several times since to clean the inside- all buttons/openings/etc on the iPhone are accessible and the covers fit (and stay) very nicely, this is much better than on the other Defender series cases for iPod Touch and iPad- price on Amazon currently is amazing - I'd highly recommend this based on the value you get -- in fact, I'd suggest you get a couple if you are planning to keep your iPhone 4 for 9 months or longerCons:- the rubberized outer layer is starting to show signs of stretching after 8 months of use, especially around the see-through window on the back - also noticing this around the covering for the 32-pin connector- the case doesn't fit together completely - when you squeeze the front and back of the case, you notice some movement and you'll also see that dust begins to creep into the inside of the case and shows up under the screen protector, which is one reason that I open and clean it every few months - though I also wonder how many times this was designed to be opened (am I compounding the issue by doing this?)- clip-on holster is bulky, but doesn't have to be used- adds some weight to the iPhone, but the trade off is a good feel and sense of protection - well worth itRecommendations:- would be nice to see if there is a way to overcome the "stretch" factor for the rubberized outer covering - in fact, I just ordered another one from Amazon to replace the previous one- see if you can tighten up the specs a bit to prevent the dust "creep" that is happening with both of the iPhones that I have in this case currently - not a major issue, but a bit annoying to have to tear it apart and clean it every few monthsOverall, for the price currently being charged and the value derived, I would highly recommend this to anyone.  Now if price is not a concern, you might consider another alternative such as the Lifeproof case (which I haven't tried yet, but looks like it has most all of the same features and adds water/dust proof, but also lacks some of the accessories as of this writing).  Of all of the Defender cases that I have, this is by far my favorite and is the standard by which most other cases are judged by me.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: I'm pretty sure nothing can hurt my Iphone now.  This thing is pretty secure. the phone is completely encased with thick plastic all around and has a built in screen protector. reviewText: A colleague of mine bought a slim, handsome case for his new iPhone and upon dropping it for the first time, cracked the phone.The Otterbox is not a slim, stylish case. It is black, rubberized armor for your iPhone. You may damage the case--you may drop it on concrete in the parking lot or down the stairs--but your iPhone will remain intact and free from damage.So the question is, do you want the iPhone because it's slim and compact, or do you want to protect and therefore keep it for years of use?  The choice is yours!Two more things:  I've read in other reviews where the case obscures the headphone/wired headset jack. The truth is it covers it but is easily flipped over for access to the jack. The Otterbox also comes with a very sturdy belt clip case, much like a Blackberry case, if you use that sort of thing.My one wish, and this is no gripe with the case, is that devices such as iHome alarm clocks and others that let you play music and charge the phone would work with a phone case on, but alas they do not.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: I needed another case since my old defender got cracked and the silicon was messed up so I ordered the black on white case. After reading the negative review, I wasn't worried about how it would hold up but whether or not I would get sent a fake one. The things I checked were:*Packaging - People said that they sometimes got theirs in a zip lock bag. Mine came in retail packaging*Differences in design - most fakes usually come with a linear thing that goes down the silicon. Mine didn't. I also looked at the Otter Box logos on the back and inside the case. They matched up and I was convinced it was legit.Overall, I know how well this case can protect since my phone is practically brand new and it's been in the defender for almost 2 years. I do want to note that the proximity sensor doesn't work during calls. I thought this was only an issue for the white iphone but this is not the case since mine is black. I did the sharpie trick but it didn't work and that irritated me because now theres an ugly mark I'm going to see every time I open up the case, but how often will that be? I don't know if this happened with my last defender, since I never paid attention to it and I'm not one of those people who puts their phones against their cheek. It's a good buy and cheap too! Well, cheaper than retail anyway.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: Once it's on your iPhone, it fits great, it looks great, it's functional -- but sitting there trying to figure out how to SEPARATE the components in order to install the @$#(* thing is enough to drive you nuts, and that's WHILE I had the Otter Box video on my computer screen.There are three clips that hold the back and front together, but the think is that the silicone strip or belt that runs around the outside needs to be removed FIRST. I wish they'd ship the thing in PIECES, that would be helpful!Anyway: once you've got the thing apart, try not to get any fingerprints on the inside of the clear plastic parts like I did. I haven't used it yet, I don't usually wear a belt so I don't have a good place to clip it to.I'm happy enough with this thing to be ordering a second one for my kid. reviewText: Getting an iPhone 4, I wanted to protect my investment. I love the rubber case because it really helps maintain a grip without fear of the smooth Apple surface slipping from your fingers.I give a thumbs up for making the interface port flap easier to work with.  Yes, it seems flimsy compared to prior designs, but it does it's chief job...keeping junk out.  The version for the 3/3GS was too thick and fussy to work with, so I see this as an improvement.I do give a thumbs down for the case not being as "thick" as the one for the 3/3GS.  That case was like a tank with thick plastic and rubber protecting the iPhone inside.  I can't say this case is less adequate for the task, but it certainly doesn't inspire the same confidence as the 3/3GS model does.That it comes with a belt-clip holster is always an added bonus.  Most people are happy to just get a "protective case" that clips on the back side and does nothing more.  This item shelters your phone from all sides.

reviewText: I have purchased 3 of these and recommended them to 5 other family members.  These cases are great and they protect your iPhone like no other case.  They come with a hard plastic case with a felt inner liner to protect your iPhone and it has a built in screen protector that resists finger prints and bubbles (You will have to clean it).  It then has a textured silicon rubber skin exterior that helps you grip the device and protect it from falls, yes they do happen!  The phone and case then snaps into the belt holster either face-in (max protection) or face-out for viewing.  The holster clips on your belt and will also rotate.  In addition you can lock the belt clip open and use it as a stand to set your phone on a table or airline tray to watch videos.  I liked the Zircon blue color and my wife got a pink one.I accidently dropped my iPhone onto a 2 inch square steel rod about 3  feet down and my heart stopped.  Not a scratch and it still worked perfectly.  Since the iPhone 4 is made of hardened glass on the front and back I am sure that it would have cracked, broken or chipped without the case.  Thank you Otterbox!Just a warning is that the case does make your phone bigger and it probably will not plug into your stand charger or player/speaker system.  Cable chargers work fine.  You don't get to see the beauty of your fantastic designed iPhone but you will keep it from being damaged from your human mistakes.By the way, Otterbox has the best customer service available.  My wife's silicon outside cover didn't fit right and they immediately replaced it and shipped it no charge.  They are the best!
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: The OtterBox brand has been around for long enough to be well-established. If you're just now getting with the program, like me, OtterBox is a tough case for your iPhone. Getting one is simply an experience in itself. I've had experience with other cases and this doesn't come close to comparison.With the OtterBox, there's actually two cases. One is hard and comes with clear window for the touchscreen, which means there's no need for a screen protector. The second case is an outer soft cushion that's textured for better grip. It also protects the ports with flaps that sort of snap into place. Sounds weird since this is a soft texture, but that's what it feels like.Inside the box--actually printed on the inside, are assembling instructions that are easy to follow, but it's a no-brainer putting this together. Common sense will pretty much guide you through.After putting on the soft case, I noticed the hole of the earphone didn't line up. I thought this was a flaw until I visited their website. Here's what was posted:  "Actually, the port cover is correct. The hole in the port cover is intended to leave open access for the noise-cancelling mic. To use headphones you need to open this port cover. This cover prevents dust and dirt from entering the device when the headphone jack is not in use."If you've never used an OtterBox, YouTube has so many bizarre demonstrations of iPhone users dropping their devices off houses, apartment complexes and buildings. One person even drop-kicked their iPhone a couple of times and the OtterBox held up and also defended the phone. I have no intention of doing anything that extreme. I just wanted a heavy-duty cover with a good clip--which is included--so that I can listen to music during exercising. Since I live in a humid climate where it rains a lot, I also needed something to protect the iPhone. The OtterBox case is that and more.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: The website and I think even the amazon description says it does not fit the white iphone. SOme think this is b/c of rumors the white phone is thicker but it is actually potential interference with the proximity sensor. Regardless, I have an ATT white iphone 4 and have been using this case for a few weeks with no issues related to fit or the proximity sensor. Symptoms of problems with this relate to making phone calls and the screen wither not shutting off when placed to your ear or not re-awakening when you pull it away from your face- I have had this with my last phone and a different case so know what to look for and there is definitely no issue with that.Aside from that I have to agree with many of the other reviews about the quality of this case compared to the 3Gs Defender case.  I have had 3 iphones and 3 defender cases and although there are some improvements with this one (specifically the dock connector space will accomodate more sizes/shpaes of OEM connectors. The silicone covering is not as picket friendly as the last defender case and feels thinner and more prose to losing its shape or all out ripping. When you put it on it feels a little like you are molding clay to fit the plastic case- you have to smoosh it into every seam. the dock cover wanted to pop off too easily on the first one I got (not on amazon) but I returned it and the second one seems to fit a little better. I also feel there are more openings in this case leaving it vulnerable to wet environments. Otterbox does not claim it is water proof or even water resistant I don't think but they actually called the first one splash proof or something and then stepped back from that with the 2nd one and now this one feels even less so. I take an use it out on a boat and there were times I had a puddle of water sitting on the screen of the 3GS case - I never worried about it. I do not feel anywhere near as comfortable with this one. I think the silicone issue was an effort to make it less bulky and it is but I wish they offered the thicker one for the customers who really want that much protection.I also hate the hole at the top for  the facetime mic. Given that this feature is not used all that often would it be a big deal to have to remove a cover when you were using facetime? I understand that the camera can no longer be covered b/c of the flash but I would prefer a less holey case. I have to conclude that this is likely still the best case on the market and I am relieved it does fit the white iphone but it is dissapointing. They screwed up their commuter case too but I will leave that for another review!p.s. there are lots of white cases out there that cause a haze over photos when the flash is used and I am happy to say that is NOT an issue with this case so hats off for that at least!

reviewText: After going for a run in the rain I was horrified that my iPhone 4 got pretty wet despite staying in the front pocket of my waterproof pants. I had another silicone case on it and sadly the screen (which was left entirely exposed) got super wet. Luckily for me the iPhone was still working just fine, but I got a little spooked by the experience.I decided I wanted a case with maximum protection and I've known for a while about the Defender series from Otterbox, so I gave it a shot.I've had the case on my iPhone 4 for a week now. Here are my observations:* The case offers excellent protection for you iPhone. Unlike most cases that only cover the back of your iPhone, the Defender covers the front and has a built-in screen protector. Suffice to say protection wise you are all but set with this case.* The built-in screen protector is a really nice touch. It does not "oil-slick" or create any ugly bumps. It also causes you not to lose any touch responsiveness. (So important!)* The case comes with a belt clip which is made of nice plastic. I'm not a cell-phone-belt-clip kinda guy, but if you are, you'll be happy here.* Putting on the case was pretty simple (there is a video on YouTube by Otterbox in case you need help). However taking off the case is another story entirely. You need to lift up and then pull apart a notch on the top of the hard shell to remove the case. I had to learn this via a user submitted YouTube video. Otterbox should have a "how to remove your case" video too.* The case adds weight and bulk to your iPhone. However it's much less than I expected.* The case is a dust magnet. The dust that gets on the silicone isn't a big deal in my opinion, however it will be unsightly on your screen protector (especially corners and edges) and on the two covered holes on the front of the case and the two open holes on the back (camera and flash). This isn't a huge deal however it does bother me to look at my case after only a week and see dust gathering in places where it didn't before I used the Defender.* The screen protector is great (as I said before) however be aware that all screen protectors take a way from the clarity of your glass screen. Essentially your screen goes from bright and clear sans protector to a bit grainy with it on. It doesn't really bother me however it is noticeable.* The volume and home button is super responsive with the case because Otterbox smartly included little bumps on the silicone case so when you press those buttons with the case on it works well.* The cut out hole on the back of the case is excellent for when you want to pull your iPhone out of your pocket (just put your thumb in that hole) or when you are holding the phone to your ear and you can nicely place your index finger on that spot.So is this my new everyday case? I've decided no. Instead I will just use it when the weather is bad, I'm off to the beach, or I'm going to be in a social setting where I am worried others might use my iPhone to snap photos, etc. I'm going to revert back to my old silicone case because I miss the clarity of using the screen without a screen protector plus it won't collect dust in those little spots as the Defender did. But I'm still glad I have the option to use the Defender when needed.The iPhone 4 is a slippery piece of hardware (hello all-glass back/front) and I highly recommend a case in general. That flat backing doesn't help when gripping the phone and placing it near your ear. The Defender is an excellent choice in that it truly protects your iPhone unlike other cases that offer much less peace of mind. However in the end you'll have to determine how much protection you think you'll need and if you are willing to live with additional bulk and weight added to your iPhone.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: I gave in to pressure and bought iPhones, and must admit I'm starting to like the thing...However, since the first iPhone came out over four years ago, I've seen the effects of dropping the phone.  I've seen the screens cracked and the back of the phones shattering, and did not want to deal with those issues, even with insurance.This case didn't seem like it would be very protective when it is in three parts, but when assembled around the phone, it creates a barrier that protects the phone better than any other case I've seen on the market.  I see people walking around with phones with no cases and others with only a rubber case wrapped around the phone, which would not protect the phone in a serious fall...  I've dropped my phone several times on parking lots, and from a three foot fall onto concrete or asphalt, I've had no damage after taking the case off the phone.  Incredibly, even the case doesn't show the wear from being dropped.This case goes on the phone in three parts, the first two being a plastic case that when assembled around the phone is extremely rigid, and has some padding inside the case.  The third part is the rubber shield, which fits around the plastic case, and acts as a bumper if the phone is dropped, as well as a non-slip surface when holding the phone or setting it down.These cases sell for $50 at most retail stores, but Amazon comes in at $20 - $30 for the case, which is not cheap, but will pay for itself in protecting the phone.  Even at $50 I'd recommend buying the case, but at half that cost, it's a no brainer...

reviewText: I have the iPhone 4s and read that this case worked great for it despite it being marketed as the iPhone 4 case.  I just wanted to leave my experience for use with the 4s.  It protects and fits great.  I only have 2 small issues. One is that you have to lift the flap to access the earphone port.  My second issue is that I've also found that the touch screen is not as sensitive to touch.  Before I put my Otterbox on, I had a Zagg Invisishield on my screen.  With that on the screen, the Otterbox touch screen worked great and registered every little keystroke.  But it would press onto the inside of the Otter screen and cause a splotchy mark that limited my visual.  I had to remove my Zagg screen shield to get rid of the weird sheen and then I noticed the touch pad wasn't working so great.  I hope this helps anyone deciding on the Defender case.  Overall, I'm pretty happy with it as I tend to drop my phone more often than I'd like to admit and this will protect it against breakage.

reviewText: Good:  Strong large case.  Seems to protect everything. Easier to hold the phone now with the rubbery grip and larger size.  Read the tips below and you will not have any problems.Bad:  Large size(bad for some, maybe necessary to protect the Iphone.  This case is primarily designed to protect and allow for drops).Needs modifying:Needed to use a little baby powder between the screen cover and iphone. (a tip I picked up on the web); this removes the air bubbles that get trapped between the phone and clear plastic cover.Removed the small clear plastic cover on the inside top of the case which covers the forward camera and sensors. This was easy to do.  The face sensor turns the screen off when you hold the phone to your ear. It is blocked by this plastic, allowing your face to hit keys, like the mute button, while you are on the phone.  The cover interferes with this, so it had to go. The depth of the case still protects the sensor just fine.  Your brightness sensor might also be affected by this case.The case is somewhat difficult to put together and take apart. Make sure to stretch the rubber and pull towards you to get it to grab the edges of the front of the screen.  The rubber can grip your pocket while taking it out. On the other hand, its harder for it to fall out of your pocket too.(The bare Iphone seems to be designed to slip away from anything, hands and pockets).Note: the tiny hole at the top is for the noise cancelling mic, not for the audio plug.  You need to open the flap to plug in the audio connecter.  This is as designed to keep dirt out of the hole. (I read this on the company's site)I really like this case. Once its together and modified and clean, you should not have to take it apart for a long time.  Follow the above advice, clean the screen well before installing the case and you will like it a lot.  Feels like I can drop this on concrete and not have any problems.This is not a slim case, nor is it elegant.  It may save you some money in the long run from drops.

reviewText: The Otterbox Universal Defender case for the Iphone 4 has proven to me time and time again that it is the ultimate protection for the Iphone 4.  If you value your device this is the way to go.  This is my second purchase of such a case and that should speak volumes. My previous case lasted almost two years before I finally decided to replace it. Ultimately, the phone has outlasted the case.  I am one who constantly drops my phone due to the fact that I am constantly on the go and in and out of my vehicle all day long.The three piece design, which includes a screen protector provides constant protection of the face of the phone as well as the vulnerable corners of your device.  While the only draw-back might only be the rugged silicone which wraps around the two-piece plastic case design, it certainly provides protection and grip to the phone.  The draw-back being that it does not allow your phone to slide in and out of your pockets as easily as one would hope.The flaps that cover the phone's usable components such as the charging pins, on and off button, and earphone jack have a tendency to flip open at times, but they still offer a certain level of protection regardless.  While the phone offers a little more bulk to the device, I would much rather have the bulk than to have a damaged phone.When I wear this case out, I am certain that I will purchase another.

reviewText: I've tried several iPhone cases and I've found the Otterbox Defender case gives the best protection for your iPhone. The soft rubber shell goes on the outside making for a non-slip gring.The problem I have found with their solid black cases is that the soft rubber outer shell is so soft it doesn't stay on perfectly. reviewText: It's easy to put this case together, and according to all the countless YouTube videos, I'm sure I could drop the thing off a building and my iPhone would be fine.However, this protection comes at a price. The plastic screen protector dulls the otherwise vibrant colors of the iPhone 4; luckily it is only held on with a bit of glue and it was easy to remove (just push it out when the case is dismantled).The other problem is that the outer silicon layer keeps coming loose. It sits properly until you try to pull it out of your pocket, at which point the silicon layer doesn't sit right anymore, and you have to re-set it. It's not a huge deal but it is a constant small annoyance.Also, one reason I bought this case was because it comes with a belt clip. However, the belt clip part is SO bulky, I never wear it. It makes walking around, sitting down and standing up, uncomfortable. Also, a belt clip should make my iPhone instantly accessible - that's why I want one - but this clip makes it very difficult to remove the iPhone with just one hand. It ends up being an awkward two-handed affair that, frankly, renders moot the benefits of a belt clip.Finally, this thing is VERY grippy, which is good for holding onto the phone but rather awful for getting it out your pocket. I have literally turned pockets inside out when attempting to remove the phone -- and when I finally do get it out, there is often a credit card stuck to the back because it is so grippy!Overall, it's fine at the reduced price that Amazon charges, and it definitely provides protection, but I think there are probably other cases out there that provide almost as much protection while not having the same problems as this one.
title: OtterBox Universal Defender Case for iPhone 4 (Black Silicone & Black Plastic)

reviewText: Original one star review: I just put this case on my phone, replacing a similar Otter case purchased in March that got really messy.  It protected my phone while I painted and remodeled our house.Despite living on my tool belt for month and suffering several falls, this case was spattered with paint, but otherwise functioning perfectly.I put the new, replacement Otter case and iPhone into my purse with the same stuff as had been there since March.Now the brand new clean screen protector part of the new case has a large, deep scratch.  I have to assume that the new case has a fragile, easily scratch-able screen protector.  I'm so disappointed with this product.Updated five star review: called the manufacturer and they shipped me a replacement case.  They couldn't have been nicer or more cooperative. I couldn't have an Iphone without a case like this to protect it, so I am really delighted to have one minus the big scratch on the screen protector.  I'll flip the face of the phone into the case when it has to go into my purse from now on, protecting the screen protector.

reviewText: I have 3 of these cases for myself and my 2 daughters.  I did alot of research, and this is the perfect compromise between protection, form factor and functionality.It is NOT a big, bulky, tank like case that offers absolute maximum protection, so if that is what you are looking for, this is not your case.  If you are looking for something that basically fits your Ipod like a glove, maintaining it's sleek form factor, while offering excellent (but not maximum) protection, this is your case.  All 3 of us have dropped our Ipods at one time or another, and these cases have performed well.  The Ipods, and the cases, were not damaged.If you have dockable music players, this case is almost mandatory.  The bottom 1/2 of the case slides off easily, allowing your Ipod to be docked.  Other cases, even good cases by Otterbox (i.e. the Defender series) do not have this functionality.  You have to remove the Ipod from the case to dock.  Easier said than done, especially if you dock your Ipod frequently.One caveat.  Don't bother with the screen protector.  It may work well if you put it on and never take the bottom half of the case off to dock your Ipod, but if you do, then the constant sliding of the lower part of the case against the screen protector will take its toll.  I say this from experience.  I really don't think the screen protector offers much in the way of added protection anyway, so I am not the least bit concerned about not having it on.Overall, I highly recommend this case.  I like it so much, that one of the reasons I am holding off on upgrading my Ipod to 5th generation, is because Otterbox has not made a Reflex case yet, and I don't see a suitable alternative from anyone else.  I'm not going to spend $300+ on a new Ipod and not have a decent case to put it in.
title: Otterbox Reflex Series Case for iPod touch 4G - Hot Pink/Black

reviewText: I got this case for my thunderbolt because I wanted maximum protection for my phone.  Installation was easy (snap on hard plastic case, and then put rubber bumper around it) and it certainly does the job.While it does make my phone thicker, I'd hardly say it makes it impossibly thick to fit in a pair of pants.  However, the rubber is pretty grippy, and if you're wearing any sort of tight-ish pants, it will take a bit of extra elbow grease to get the phone out.  However, they include a belt holster that allows the phone to be locked in to it...if that's your style.My problem with the case is that it has a built in screen protector.  it does not sit totally flush with the screen, and as such, dirt, dust, and grime have gotten under it. reviewText: I have big, clumsy hands. It's a miracle that my Incredible 2 did not break after dropping it several times during the first few weeks with the flimsy rubber case I got from Verizon. After my last scare, I got on to Amazon to order this case. I had previously owned an original Motorola Droid and had an Otterbox Commuter case. I really didn't like that case too much, particularly the smooth hard plastic back (in fact the entire exterior of that case was smooth, hard plastic). On this case, the *interior* is hard plastic and the exterior is a soft rubber that has a sort of diamond-patterned tread on it. It feels *great* in the hand and completely gives me the feeling that if I drop it, it will survive. I also like how it has a plastic cover for the screen. I left my regular screen protector below it, but this plastic cover just gives one more layer of protection. To sum up, I'd recommend this case to anyone clumsy like me. At $30 on Amazon it's a great deal compared to the list price of $50. It definitely adds some bulk to the phone, but I like it - with my big hands it actually feels better, and the added heft makes me feel like I have my OG Droid in my hand again!
title: OtterBox Defender Series for Droid Incredible 2 by HTC

reviewText: This case has come in handy since I am a "phone dropper" and thus far it's kept my phone quite protected. reviewText: I had ordered the OtterBox Defender Series but it was too bulky, the sides (around the display) were way too high (made for difficulty accessing the pull down menu) and I did not really like the built-in clear screen protector that was over it.  That said, the holster was great, the protection was awesome and if I worked in Construction or some other rough-and-tumble trade, that would have been the perfect option.So I sent that back and ordered the Commuter Series.  I like it!  Only I am giving it 4 stars because I would have loved it if there were a holster or belt-clip with it.  For some reason, I hate putting my phone in my pocket or purse and prefer to have it somewhere that it is always accessible and this happens to be my belt or hooked on my pocket.  And, this way the phone does not collect dust and "pocket fuzz" (and the Commuter Series does tend to collect it quite well on the silicone cover). But, alas, the holster I purchased (also through Amazon) will not fit the phone with this case on it.That said, the case has a lot of plusses!!!  The bulk (from the Defender Series) is considerably less.  The sides around the display are not high and this makes everything accessible.  The protection is amazing.  I am not a phone dropper but I love to have a nice phone.  The OtterBox Commuter Series, in my opinion is classy and sleek and makes for a professional phone. I do kind of wish it came in other colors (such as royal blue) but I have not found that yet.The self-adhesive screen cover is great.  It comes with a OtterBox installation card (so you don't have to use your credit card - lol!) and when I put it on, following the installation instructions, it was simple and there are no bubbles.  It also comes with a little screen cleaning cloth which is cute.Yes, it does collect finger-prints but I think, in time, as my other self-adhesive screen covers did, this dies down after using it for a while, and believe-you-me, I'd rather have that than a scratched, messed-up screen. (My last screen protector saved me from a serious scratch when I was working on the construction of my house roof, the scratch only made it through the screen-protector and could have been BAD; all the way through the screen).  Also, I use my Friendly Swede styluses (also highly recommended) a lot so this cuts down on the finger prints.The price was great!  The price listed on the box was $34.00 and I believe I got this, with shipping, for around $10.00.  What a bargain!Anyhow, I am looking for a holster that works for this (and will fit my phone with this case) so if anyone knows of something like that, please let me know.Otherwise, I highly recommend this case!
title: OtterBox Commuter-Series Case for Samsung Droid Charge (Black)

reviewText: I was skeptical because of the other reviews, but this case is great. It's easy to install and very strong. The belt clip is also nice because the case is so bulky which makes it difficult to get in and out of you pocket.

reviewText: Okay, to start, I work around and in the water, in the rain, snow, weather, etc.  I've had an Otterbox on my Blackberry 8350i, my now retired Centro, and now on my Samsung Charge.  I schlep around the Blackberry and the Charge together on the same belt in Otterbox cases.  So this is where I'm coming from.This case is large, as someone else has written.  And no duh on that.  The damned phone is huge, so the case will make it that much bigger.  Deal with it!The Otterbox case fits very well onto the Charge, and the quality of the plastic and neoprene castings is excellent.  The clear plastic screen protector is integral to the plastic front cover of the case and it has no negative impact upon the functionality of the Charge's touch screen.  The belt-clip holster for the case is of the snap-in variety, not a true holster like on the 8350i or Centro.  For the uninitiated, what this means is that there's a little tab that holds the Charge in the holster and this tab must be lightly depressed in order to extract the phone from the holster.  This tab is pretty prominent in the glamor shots of the case.  While I'm quite suspicious of this design, so far there's been no problem with the Charge popping out (although I've had the case only about 24-hours).  The belt clip on the holster allows for the holster to be rotated in 15-degree increments as is usual for the Otterbox Defender cases I'm familiar with.  There are covers for all the ports (HDMI, micro-USB, and headphone jack) and these are all well placed and seal well.  There is enough room to plug my rather sizable after-market micro-USB charge/data cable into the USB port which surprised me after reading someone else's review complaining of the need to take the Charge out of the case to charge the battery.  The volume and power buttons are all very well placed and responsive.  As compared with the cheap plastic case I had before, these buttons are all 500% more responsive and much easier to locate tactily because of the bump-outs in the neoprene.So, with all the above why did I only give this case 4-stars?  First off, I'm a hard grader.  Secondly, I'm not impressed at how well the case seals the Charge.  There is *NO* cover to the rear facing camera, the ear piece, or the rear speaker!  I didn't look really closely but there may also be no cover to the front-facing camera or the proximity sensor.  Having experienced the 8350i and Centro Otterbox cases with some type of white cover (water absorbing?) on the speakers and ear pieces of these phones I'm quite disappointed.  I envision being out in the rain and having one single rain drop hit the ear piece and fry the phone.  I consider this a big design flaw.  Thirdly (you are still counting, right) the neoprene over the four hard-buttons along the bottom of the phone is black ("no kidding", right?)  But this neoprene has very little for the non Braille-readers to distinguish these four buttons from one another.  So where I used to be able to grab the Charge in the dark, find the power button on the side, and then proceed visually, now I still need to fumble around to hit the four hard buttons (Menu, Home, Back, and Search).  If the neoprene were *clear* or *translucent* then this wouldn't be a problem.  Also, I find that unlike the volume and power buttons on the sides, the four buttons along the bottom take a lot of force to activate.  I attribute this to the neoprene.  And fourthly the belt clip on the holster seems *less* beefy than on the Defender case for my other two phones.  In my experience the belt clip is the weak link on these Defender cases and I wouldn't have expected that the Charge's case would be *less* strong.  But, time will tell...Well, that's about it.  I'll try to update this review in about a month.  I hope it helps people decide what they will be doing.### UPDATE 10jul2012 ###The above review was from Aug2011, now it's about a year later.I still have the phone, I still have the case.  I think I'd probably give it 3.5 stars now.  About 8-months into having the case the clip for the holster broke on my belt (remember I said the belt clip was the weak link on these cases?)  Well, Otterbox honored the warranty and sent me a whole new case (cover and holster) when I submitted a claim.  This warranty resolution was easy and and part of the reason the case doesn't get fewer stars.Shortly before this, however, the phone fell out of the holster while I was near the water.  Long story short, the phone was submerged in about 6-inches of water for 5-minutes.  I'm pretty sure the Otterbox case on the phone helped a lot to keep out the water (the red tattle tale on the battery is barely turned) and the phone is still, knock wood, working.  But, to avoid this problem in the future, I now have the phone in a Nite Ize caseNite Ize Clip Case Cargo Magnet Tall - 1 Pack - Bulk Packaging - Black.  The Nite Ize case only makes the phone on my belt a hair bigger than the holster from Otterbox, and I've never had a problem with a Nite Ize clip or case.So, there you go; hybrid solution.  Hope this helps you!

reviewText: This is an awesome product; there is no question about it.  If I were in construction or did a lot of outdoorsy work or what-have-you, this would have worked well. I returned it and I may get the Commuter series, still thinking about that.A few things I didn't totally like about this were that the sides were too high (I would try to grab my pull-down/information bar) and I would have to try a few times because my finger didn't quite fit; it was too bulky; and the built in screen was a little too dark. Also, not that it matters much, because I have the controls memorized, if you want the lights on your menu, home, back and search buttons to show, this covers that completely and you cannot see them in the dark.  Not an issue for me because they are always in the same place and I do not have to see them.That said, the phone was PROTECTED.  There was no question that my phone would be fine if I dropped it.  But, since I am not really a phone dropper, it was a little too much.So, if you are a phone dropper, don't mind bulk and want your phone PROTECTED, this is a great product!

reviewText: I cannot sing the praises for OtterBox cases loud or long enough.  I have literally dropped my phone out of a moving car and nothing happened to it or to the OtterBox other than maybe a few scratches.  I drive a bus for Scouts and my phone has slid off of the dash out onto the ground in parking lots several times.  After over two years of using this OtterBox with my Droid X2, I sold both to someone else to offset the cost of my upgrade.  The buyer could not believe that the phone had zero wear marks on it.  They were also amazed at the small scratches on the OtterBox considering the abuse it had taken.  While this type of OtterBox is not waterproof, this phone had been dropped in the river for about 2 seconds and the moisture sensor in the phone was unable to tell.  Yes, they do protect against some water exposure, but they are not rated for submersion in water, yet it protected my phone in that instance.

reviewText: This case is perfect for protecting my phone while allowing me to have access to the screen and buttons. I am not concerned about dropping my phone now as the silicon is fairly thick and appears to offer some shock absorption (not that I will be testing this anytime soon).Getting this case on is easy. Getting it off to clean the phone and/or change the battery is easy too. I like the easy on / off with the great protection. I have not used the screen saver that came with this as I am using another kind of screen saver sold by another seller ... so I cannot speak to the ease of applying the screen saver that came with this case.My only complaint, is that the silicon is a lint/dust magnet. UGH. I'm constantly cleaning off lint and dust. I wish Otterbox would have found a way to have the plastic wrap around the silicon so I would not have to deal with a dirty looking phone. BUT ... a dirty looking phone is tolerable when compared to the protection this case offers.Over all, a good buy and good value for your money. Do not hesitate to buy this.

reviewText: Pros:-Very protective case.-Works with the Evo V from Virgin Mobile(Reason why I bought this case)-Rubber grips everything and doesnt slip out of hands easily. The inner plastic case has a groove on the outer side that the rubber locks into keeping it from coming off.-Front built in plastic for screen doesnt reduce touch response in screen-Plastic covers over camera lenses keep lenses from getting scratches and doesnt seem to alter the picture quality from what I can tell.-Inner half of case has foam inside keeping the phone from hitting the plastic, And the thin part of plastic at the top above the earpiece does seem like its easy to break, But havent broken it myself yet even with a few drops under my belt.-Rubber flaps to cover all the ports and switches is definitely nice.-Buttons seem to be easier to press with fingers but dont activate in pocket easily.-Clip on holster works great as a prop to hold the phone standing up.Cons:-Outer lip around the screen is HUGE. I have problems trying to type P and Q and backspace with my huge fingers, but definitely will protect the screen if dropped.-Case takes some fiddling to get on/off, But after a few times of taking it off and putting it back on, It goes on easy and fast.-I have noticed a slight discoloration from the plastic on the screen. It is nothing major but after looking at the screen in and out of the case i can see a slight difference. it seems to take some of the brightness away.-Easily doubles the thickness of the phone, Which may be a bad thing to some people.Definitely a must have case if your out working all the time, where your phone can be dropped or bumped into constantly. This case WILL protect your Evo 3D/V.
title: OtterBox HTC EVO 3D Defender Series Case - 1 Pack - Case - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: I had this case once before, and paid a pretty hefty price for it from Verizon. I ended up giving it away because:It's ugly.It's heavy.I can't use ANY of the Moto docks with it.I started using the extended battery.I am envious of the Razr's diet-skinny form-factor as it is (WHY did I upgrade so soon?!)....and then I dropped my phone.The case I replaced my Otterbox with (see my other reviews for the exact case) was more stylish, allowed the use of all my pricey accessories, and accommodated the massive extended battery. It also allowed some pretty nasty damage to the face of my phone, and while removing it just now I discovered that the stupid case cracked! While switching it, I saw a LOOONG crack down the back of the holster part. No matter how slowly/carefully I moved, the crack expanded and eventually the case split in half. I've had it less than a week! Good that I was removing it in order to switch to Otterbox anyway; bad that the store probably won't take it back now.Needless to say, I will never leave Otterbox again! While I'm galloping around the city, I need to ensure that my phone is safe. I'll just carry a power pack with me and forego the extended battery. As for the dock, there are dock/webtop launcher apps for the Bionic, and the lock-open belt clip keeps it at a good viewing angle.My phone may look like a piece of military hardware, but I'll take brawn over beauty in this case.
title: Otterbox Defender Series Hybrid Case and Holster for Motorola Droid Bionic - 1 Pack - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: I am extremely pleased with this Otterbox case that I received today (10/26/2011) for my new Droid Bionic smartphone and will certainly be considering this same case manufacturer when purchasing new phones in the future.The Otterbox replaces a very nice flexible TPU case that I had initially purchased here on Amazon.com.This case simply provides much more serious protection. It's certainly worth spending approximately $30.00 now to avoid having to replace a potentially damaged phone in the future ($699.00 retail!) to say nothing of the fact that regularly using this case will certainly increase the trade-in/resale value of the phone kept therein when it's time to get a new phone.I also really like the built-in screen protector. There's no need to bother with often difficult to apply stand-alone screen protectors.I have noticed several complaints about the size of the case in reviews posted here, namely that it makes this already large phone even larger.Personally, I don't find the increased bulk of the phone (especially the thickness) while in the Otterbox to be very bothersome. The Droid Bionic is already a big phone from the get go and will remain so no matter what you do.If your employment/work situation allows you to wear cargo pants on a regular basis, I find that this is the best way to always readily have this phone at your side. It fits perfectly and unobtrusively into the right cargo pocket of my pants and I can avoid using the included belt holster/clamp.

reviewText: This is the 5th Defender case that I have purchased.  No, I'm not insane but I just kept trying to find one that would work out for me. I've had the blue, red, black, white and lavender.The problem is that when you have a black car interior, black car seat covers and a black purse it is real easy to give yourself a coronary every time you can't find your Iphone - as I have. And I refuse to give up the Defender model since it is practically indestructable.This case is outstanding. The back has a lovely light brown to dark brown woodsy picture that has bright orange higlights around it. The front is bright orange surrounded by black. I cannot misplace it. And it isn't an obnoxious orange either. Unfortunately I am not a "pink" or "yellow" person, so those colors were not options. But I needed something bright, classy and Defender. Problem solved.I also like the fact that Otter Box upgraded the material for this case. It is no longer that stretchy, rubbery fabric that could not slide into my pants pocket without sticking, therefore making it impossible to just grab the phone when you needed it.  The case has a solid feel to it which is entirely in keeping with the point of owning a Defender.Okay so I had to make adjustments and buy some extender cables to connect my Iphone to various speakers and docking stations in my home.  Big whoopee. Far less of an expense and inconvenience then replacing my Iphone.There is nothing out there that equals the Defender case and nowhere that equals Amazon's pricing and product protection.

reviewText: I like the Commuter Series Case better than theDefender Series Casefrom the same maker (OtterBox).  I find the Defender case too bulky, and the belt clip adds even more bulk, so much so that I took my phone out of the case and carried it unprotected.  The Commuter Case still adds bulk, but not as much.What I like:-two piece design (silicone + hard plastic) combines protection from direct impact and adds shock absorption in case of accidental drops-ports are covered by silicone flaps-easy to put on and take offWhat I don't like:-the silicone flap for the earpiece takes some effort to open; I use my phone to stream Pandora in my car, and I use aMonster 3.5mm audio cableto play music through the auxiliary input.-silicone wraps to the edges of the screen, and seems to disrupt touch function; sometimes the screen is not responsive (I am not using a screen protector)

reviewText: Fits very nicely. Personally, I wish it had more (or any) frontal protection. But I understand that the iPhone 4S's screen area is not that large to begin with. I don't want to argue with iPhone peeps. Spare me, please.For parents searching for a robust case (i.e., a case that will prevent damage to their child's iPhone), I would suggest investing in a so-called "LifeProof" case instead. LifeProof offers superior shock protection and something that no other iPhone case even considers -- water proof protection. To me, $45 for a LifeProof case (protecting an iPhone 4S) is a wise investment.Nevertheless, if you're a fairly careful person, or if you believe your kids are (good luck on that), the Otterbox will offer a fair amount of protection from shock.  But, if it gets wet, or if they strike the frontal area of the iPhone, then as they say, "have a nice day."LifeProof for kids.

reviewText: The case came quickly, nicely packaged in retail packaging. It fits well, looks like it will do a nice amount of protection since it states it will provide shock absorbance, dust resistant (doubt that, all rubber cases attract dust) and scratch resistant, but I've had past experiences with otterbox cases for my past smartphones and all the cases I've owned did a great job. The only bad thing about this case is the installment of the case itself. The iPhone pops right into the rubber layer easily, but squeezing the phone into the hardshell case is a pain in the ass. It tells you on the directions to put the phone in the bottom first, then pushing it into the top. I've tried both ways (putting the phone in from the top and bottom) and both were really difficult to do. Once I put it in the bottom way, trying to push down on the phone so I could squeeze the top half of the phone into the top of the hard case was a pain in the ass as well. You have to literally bend the hard case over the top of the phone and try to get the lock button and headphone cover buttons into the holes without pushing the rubber part off the phone, which will happen. reviewText: Most of the time my iPhone stays inside an Otterbox Defender case. However after trying out some other cases of other brands recently, that were all smaller more sleek cases, I decided to order a Otterbox Commuter case to try it out. It's significantly slimmer than the Defender, so I find it fits in my jeans pockets easier. Both the Defender and the Commuter use a 2 case design of one case fitted inside of another. The inner case of the Defender is hard plastic, with the outer case being soft rubber. The Commuter case is the opposite, having a soft case for the inside and a hard plastic case for the outside.Check to make certain when you order your case that you are getting it from Amazon themselves (might also say "Fulfilled by Amazon"), if you want to be certain you are not buying a knock off fake. While the majority of 3rd party sellers here are probably selling the genuine thing, a number of recent negative experiences many have people have posted about in their reviews sounds as though one of the sellers was shipping out fakes. Real Otterbox cases are tough, and last a long time. They don't fall apart within days. If you're buying this and able to get it shipped to you using Amazon Prime Delivery or Amazon Super Saver Delivery, you are getting it from Amazon themselves and should receive the genuine case.I ordered the Hot Pink and White case, and I find it's a little lighter in color than the online photo shows. Online the case looks almost fuschia, but in hand it's a lighter shade. It comes with a screen protector you can apply to your iPhone touch screen, and it goes on quite well. All the buttons on my phone are easily accessed when it's in this case, and there are snug gaskets over the charging port and earphone port to help your phone resist being damaged should it come in contact with water. It's a cute case and I think I'll be ordering a second one in another color. If you're looking for a little extra added protection, check out Otterbox Defender line.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for iPhone 4/4S  - Retail Packaging - Hot Pink/White

reviewText: I bought this for an iPhone 4 and it fits perfectly. I especially like the big cut out around the flash and camera. First case that does not distort flash pictures. Bubbles galore and I have put on other screen protectors and none of them got near the amount of bubbles this one did. It could have been user error but I am pretty careful with getting screen protectors on. Also it doesnt feel that good to hold. Now that is a trade off as I am sure the Otter protection comes from the rigid plastic. But the plastic doesn't feel particularly good. The inner rubber case does feel good where you can grip that though.Bottomline is a good trade off for adding minimal size yet providing what seems to be good protection. It also looks nice. I would just have another brand of screen protector on hand.Update: From the department of irony. A friend wanted to see the case when we were out walking. I took the case out in a swinging motion from my front parket and it fell forward onto hard concrete with a little forward momentum. Absoultely fine. So yes the hard rigid plastic doesn't feel great, but it does serve a purpose. And although less cushion feel then the defender series that gets you less added bulk and weight.

reviewText: I compared many different cases before deciding on this one... It's a perfect mix of the advantages of a hard and a soft case. reviewText: There are three parts to the case, a screen protector, a silicone full inner case and a hard shell partial outercase.The screen protecter is fine. They include a very small cloth to clean the screen and a small plastic card to burnish the protector to you phone screen. Some brands will include a tacky strip to aid in removing small dust particles before installing a cover but OtterBox does not.The inner silicone shell is designed with a full front bezel and peel-back covers for your charging port and headphone jack. In addition your on/off switch and volumn buttons are fully covered. There is a wide opening for the camera and Apple Logo in the both the silicone case and outer hard shell.I was never able to get the hard shell fully seated on both sides of the phone. There are cut-outs on the sides of the silicone case where tabs on the hard case seat into. I could get one tab in but never both. If you don't get both sides seated the silicone frame is not snug and that part of the hard case doesn't lay flat. After removing and reinstalling the case three times I decided I don't like it well enough to hassle with it anymore.There is one other thing I don't like about the case but that is a personal preference. I don't like hard cases, I find them slippery and miss the grip I get from a TPU or all silicone case. Despite the hard case not covering the sides of the phone completely it does cover the area where you hold the phone. If you already use and like hard cases it wouldn't bother you.

reviewText: I don't know if Otterbox will like this review, but I'm going to write it, anyway.I bought this case back in November. My only complaint is that I wish they did collegiate colors.I have grown somewhat clumsy in my dotage, and have dropped my iPhone 4S a couple of times. reviewText: My wife bought an OtterBox case for her iPhone 4 two years ago, and she loved it. I borrowed her phone occasionally, and I enjoyed it too. It was well designed with enough padding to protect the iPhone, and the rubberized grip made it easy to hold. But after a couple of years of use and abuse, the screen cover was badly scratched, and the case was dropped one time too many and cracked. So we shopped around for another OtterBox and chose the Commuter Series case. If anything, it's an improvement over the old OtterBox. It's noticeably smaller and less bulky, and it's easier to insert the iPhone 4.All of the necessary openings are there, including the camera flash. The case has rubberized grips in the areas where your hand holds the phone. Unlike some cases we've seen, the opening for the charger plug is big enough to allow the plug to be pushed in without any difficulty. And the case looks good.Overall, the OtterBox case is an attractive case that fits the iPhone 4 perfectly and provides excellent protection for the phone.
