reviewText: After having dozens of mobile phones over the past decade, I've tried many many cases; some plastic, others leather, some pouches.  I was turned on to Otterbox last year for my Blackberry, and it worked like a charm.  After upgrading to an iPhone 4S, I did research online, checked many reviews, tried out cases in the store, and found the Otterbox Commuter to be the right one for me.It has a silicon inner case, with a hard plastic outer case.  I prefer the hard plastic outer, since its easier to get in and out of my pocket.  The rubber corners are a great trick for impact protection, although you won't find me doing drop tests off the roof of my car to the asphalt below.The clear plastic screen that came with the case was easy to apply and I can't even tell its on.My DW has been using the Otterbox Defender on her phone, which is fine for a purse person, but since my phone goes in my pants pocket, this slimmer version works for me.  From a fashion perspective, it seems to project the original shape and form of the iPhone, instead of masking it behind a much larger case.The ports on this phone, from which I primarily use just the charger, are easy to access and seem to get gunk like lint out of the connector.  I see myself keeping this case for the lifetime of my phone.Overall, I'm completely pleased.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for iPhone 4/4S  - Retail Packaging - Hot Pink/White

reviewText: I love this case. It might not be the slimmest one around, nor the most glamorous looking but if you're a klutz, like me, it is WORTH IT! I am tall and therefore the height I drop it from is significant enough to do serious damage to the phone without a case or a flimsier case. I can attest to this because after almost two years of ownership, it has developed a small crack (the case, not the phone!) from all the dropping.I can fit it into my back pocket, it's not insanely huge and the silicone allows it to be grippier and prevent it from sliding all over smooth surfaces. It also increases the shock absorption and distribution when you drop it. A hard case can crack on impact and ruin your phone, a soft one might not be protection enough, this has both things.One thing that was kind of annoying, but something I anticipated after watching a review on youtube about this case, is that the silicone flap that over the charge port doesn't close all the way and the fact that the plastic portion might have a slightly imperfect fit over the silicone. You will get over this very quickly, it is not bothersome enough to interfere with anything. I'm pretty OCD about this stuff and I don't even notice it anymore.It is easy to take the phone in and out of the case and while for the most part your phone will be left with no marks, I DID end up having slight marks on the metal band around the phone where the volume and power buttons are. This is part of normal wear and tear, I'm not too concerned.I've dropped my phone off tables, couches, onto linoleum and cement and it's been just fine in this case. It's a worthy investment!
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for iPhone 4/4S  - Retail Packaging - Hot Pink/White

reviewText: Practically everyone has an otterbox for their iPhone, so I figured I'd give it a shot, in hopes of protecting my brand new phone 4S. When I first got this case I was really pleased with it. It fit very nicely and also looked nice. The first drop the plastic cracked at the top corner near the ear bud jack. It did protect the phone, but the case got loose on that top corner. Then I took it off to put a screen protector on and went to put it back on and you have to bend the plastic on the case a little to get it over the top rubber buttons covering the ear bud jack and on button. I did this and the whole upper third of the case snapped off. Now i put the case on successfully two or three other times before, but this time it snapped. And looking at it the plastic is very thin and cheap, probably why it cracked the first time I dropped it. It's a nice case that looks good, but the plastic is made way too cheaply. I'd rather just be careful with my phone and get a cheaper, less bulky bumper case.

reviewText: There are many Otter box's on the market, but this is probably one of the more cost effective for durability and function. The first inner layer is a robust silicone material which is durable and absorbs impact force along with the outer hard plastic layer that fits tightly. Most of the buttons: power, volume, headset input and the 30-pin plug are covered with the silicone. The camera and flash are given a wider window for easier cleaning for dust and debris and for picture clarity.  One poor note - the headphone 3.5mm plug is covered with the hole on the wrong side.The feel of the otter box is a little less slippery than most and definitely less bulky. It's really just a series of thin, but tough skins over your phone. There is no doubt that you can drop this and feel protected. The hard plastic outer sheath does not completely cover your iPhone like the others. Instead it has cut-outs to give just as much protection without excessive cove rage. It's simply better designed than previous models. Check out the price on other models and you'll see that this is on the lower end, but it doesn't skimp on quality.It also comes with a separate plastic clear cover along with a cleaning cloth and an installation card for those bubbles. YOUTUBE has some great videos of how to easily apply these covers without any bubbles or trouble.

reviewText: This case fits perfectly for those like myself who prefer to carry their iPhone in their pockets. I found the Defender case to be too thick and rubbery to permit one to easily insert and remove the iPhone from a shirt or pants pocket.There is a little design flaw with this case, hence the four star rating.  The plastic frame at the bottom of the case in front of the docking port is a little too thin.  After putting this in my pocket upside down for ten days, the plastic piece in front of the docking port split in half.  It is just too thin to be tugged on when removing the case (and iPhone) from a pocket.  The piece at the top of the cover spans the entire depth of the iPhone and doesn't seem to be prone to the same cracking.  So, as long as you pull the phone out of a pocket by the top of this case, you should be fine. reviewText: I really dig this case.  I originally considered an Otterbox Defender, but after comparing Defender and Commuter cases in the store, it looks like the Defender is about 1/8 to 3/16" bigger in every dimension, including thickness.  I wanted it protected, but I didn't want it in a bubble.  Also, my wife as a 3GS defender, and the rainbow effect on the screen was unattractive.So I instead went with the commuter and a Zagg invisibleSHIELD case-friendly screen protector.  Let's just talk about the Otterbox, though:The silicone portion is not the gummy/sticky kind.  It's got a bit of rigidity to it, fits the phone correctly, and covers the charge port and headphone jack that flip back for easy access.  The silent/ring switch is exposed.  Volume/power buttons are covered and there are tactile bumps on their place.  The cameras (front and back) and home button are all totally exposed, which you can see in the pictures.  Also, a cut-out for the Apple logo is (amusingly) on the back as well so you can tell it's not one of those evil Android devices I've read about (I kid).It would have been nice if the volume + and - buttons were labeled, but up is above down.  Not a huge deal.  I find the sleep/power button difficult to press.  There's a lot of "give" to that button that wasn't there previously.  I took the phone back out of the case to make sure I hadn't broken the button or something (I hadn't).  Again, you get used to it and it's not a huge deal.  You learn to apply more pressure and just press on one side of the button instead of the middle.The outer plastic part is slick.  Literally.  I picked the phone up for the first time and it immediately slipped out of my hands and landed on the carpeted floor.  Easy to slide in and out of your pocket, but I wish it had a soft-touch texture or something on the sides to make it more of a sure thing to hold.It's kind of like an inside-out Defender, as the soft silicone is on the inside and the hard plastic is on the outside.  The Defender, as noted above, is silicone on the outside.Still, despite all my complaints, I feel that my phone is protected and secure without feeling super-big and bulky.  It adds maybe 3mm in each dimension (height, width, depth).  If you need less thickness, I'd argue that you are not really protecting your phone.  If you want more thickness, the Defender is there for you.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for iPhone 4/4S  - Retail Packaging - Hot Pink/White

I've had the iFrogz Luxe Case, SwitchEasy CapsuleRebel M Menace Hybrid Case, and the Agent18 EcoShield Slider; my boyfriend also had the Otterbox Defender. Although each of these cases has perks, they all have drawbacks. I see many more pros with the Commuter Series from OtterBox than I have seen with any other iPhone case.For starters, the case is not bulky. When comparing it to the Defender, it wins hands down. The defender was awkward, bulky, and came with a holster clip that most girls won't use. Yes, this case would be handy if you were possibly in the construction business or if you really had a problem with dropping your phone, but for my needs, it didn't fit the bill. The Commuter case has a soft inside and a hard exterior, and they come in two different colors. This is both appealing and functional. The soft rubber casing allows for a no-slip grip and shock absorber and the hard shell keeps it from being too sticky. It is comfortable in the hand and provides the perfect balance of rubber to hard shell casing.I have dropped my phone a few times and the case has held up well, I can't see any wear on it. However, I have noticed that the soft shell (my color is yellow) does show discoloration. My hard shell is gray and you can see gray spots all throughout my yellow case. While this is not a big deal to me, it is just something I thought was worth mentioning. The Commuter Series in my opinion is superior to all other iPhone cases I have owned and, for $22, I think it's worthy of protecting the iPhone.

reviewText: I got the Commuter Otterbox case the day before my new iPhone 4s came. I've been debating for a few days on whether to get the Defender or the Commuter and after doing some research, I have decided to get the Commuter. The Defender is nice and seems super durable, but honestly I do not drop my phone that often and I am usually good with my phones, except for the occasional accidents I drop it every once in awhile. Also, the Defender is too bulky for my taste. One reason I got the iPhone was for its sleekness and the Defender would have ruined that feature for me. Since I do not want to compromise the sleekness of the phone, but also want great protection and knowing I take good care of my phones, the Commuter seemed like a good compromise.I will admit, putting on the case took a bit of effort first. You definitely have to "massage" the phone in the case a little since you are trying to make it line up with all the buttons/switches with the silicone case and the hard plastic cover. I am a perfectionist so when I saw that it was not lining up correctly, I kept fidgeting with it or took the phone out and tried it all over again. The trick is to slide the bottom part in first and then press on the top part to snap it into place (just like the video on otterbox.com) Before I was doing the opposite so I felt kind of dumb that I did not just look at the video first (haha). I can reach all of the buttons and switches fine and the flaps for the usb/charger connector and the headphones stay in place when I tuck them in. I can see some people with big fingers having trouble trying to switch the silence on/off, so keep that in mind if it is a big deal for you.I am not really sure why some reviewers said their case is not lining up correctly with their phone or the phone just does not fit with the case. I am looking at my phone with the case on and it is all secure and tight. I do not have the screen protector that came with it on, but I am sure I will need to soon so I do not regret it later.Like I said before, if you're clumsy, just get the Defender and you will not have to worry about your phone at all. If you are usually mindful with your phone, get the Commuter. I have not dropped my phone on concrete or anything like that yet (fingers crossed!) but if I do end up letting it happen, I will update!UPDATE!Ok, so I've had this case for a little over a month and my iPhone is still sitting pretty in it. I just dropped my phone today on tile when it slipped out of my hands because I was fiddling around with my handbag. Oh my god was I happy that nothing happened to my phone or case! I still say this case is a great buy, I mean 20 bucks to protect a $200 phone is pretty nice! I'm never letting this phone out of its case when I'm out. If it wasn't for this case, my phone will be shattered!Only negatives about this case is it takes a bit to get the phone to fit in the case, but you get used to it after a few times. Also, the lock/unlock button and volume buttons are somewhat hard to press down easily since the silicone covers them, but you get used to that as well.Happy hunting for the right case everyone!

reviewText: I am obsessed with babying my iPhone 4S, but didn't want an overly bulky case. After reading all the positive reviews and YouTube videos I decided on this one. Just don't think it's going to retain a sleek look. Was pretty happy with it until I realized it won't fit in a dock at all and the headphones won't go in. Found a few new annoyances. 1)The snap in protector for the charging slot won't stay in. 2) The lip on the side gets in the way in landscape mode when texting/gaming (kind of). 3) when I pulled off the case I realized that the silicone is letting in (and trapping) all kinds of dirt and grime. reviewText: I don't like cases for my iPhone.  I think they all take away from the sleek looks of an expensive phone.  I haven't  found any case  that improves the look of my phone.  But, it's difficult  to rationalize the feeling when you drop your phone and you know it's going to shatter.  In that brief moment in time, your pulse quickens and your BP rises.  You break out in a sweat and you remember having  looked at cases and thinking, "I'll just be extra careful," knowing quite well that you really should have used protection....All this takes place in one or two seconds.  And then reality hits:  You pick up the phone and see the glass.  It's like having your puppy run over by a car...sickening.  So you spend a hundred dollars or so to get your screen replaced, and the same day you pick out a durable case like you should have done in the beginning.  Do yourself a favor and buy this case before it's too late.  The Otterbox Commuter will not improve your phone's looks but it isn't as clunky and the Defender series.  You need it, you know it, now buy it .

reviewText: So first off, this is not a terrible case.  It has a nice form factor, appears very well made, and provides ample protection, including a small bumper which protrudes to protect the screen, which I consider essential and is missing from many other "slim" cases.  (Admittedly I never dropped my phone in the case so I can't vouch for it being as protective as it appears.)  Unfortunately I do have some quibbles which makes me unable to recommend this case for the $20 I paid for it.1) The case is actually two separate parts, a silicone inner section and a hard plastic shell.  This is a somewhat awkward system and I wonder about it's purpose as it doesn't appear that you could use either part separately, so why make them as separate pieces.  In any case, it makes putting your phone into the case MUCH more difficult.  It took me probably ten minutes to get my phone lodged in there properly, and I was worried all the while that something was going to rip.  If you dont change cases often this isn't a huge deal but it is bothersome.2) The hard plastic shell is oddly slippery.  I know this doesn't seem too bad, but considering how often I'm holding my phone I could easily imagine it being a sizable annoyance.3)  This is more of a recommendation, it looks terrible if you're using it with a white phone (If it's the black case.)  I thought it might look good but it was actually very unattractive to have the black case with my white ipod.  My personal opinion (although my girlfriend agreed.)

reviewText: I was impressed with the protection and the clear cover - applied easily without bubbles. Also when installing the OtterBox over the phone with the shield, be careful to prevent peeling back the shield.  Once on, the results seem good with decent protection. reviewText: Firstly, this is MUCH closer to a maroon than a 'plum' color. That's fine, but I was hoping for a case that was less bulky but still protective. This doesn't feel any less bulky than the Commuter series case that I already have. It is, as others have said, impossible to put the case on with a screen protector in place. Can't do it, no way, no how. The case is also not 'grippy' at ALL. Some people may not like that the phone can easily slide around on a hard surface. What's more, the buttons are hard to push, requiring quite a lot of pressure, when covered by the case. The opening for the sync cable at the bottom is quite deep, so anything short of the slim iPhone sync cord that came with the case won't fit. On the plus side, unlike many other 'slide on' cases that are made in this fashion, Otterbox has taken care to line the insides with a thin felt, to prevent scratching of the phone itself (as it is a VERY snug fit). If you dislike the silicone/rubbery casings on the Commuter series, and want a snug fitting case, this is probably the way to go, but it's not a significantly less bulky case compared to the commuter series. One very positive thing I noticed, however, is that the screen protectors that are included have been changed so that they do not impede the prox sensor on the white iPhone.

reviewText: This is a great daily use case.  This is my fourth case for the Razr and I'm finally happy.  The case does not add a tremendous amount of bulk (it's only a hair thicker than my old DX is without any case).  It's already saved me from one drop on the corner, one accidental throw that landed on the corner and one that landed face down (all on pavement).  The best part is that it fits in the car dock and the connector lines up perfectly if you remove the insert in the dock.Pros:* Slim enough to still keep in a pocket* Good protection, it's saved me from 3 big drops so far and all I have is one small nick in the plastic* Fits the phone well* Fits in the standard Moto car dock* The rubber buttons line up well with the physical buttons and actually make it easier to use them* The bezel is NOT too large to get to the edge of the touch screen (the larger bezel on the defender makes it difficult to get to the edge of the touchscreen if you have big fingers)Neutral:* Because of the shape it takes a little more effort to get it into the car dock than bare, but it clips in snug and does not shake.  To take it out, I put my thumb on the top of the cradle and used my index finger to pull the phone forward so it pops out (this is so I don't end up ripping off the suction cup by yanking on it).Cons:* The plastic is standard plastic, it doesn't feel as nice as some others (but it won't lose the finish like those others might).* The flaps that covers the top ports is rubber and it can be difficult to get it to go back in, I just cut mine offVerdict:This is how ALL smart phone cases should be made, the right amount of protection vs bulk and it fits in the car dock, WIN.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: I have decided that otterbox cases are now the best on the market, Even if the price is a bit high I still like the protection these otterbox cases give to your devices I will order otterbox again.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: What can I say that hasn't been said already? Otterbox has yet to disappoint me with their products.  My Samsung feels great in my hands and I have friends who wished they had purchased one for their device.  Their phone dropped and cracked/shattered in one of the upper corners.  Great product!
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: This fits my Razr perfectly and comes with an easy to install screen protector.  Besides offering excellent protection, it also fits the Razr car mount without taking the case off.  Excellent value and protection.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: First, reality check:  Kevlar and gorilla glass do not make the Razr indestructable.  However, being super thin, the Razr can wear some beefy protection and not feel like a brick in your hand.  The Commuter does it for me.  The interior silicone wrap serves as a bumper and shock absorber, while the hard case makes an already sturdy phone feel rock solid.  With the commuter case, the Razr becomes about as thick as a naked Droid X or Bionic.  I also find the phone stays in my pockets a little better with the case on--without, it is so thin and slippery, it can slide out of a pocket if you sit the wrong way .All the ports are covered but easily accessible by silicon flaps that tuck into the hard shell, except the SD/SIM card slot.  This to me is the one down side--you have to removve the case to access the SD card.  If this fixed, 5  stars easy. The power and volume rockers are completely covered, yet still easy to press.  The screen side has a silicon edge around it, making it impossible to lay the glass down on a flat surface.  This screen bumper is far enough back to not interfere with the touch screen itself, so you get protection without messing with functionality.Overall, great protection that does not look like Fort Knox on a phone, yet still keeps your Razr safe.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: As said by everyone here, this cover is in 2 parts which provides a soft cushion to the phone inside and a hard cover outside.Definitely, i dont wanna drop my phone but i am pretty sure this cover will protect it from any minor accidents.Aesthetics - The cover looks nice, but no one will realize that you have a razr. The phone is truly amazing but definitely any phone inside a cover is never the same. The phone feels better in the pocket now. The cover doesnt add too much thickness to the phone, its still comparable to galaxy nexus without cover. There is no opening for the microSD and SIM card slot in the cover. The microHDMI, charging and headset jack are securely covered, easy to open and close. The volume rocker and switch off buttons are nice and easy to recognize with the cover on them.Protection - Looks like this cover will provide sufficient protection from minor falls. atleast u dont have to worry about it each time you put the phone on any surface or throw it in the bag. Initially, its a little hard to put on the cover and it doesnt come out easily too, making it feel more secure inside. After a couple of times, it will be easier to take out as you get used to it.Grip - I have not had any issues in gripping the phone, the back is slightly textured and definitely the cover never slips from the hand or the pocket.Screen Protector - Not that great. Oil like texture can be easily seen on the screen protector every time u touch it (Its strange coz there are no bubbles). screen protector covers the whole screen except for the mic and the front camera, which is good.Price - Good price considering what i paid for the phone. I can pay this much to protect it.Final Words - Very nice protection for my Motorola Razr XT910. I  love my phone and this cover is the right choice.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: I was shooting a bit in the dark when I was picking a protective case for my new Droid RAZR. I'd heard good things about Otterbox so I gave it a shot. It works beautifully for my needs. It doesn't bulk up the slim lines of the phone making it easy to slip in my pocket but seems to give it awesome protection.There is a rubber surround that goes on the phone and then the whole thing snaps into the hard shell (there is a nice video on Otterbox showing how to easily assemble). The rubber cushions the phone and covers the on/off and volume keys but they're still easy to work. The rubber also covers/protects the ports on top of the phone but they are still easy to access. The case also has a good grip so I can avoid dropping the phone in the toilet!Be aware that the package includes a screen protector so you don't need to buy any other!
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: The reviews about the install being any sort of difficult lead me towards fearing for the survival of the human race... You slip the silicone glove over your phone then slide the plastic over that. Done. This literally took me less than ten seconds without looking at the instructions which are in themselves simply 4 pictures with no words, the 4th image being a picture of the word Go. Honestly people. As for it being slippery, imagine holding a tv remote then add a speckled friction adding texture, that is what this case feels like, yet plastic is a mistifying material I know. Once you have ventured aimlessly past your aversion to plastic and the hard to follow, put the case on the phone, instructions... This case is awesome the pictures dont do it justice, as good looking as the razr already is I actually think it looks better with this case. Being an otterbox you know the protection will be sufficient, this is no defender level case by any means but I no longer worry about typical drops onto pavement or day to day type accidents and unlike the defender the case adds very little size to the phone and it still fits comfortably in your pocket.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series for Droid Razr by Motorola

reviewText: Otterbox cases are always reliable and dependable.  This case is no exception.  Although they are difficult to remove and put back on, the Otterbox cases always give great protection and stay as thin as possible while still performing their basic duty of keeping your phone safe.

reviewText: Fortunately, i read the description and looked at the pictures before ordering, because this is the most minimalist Otterbox I've seen. I've had plenty of other cases of this style, and this one feel very sturdy and secure. Nice bonus that there are lint flaps to keep the USB & HDMI ports protected, the silicon wraps over the screen just enough that even the edges of the screen protector I have are covered (UnfortunatelyI'm stuck with a screen guard that is cut short and narrow...).  The hard plastic shell only wraps around the top and sides~ kinda nice that i can now lean my phone up in a corner and it doesn't slide back down.All things considered, this case is well worth the cost, and I'd recommend it to anyone who has a razr.

If it sealed better, it would be great!3)The opening to the headphone jack is not accommodating to all headset jacks (My primary pair of headphones, specifically).Despite these, its overall I very nice case and would recommend it.EDIT: December 22/2012. Case broke on my earlier this year. If one of the covers (i.e. charge port or headset) rips off, the case doesn't stay on too well. Stopped using it because of this, but still the best case I've ever owned.

reviewText: I have always wondered why people would pay so much for a phone protector.  I thought since the price was more than 50% off I would try this out. reviewText: First of all: this case rules when it comes to protecting my phone. The screen-cover is a little janky, but it needs to work with the touch screen. It's wonky, but it works perfectly.I'm not knocking a star off because of the size: this thing is meant to fit a phone that feels more like an iPad than the sleek tricorder-thing I used to press to my head a decade ago. It is impossible to wear this on the belt without also strapping on a six-shooter. It looks ridiculous, like I'm carrying around a portable DVD player so I can quick-draw Seinfeld clips.What I'm knocking a star off for is the color. Black. I work outdoors, which means black is impossible to find if I drop it. The size of the phone is already ludicrous. Why not some Day-Glo colors? I'd pay extra for them because it will save me the $100 deductible to replace my phone when I lose it.Again: awesome case, sturdy, virtually bullet-proof on three out of four of its sides.

reviewText: Hey, these people know what they are doing. It seems to me that the hard inner plastic case takes a bunch of the shock by spending the energy on breaking apart the two halves of it's self. Then the rest is spent in the rubber shell. The shell definitely protects the phone from scrapes and scratches and the plastic screen cover that is attached to the hard plastic case does an excellent job at protecting the screen. I wouldn't buy any other case.A word to the wise for any of you who might be tempted to remove the screen cover. I did so on my brand new phone and grit got stuck around the edges of the screen opening and left pits in my phone glass and case. This isn't the cases fault, we're the ones who chose to modify the case design. If you take the screen protector out, be sure to take the case off and clean regularly to minimize damage.

reviewText: This case makes a large phone huge. So if you think the phone is a little too large without a case, don't get this.  However, if you think you will take your phone out into the world and would like to have some assurance that it will survive some rain and the occasional drop on a rock (or asphalt), this is definitely the case to buy. Lots of protection on every side of the phone.My only complaint is that the clear plastic window for the front of the phone makes the screen look a little grainy. I bought the Nexus primarily because of the large high resolution super sharp display and the Otter case degraded that a little. Not as bad as some of the other protectors I have seen.  There is a solution!  I purchased the Aduro membrane screen protector ( http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B007NMJM66/ref=cm_cr_ryp_prd_ttl_hst_5 ), which was highly regarded as very clear. I loved it!  So, I pushed the Otter plastic screen protector out of the case (it is glued in to the front frame) and spent some time getting the excess glue off the case. then I put the case on the phone with the Aduro screen protector already on it. The Otter case provides a protective frame on the front of the phone that covers the edges of the screen and everythign is protected while leaving my screen crystal clear and high resolution.
title: OtterBox Defender Series for Samsung Galaxy Nexus

reviewText: I have always had Otterbox cases and loved them. However, this case is already breaking/broken after less than a year from opening the case up. reviewText: Otter box being well known for their durability, this case does the trick. Worth the money, I will never use another case.

reviewText: Otterbox is one of the better/tougher line of cases for your smart phone i have come across, especially the defender series.  I don't use the belt clip part, but the case itself is tough as nails.  I have dropped my phone countless times and while the otterbox case has dings and scratches, my phone is in mint condition and doesn't have a mark on it. title: OtterBox Defender Series for Samsung Galaxy Nexus

reviewText: Otterbox makes the best cases for phones that I've ever found.  This case works for the Samsung Galaxy Nexus phone, which you can buy unlocked for GSM networks worldwide from Google for $349.00.  There is also a proprietary version from Verizon and Sprint, which I assume that this case will work with as well.The case consists of four parts.There are two hard plastic pieces that you snap around your phone.  One hard piece is for the front of your phone and the other is for the back of your phone.  The front piece includes an integrated clear plastic screen protector.After you snap those two pieces together around your phone, you then wrap the third piece, a soft rubber shell around the hard pieces.  The soft rubber piece acts to conceal the seams on the hard plastic pieces, to add additional impact protection, and to make it harder to drop the phone.The last piece is a hard plastic belt holder, which can also be used as a hard plastic cover for the front of the phone.  This piece is entirely optional.  You can use it, or just put it into the drawer.  The phone will snap into and out of this piece in either direction, so you can have the phone on your belt facing inwards (screen protected) or outwards (screen visible).  I prefer to keep the belt clip portion clipped onto my backpard, with the screen outward, so I can use the phone while it's clipped onto my bag.The whole case shows a high degree of design intelligence.  It provides the ultimate in protection for your phone, and has the bulk necessary to achieve that goal.If you want a great case that is less bulky, Otterbox also makes a version for this phone called the Commuter, which is thinner and offers no belt clip and no integrated screen protector.  However, it still offers a very high level of protection.
title: OtterBox Defender Series for Samsung Galaxy Nexus

reviewText: UPDATES AT THE BOTTOM -- possible extended battery problem...Just want to start off this review with a disclaimer: Otterbox Defenders are known to be bulky compared to the "skin" style cases such as the popularDiztronic Flexible TPU Case. This review is written with that in mind -- I'm not knocking this case's size, because we're all aware of that going in.And in answer to another question that is sure to arise, YES, this case is compatible with theSamsung Galaxy Nexus 2100mAh Extended Battery & Cover. The extended battery comes with a replacement back for the phone that results in perhaps an extra millimeter of thickness, making the fit of the Otterbox Defender snug, but just so. It fits.If you're in love with the subtle curve of the Nexus' screen, a word of warning: this case makes it disappear. As you can see from the photos I've added, there is a slight curve evident when the phone is set, face down, on a flat surface. But the bulk of the case really makes the phone appear to be dead flat up front. The back, however, attempts to maintain a bit of the tapered curve, and even has nicely rounded edges that make this monster more comfortable and natural to hold.The case is actually four components, as follows:1. There's a hard plastic "inner" case that is actually two pieces, a front and a back that snap together around the phone. This hard plastic has cutouts appropriate for the display screen, front & rear cameras + flash, LED notification, speakers & mic, prox sensor, headphone & MHL (USB) port, plus the volume rocker and power button.2. Glued into the hard plastic case is a "thicker-than-mylar, thinner-than-a-credit-card" screen protector. That's right, it's a rigid plastic screen protector, and it can't be swapped out.3. The whole plastic shell is wrapped by a substantial silicone boot. The edges of the boot engage with a channel around the face of the plastic shell to "lock it in" and, for the most part, give it a very integrated look. The boot has two very pronounced solid block protrusions that carry button presses down to the power and volume switches on the phone. Cutouts are present for front and rear mics, camera & flash, rear speaker. Silicone flaps cover the MHL and 3.5mm audio jack, and these flaps are held securely closed by channels on the hard plastic shell. The back of the rubber is lightly textured for improved finger grip. The boot itself is soft and not overly sticky/grippy -- in fact, a little "slippery." So it doesn't give me too much of a problem in my pockets whereas some silicone cases tend to grip pocket material -- as in the actual cloth in my pants or jacket -- making inserting or retrieving my phone a nuisance, and collecting pocket lint in the process. The Otterbox boot *mostly* doesn't have a problem with that.4. Lastly, there's the holster, which is, in fact, optional. The phone snaps in securely, either facing out or facing in, and the spring loaded belt clip rotates a full 360 to allow the whole contraption to be worn in any orientation. To round things out, the holster doubles as a desktop stand and holds the phone in a not-quite vertical landscape orientation, for media consumption.One benefit of having a phone as thin as theGalaxy Nexusis that a relatively bulky case such as this can be fitted without causing the phone to resemble a paperback book. And without the holster, my rubberized Nexus still slides easily into pant, jean and coat pockets.But let's talk about some of the negatives:- The holster blocks the 3.5mm audio jack -- so no wired headphones if you're using it as a desktop stand.- The case covers the 3-pin connector on the side of the phone. But considering the phone with *any* case will never fit into a Samsung desktop dock or vehicle mount that might make use of those connectors, it's a bit of a moot point.- I've noticed the hard plastic frame around the screen obstructs the movement of icons and widgets to the next left screen on my Home page. It's just in the way by maybe a millimeter, causing me to have to "re-grab" the icon closer to its right edge to be able to force it on over to that next page. A minor annoyance that doesn't affect day-to-day use, except for when I'm rearranging icons & widgets.- The cutout surrounding the camera lens & flash is a finger magnet. I almost wish this came with a removable plug to provide protection in day-to-day use, because having a recessed, oily camera lens is not good for snapping pics.- The silicone cover is just every-so-slippery, and with the extra weight added to the phone (mine now weights 210 grams / 7.4 ounces with the case + extended battery), if I'm sitting around lazily ingesting a longer YouTube clip, the phone tends to want to droop a little out of my grip.- The mic port cutout in the boot is just every so slightly misaligned. This hasn't caused a muffled audio problem on the other end of my calls that anyone has pointed out, but the potential is there. It would be easy to correct with some precise work with a razor blade.- I don't want to knock the integrated screen saver too much, but it has these faults:(1) It collects lint and dust underneath (between the screen protector and the screen)(2) It has a slight, slight unevenness to it -- I can feel a "wave" as I run my fingertip across its length(3) It is not independently replaceable if I scratch or damage it, and there's no way I'm going to slap a stick-on screen protector over it!(4) It is a fingerprint magnet, especially in contrast to the bare Nexus screen, which incorporates a oil-resistant coating(5) There is a slight rainbow discoloration to it at certain viewing angles and/or brightnesses, AND it makes off-angle reading slightly fuzzyBut in day to day use, the Otterbox screen protector is very invisible to me. I'm impressed that this hunk of clear plastic sitting between me and my phone doesn't present itself as more of an obstruction.And that can be said for the Otterbox Defender case as a whole. Yeah, there's no getting around its bulk. But it has a level of finish that is betrayed by its size, and I trust it to keep my silicon, glass and plastic toy from getting too banged up -- because I know those few accidental drops my last phone survived are only going to be rougher on a phone with a screen this size.+ + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + + +Update September 2012:During the first few months of use of this case (and the Galaxy Nexus on the 4.0.1 ICS operating system), I began experiencing an increasing number of lockups where I had to remove the Otterbox case to perform a battery pull to reset the phone. This took a toll on the case, and eventually the tabs that hold the two halves together chipped off and no longer held.At the end of March, I contacted Otterbox, who collected some basic information, and sent me a replacement case.The replacement case seemed every bit identical to the original. Despite what I read online about Otterbox slightly modifying the case for something or other, the rep I worked with assured me that they hadn't -- and there was no evidence that anything was different, i.e. no changes to model or version numbers stamped on the case. Oh, and the screen protector on this one was perfectly flat -- gone was that "wave" I mentioned in my review.About this time, I updated my OS to 4.0.4 and the lockups stopped, so the phone has been more-or-less sealed in the case, with the exception of 3 times I've removed it to show the naked phone to somebody.This third time removing it, I was surprised to find all but one of the tabs broken. It appears that the only thing holding the case together was the exterior boot. I haven't abused the case, and can only suspect the pressure from the extended battery cover is contributing to these tabs breaking.

reviewText: I bought this case for my brand new AT&T; iphone 4S (white). My BF has the Verizon version, and the case fits both. I was a little worried when I ordered it because one review said the headphone jack hole was in the wrong place and that it actually isn't for the 4S after all. That is not true.There is a hole at the top of the case - for the microphone. The headphone jack is appropriately covered with a flap to avoid introducing dust and debris into the hole when it is not in use. All of the other holes, buttons, flaps, etc line up as you would expect. The buttons can be pressed easily through the raised portions of the case and the flaps can be opened and closed without issue, once you learn where they all are. = )The description and picture don't really do the case justice. The blue plastic is a vibrant ocean blue (nearly teal), the purple is a dark purple, but not quite plum or eggplant. It looks great with my white iphone, but also looked great with my boyfriend's black one. Please note, however, that the opening about the back camera/flash has BLACK plastic and not blue. This may be to avoid reflective issues with the flash, and does not detract from the case in any way - even with a white iphone.The case is solidly constructed and pieced together in such a manner than none of the pieces could accidentally come apart without either major breakage or purposeful intent.The screen has a built in screen protector, which works well even with the second one I have underneath it (yes, I am paranoid and clumsy). The back hole exposing the apple logo also has a plastic protector. The only places the phone is even remotely exposed when all flaps are in place are: around the bottom speakers, the top microphone, the front speaker/sensor/camera area and the back camera/flash area. The exposed areas are as minimal as necessary and do not make me feel that the case would not fully protect the phone.The case is slightly grippy and does not slip easily, but does not appear to attract lint easily, either. The screen does not have an overly plasticy feel and wipes clean easily. Although the clear film could be scratched, it would not be done so with incredible ease.The case does add bulk to the phone. There is no getting around that. I do not find the bulk to be prohibitive, but I almost never carry my phone in my pocket. I'm not an engineer, builder or mathematician, but I would say it increases the size by about 25-30%. This is not a lot when you stick the phone in a bag or purse, but might make a difference if sticking it in a pocket. The phone also come with a black belt clip. The belt clip adds somewhat more bulk, but the phone can be placed inside with the screen pointed in or out, depending on if you value protection or convenience. The clip on the belt clip also rotates so that you can wear the phone vertically or horizontally, depending on your preference.Please note that some descriptions say the case is felt lined. That is not true. It has a pad inside that covers about 75% of the back plastic - most likely to help cushion the phone, stop the case from scratching the phone, and to help with heat distribution. But the case is not lined in any way on the inside.Last, but not least, there were some reviews (for other colors) that state one of two things are detractors: 1) That the case causes sound irregularities, such as lower volume or echoing OR 2) That the case interferes with the camera and/or flash. Well, I don't know what other people are doing, but I do not find either of those statements to be true. I tested both the earphone and speakerphone with and without the case and found no issues. I also took pics with both the front and rear camera before and after placing the case and found no issues there either.So far, I really like the case. If any issues arise, I will be sure to post them and adjust my rating as necessary.
title: Otterbox Defender iPhone 4 / 4S Case with Holster (Purple and Blue)

reviewText: Like the other reviews, requires a lot of finagling if you have a screen protector - but it is not impossible. Once you get it on there, it's worth the effort. I've dropped the phone several times and no damage.To put on with the screen protector, you need to hold the screen protector edges down with the fingers of your left hand while you put the top half of the case on at an angle with your right hand. If it starts to bubble, you have to start the process again and reposition the screen protector.I've done this several times with the thick privacy screen protectors and two of these cases with flawless results and no cutting of the screen protector or shaving of the case.

reviewText: I'm a huge Otterbox fan. I've put Otterbox Commuter cases on all of my phones. I ran across the Reflex on Otterbox's website and decided to give it a try.It's a snug fit and is fits the phone like a glove with very little added bulk. I was surprised by the quality, it definitely looks like it will absorb some shock.. which is true to Otterbox's charactor. Here's where the case fell short for me:I use Zagg's on my phones. This case, being so tight and a slide on, is incompatible with the Zagg. It's impossible to get on with both the front and the back Zagg applied, and is very difficult to install with just the front installed.. plus it peels up the protector if you're not careful.The second deal breaker for me was the port opening on the bottom. I use an aftermarket 5' charger at work, and the charging port opening is too narrow for it to fit my cord. No bueno.Otherwise, cool looking case in the transparent clear, would probably look really cool in one of the colored transparents with a white iPhone. Quality seemed great. But everyone's wants and needs are different and this one just didn't work out for me. I'll be going back to my trusty Commuter series.
title: OtterBox Reflex Series Case for iPhone 4/4S - Retail Packaging - Clear

reviewText: This is the first Otterbox of this kind that I've purchased. It comes loose once in a while, and I wonder if it might come apart. The back side (where it snaps together) closes with a "click" sound, letting you know that it's secure. When it moves slightly, I get slightly concerned of it's ability to keep my cell phone safe.Only parts of this phone cover is rubberized (the black parts), the rest is hard plastic. reviewText: I previously had an OtterBox Commuter case on my iPhone 4S. At first, I loved it as well...however, a year later, after a few drops and putting it in and pulling it out of my pocket a few thousand times, the hard shell started cracking and the silicone liner started getting pretty sloppy.This Reflex case I found to be slightly loose on my iPhone with only a screen protector. However, I found that after installing a scratch protector on the back of the phone, it shimmed up thick enough that this case now fits very snugly, and I feel much more confident with it. I was surprised that such a thin layer would make that much difference, but it really did.I really like how much smoother and solid the phone feels now. The Commuter case had nice "grip," but the soft, grippy sections and many plastic edges made it challenging to get in and out of my pockets easily. The Reflex case on the other hand is nice and smooth, yet has just enough texturing to feel solid in my hand.I feel fairly confident that this case will hold up better than the Commuter did, and will serve me well for at least another year. I will update this review after I've used it for a while and see how it holds up and how much protection it offers.UPDATE:I have been using this case for about 4 months now, and am very happy with it. I did have to drill out the speaker jack opening a bit in order to get ALL headphone plugs to work. Not a big deal though. Also, I just dropped my phone on the asphalt from 6 feet in the air for the first time, and the only damage was a scratch on the case. No cracks or breaks, and the phone still works perfectly. Very impressed! :)

reviewText: I got tired of my Defender Realtree rubber exterior case and decided I would keep the orange hard plastic interior cover, but find a different rubber to encase it.  I know it seems silly and expensive, however if you treasure your Iphone's health as much as I do mine, there's nothing you won't do to protect it. And bar none, the Otterbox Defender case is the very best - hands down. Don't get me wrong, till now the Realtree was fine except that when the phone was face down in my black purse, black car seat cover or dark drawer, it could be a few seconds before I would locate it and my heart could resume beating. Not anymore.I have to say that the moment I put this new, gorgeous blue exterior case over my orange one it was like magic.  Not only will I have no trouble locating my phone anywhere, but when I do it is even more beautiful then before. The orange design on the back perfectly complements the orange case within.I only wish that Amazon could encourage Otterbox to sell the individual components so that consumers could mix and match colors without having to buy a whole unit (and get yet another holster for my junk drawer).As for the owners out there who are concerned with the slight difference in blue coloring - I have no idea what they're talking about. Everything looks great and the cover is smooth enough that it will slide in your pocket without sticking when you go to take it out.If you want a case that is stylish, beautiful, functional and offers total protection - this might be just what you're looking for.

reviewText: I have used numerous Otterbox Defenders over the years for various devices and have never had a complaint.  My teenage daughter wore her case out for her iPhone 4S after over a year, and asked for a new one.  She found this one on Amazon and asked if she could get this designer one, instead of the normal Otterbox Defenders that I slap on my family's devices.  I agreed and purchased this about 4 months ago.The first thing I noticed is that this case started to show wear within the first month.  Her old one didn't show wear for nearly 6 months.  About 2 weeks ago, we were able to accidentally test the protection aspect of this particular case...and it failed miserably.  We have these huge beanbags in our house (made by Lovesac), and that is wear my daughter sits.  When an adult is on one of the beanbags, the highest point to the ground is maybe 3 feet.  She laid her phone on the edge of the beanbag and continued to watch the movie we were viewing.  I had a birds-eye view of the phone from my chair, and saw it slide off when she shifted in the beanbag.  Remember, I said slid off, not dropped.  It slid off the beanbag and landed on the side of the case on the tile floor from about 30"-36" off the ground.  I could tell by the sound of the impact that we probably had a problem.  When I picked the phone up, I could see the shattered screen.  I have dropped my phone in normal Otterbox Defender cases from that height and higher a number of times and never had an issue.  I can't understand why this mild drop resulted in a shattered screen.Oddly enough, just the other night my wife's iPhone 4S in a "normal" Otterbox Defender case took an identical tumble from the same spot, and there wasn't even a blemish on the phone....  Go figure.Overall it looks nice and is different from the hordes of Otterbox Defenders out there, but it didn't protect the phone as it should have.

reviewText: Love it!  What can I say that others haven't.  I love my Sam Galaxy S III phone and the Otterbox case. The Otterbox provides a "grip" feel while you hold the phone and adds edge protection along all the edges and corners of the phone.  I also wanted the Otterbox for protection on the ports--charge port, ear phone port and on/off tab.  Yes... it is a little hard to press the on/off tab, but as others have said, it's worth it!  No drops yet... The case is still slim-line for a women, no added bulk! It fits nice in my purse. I see no reason for the shield protector, but it's in the draw if I ever need it.  Four stars due to the on/off tab being somewhat hard; otherwise, excellent product!

reviewText: This OtterBox Commuter is really nice case offering a sleek 2 piece design and great protection for your GS3.  The screen protector that comes with the case has done well. The phone can and will slip out of your hand easier to me than without a case.  Go figure.  My wife has a GS3 also and uses the OtterBox Defender which is bulkier than the Commuter, but the Defender case has significantly more grip in hand and feels more secure, but it is bulkier. reviewText: I can't honestly give this case 4 and 5 stars like the rest of the people. It is true that the rubber inside fits great for the S3 and the hard plastic snaps on nicely. But part of using your phone ALL day is constantly having to use your "buttons".I use my power button to bring my phone out of screen saver mode (screen turns black) and back into it. At this point I am now using my black button at the bottom of the screen for "unlocking" my phone (bringing out of screen save mode) and I still have to use the power button to go back into screen save mode (due to not having a choice beside just waiting for the phone to go into screen save by default, but that waste battery life). This button does require more than normal effort to press down on to work. Anyone saying otherwise has really powerful hands.  It is so bad, that I tried removing it a couple of times and putting it back on to make sure it wasn't just how I was putting it on.Now as person who brings this phone to work and uses Pandora alot, I find that I have to use my volume buttons A LOT. This is also very bad due to the fact that they to are just same and need a lot of pressure to work.  This is also multiplied due to the fact that I wear this phone inside a workout armband (which this case obviously doesn't help since it makes it way to big for the case (that is the case maker fault, not the otter box)). To press buttons while in the armband is just to frustrating. Make sure you set your volume and things BEFORE you put it into any type of workout band.The stars I've given is due to how well I think it will protect the phone (because I'm not going to act like I know it will protect it (and I'm not going to go throwing my phone down on the ground)), how well it fits, and it's functions. This is truly how people should be rating this. The funniest part to me is all the 5 stars that actually complain about the buttons. I don't complain about something and rate it PERFECT.And yes, I've had an Otter box before back when I had a Blackberry. I had zero problems pressing the buttons for that one.

reviewText: I picked up my Galaxy SIII phone from Sprint, and a few weeks later accidentally smashed it.  Although the phone was covered under an accidental damage warranty (something I don't usually buy or need), I wouldn't be eligible for another replacement for a long time.  I needed to protect the replacement phone as best I could, so I picked up the OtterBox case.The case arrives in three pieces.  The first is a screen protector, which I chose not to install.  The second is a flexible rubber cover that goes over the phone.  The third is a hard plastic case that goes over the rubber case.  Once all this installed, the phone is about twice as thick as it was.  I'm not crazy about that, but I need the protection so I live with it.Once installed, the case covers up the various ports on the phone to keep dust out of them.  The port covers are part of the flexible rubber piece.  They open and close easily, and "lock" into place when closed.  Because the case covers up the buttons for power and volume control, you have to press a bit harder than normal to get the flexible rubber "buttons" to make contact with the real buttons underneath.  This is both good and bad.  It's good in that this makes it a lot harder to press the buttons by mistake.  It's bad in that it's simply a bit harder to press the buttons in general.  Again, part of the price you pay for protection.On balance, I am very happy with the case and the protection it offers.  There are, however, a couple of things I don't like about it.  First, the hard plastic case is a bit slippery to hold on to, even though it's got a "rough" finish to it.  I've found the phone slipping from my hands while holding it.  It would be nice if they rubberized the back of it.  Second, the case is hard to remove.  If you have a situation where the phone has locked up and needs to have the battery removed, you've got to struggle a bit with the hard plastic shell to get it off the inner rubber case. Then you remove that, then the back of the phone, and finally the battery.  That's a lot of work.  Fortunately, the GS3 is a very well-made, reliable phone that rarely needs this treatment.  If I was a frequent traveler who had to carry spare batteries with me to get through the day, I might think about replacing this with a case that is easier to put on and off the phone.  As it is, this isn't a problem for me.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - White

reviewText: It's an Otterbox, of course it meets expectations. I was concerned that the white case would discolor but it hasn't. The power button is stiff. It is more slippery in your hand than the Defender but not as bulky. I'm satisfied.

reviewText: This case offers a WONDERFUL level of protection, stays as slim as possible, and the design is blessedly minimal.However, getting the phone INTO the case has proven to be quite the task. This case comes in two parts - the inner rubber sleeve (gray) and the outer hard case (white). It seems simple enough, you put the rubber sleeve on first and then put the hard case over it. The fit of the hard case is so snug though that its very difficult to do that. When getting the phone into the case the phone must have powered on and off three times and it eventually ended up in "safe mode" (due to a combo of buttons being pressed simultaneously - which caused me to remove the case and pull the battery to get out of safe mode).I'm still having issues with the volume keys working sporadically, but the effort and the results of taking the case off to re-position the rubber sleeve is not worth it. The number of reviews on this product makes it hard to read how other users successfully put the case onto the phone, so I'm going to do some research on other sites to see about some suggestions. I was considering warming the hard case first, to make it more pliable before putting it over the rubber sleeve, but I haven't done so yet.

reviewText: I got this case for my dad who wanted a protective case. Immediately the first thing that came to mind was Otterbox. After looking through a few cases, we decided on this one. Overall, it is a well made case that does offer two layers of protection, a gel inner layer and a hard outer layer. I figure that this will do its job very well, protecting against minor falls.2. For the amount of protection that this case provides, it is surprisingly thin. The phone itself is pretty large, but even with the case on it still fits comfortably in my pocket. Plus it looks and feels good in the hands.3. This one can go both ways. But I liked the fact that all the ports (micro USB & headphone jack) had a detachable covering on them. I feel that this adds to the protection aspect, as well as deters dirt or lint from coming in the phone.CONS:1. The gel skin is pretty thick. When you try to press the power button, or even the sound rocker, you're gonna need a bit more force. I found myself pressing more than I thought I'd need to just to get the phone to turn on and off. reviewText: This is overall a nice case for the Samsung Galaxy S3.  This is my wife's phone, so it only had to satisfy her, but I'll add my own observations, too.The included screen protector was easy to install (I've never really had a problem installing screen protectors), and fits the phone well.  Since the edges of the screen are curved, the screen protector does not go all way to the frame edge (it would keep peeling up if it did), but the lip of the rubber case comes pretty close to covering that.The case itself was relatively easy to install.  I watched a YouTube video before attempting it, and before you attempt to install it yourself, I would advise doing the same because the video shows the easiest way to get it installed.Overall, the case works well and is designed nicely.  About the only "Con" I observed is that the volume and power buttons are rather difficult to push now.  For those wanting to know, the rubber part of the case is a true light purple color, but the hard shell part of the case is more pink than purple ("mauve"?).  My wife really wanted a true pink, but this will have to do since it's the closet thing OtterBox offers.*I* wouldn't like this case because of how difficult it is to press the buttons (which I why I rated it 4 stars).  However, my wife is the one that has to use it and she says she doesn't have a problem with it, so...it's clearly a personal thing.I was deciding between the Samsung Galaxy S3 and Galaxy Note 2 phones for myself, and now that I have decided on the Note 2, I will be going with a Seidio Surface Case & Holster combo instead of this OtterBox case.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - White

reviewText: I have had two smartphones and numerous different cases.  For this phone, the Samsung Galaxy SIII, I have tried two cases.  This is the best I've ever had - period.When I went to order this case, it was on back order for several weeks and my phone was scheduled to arrive in just a few days.  I was also looking at the Diztronic case:http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0089F49P0/ref=oh_details_o04_s00_i00The reviews for the Distronic case were good, and it was also pretty cheap, so I decided to buy it so I would have some protection right away while I waited on the Otterbox to arrive.  The only real problem with the Distronic case is that it just doesn't provide much protection from drops.  I was concerned about really protecting my phone, so I decided to order the Otterbox 77-21392 Commuter Case too.I was a little apprehensive about the Otterbox because it's not as cheap and also because I have seen people with those huge cage-looking Otterbox cases for their iPhones and I didn't want something that big and bulky (and ugly, in my opinion).  The Galaxy SIII is a large phone due to its big screen, but it is otherwise very thin and I didn't wan't to ruin that.In the end, I decided to try my first Otterbox, and I am thrilled!  It just came today.  First, I have the white SIII phone, and this case looks great on it - very sharp looking.  The gray and white contrast is stylish.  Second, I finally feel like my phone is protected from drops.  Also, it clearly adds some bulk to the phone but not nearly as much as the other style Otterbox cases do and I am fine with the new size of the cased phone.  The phone feels safer and more substantial (in a good way) without being too bulky in my pocket.  Finally, the case form-fits VERY well, and the cut outs and the covers for buttons, etc. are perfect.  It adds some stiffness to the power button and volume rocker as all cases of this type would, but it is not too stiff to make it a nuisance.The case is absolutely perfect - I am thrilled with the look, feel, size, and functionality of this case.  Very nicely made!

reviewText: Otterbox is known for its quality protection, even if it tends to be at the upper range in terms of price. I was a bit wary of putting more money into a case, but after buying several lower-end cases that were always a bit off in one way or another, I finally decided to make the investment.Very glad that I did.Pros:1) Two-layer protection does protect against most everything. I've dropped my phone several times, on asphalt, concrete, and the kitchen floor (I have a four-year old who tends to knock everything out of my hands), and there is no problem at all. Case doesn't move, screen hasn't been cracked, scratched or otherwise hurt.2) The protection is great, and it maintains the slim feel of the phone. It slides in my pockets easily, without catching or being overly bulky. A lot of slimmer cases don't protect well, and the cases that do protect well tend to not be slim. Very nice compromise between the two.3) I like the colors. I got the dark purple silicone lower layer with the lighter lilac outer, and it's a nice color combination. Fun without being unprofessional or garish.Cons:1) The back is VERY slippery. Almost as slippery as the actual phone back itself, and I've found it becoming a bit hard to hold on to at times. It's not a deal-breaker for me, because that slippery aspect is what also makes it easier to get in and out of my pocket.2) The buttons are a bit stiff, like other reviewers have mentioned, but honestly, the more I've used them, the more malleable they've become. And to be honest, I can't count how may times I've handed my phone to someone to take a picture or look at something, and they've accidentally turned it off, or turned down the volume. The stiff buttons may be hard to press, but ultimately, that's not been a "bad" thing for me.The screen protector that came with the phone is meh. I don't consider it a pro or con overall. There are better quality ones out there, for sure, that actually cover the screen edge to edge, but it does the job.The cover itself is also not the easiest to get on, since the plastic is very stiff and doesn't go over the rubber easily. The tabs for the headphone jack and power cable also don't go through that easily when installing the case and get stuck beneath it, but overall, it's not that bad. A bit more effort and maneuvering, but honestly, once it's in place, it's very secure and firm. So the installation is meh, but the reward is pretty good.Overall, I love the case, and totally wouldn't trade it for any other. And I've tried quite a few.

reviewText: Really liked the Commuter series better than the Defender because of its size - the Defender isn't pocket friendly for women but will fit in a suit pocket.The Commuter series has the snap on outer case with rubber underneath exposed on the corners so it absorbs shock in the places most likely to cause cracks when dropped. I gave my Commuter case to my sister after she cracked her screen and she loves it. No issues with camera or microphone holes, both are cut to fit pretty precisely. One caveat is that it is a little hard to push the buttons at first, but it gets softer once worn in and hasn't posed any problems. Also, since the back is hard plastic it can be fairly slippery, and can't be placed on a tilted surface without sliding, even on my lap on the train. That is the main advantage of the Defender case which I replaced it with.I got the Defender case for myself thinking it would be much better, but because the soft rubbery layer is on the outside it is prone to stretching. It is still a great case and I haven't broken my phone (though I've dropped it literally dozens of times - on rocks, on the train platform, on carpet, on bathroom tile) which is a pleasant change for me.The customer service is also great - when the outer case did stretch it was within the year warranty so I just uploaded a picture with my name and address pointing to the defect and Otterbox sent a new one. I presume they would do the same for the Commuter Series. So far have had the new case for two months and no signs of stretching, so perhaps the Defender they sent me first was just defective.

reviewText: The Commuter is comprised of 2 pieces: A silicone rubber that envelopes the Samsung Galaxy S3, and a plastic outer shell that provides some additional protection. The 2 biggest problems I have are that the buttons are overly "stiff" and the plastic shell is too slippery.The Prefix has more tactile buttons (similar to the Defender) but the Prefix's outer shell is a harder rubber that is less grippy than the Defender but nowhere as slippery as the Commuter. Unfortunately, the Prefix has inconsistent build quality. One fit overly tight and another fit overly loose. I gave up on the Prefix shortly thereafter.I had been using my Defender for just about a year and loved it, except I cracked 4 holsters that were all replaced under warranty within that year. I wouldn't have an issue just having new holsters replaced under warranty, except each time they cracked was during some kind of important event or at the most inopportune time. Once was at a company bowling event. Another was when I was camping in the middle of nowhere, another time was at a shopping mall parking lot.The Commuter is noticeably thinner and lighter than the Defender. The plastic shell is slippery and hard, so it tends to slide around on surfaces and tends to knock around on a dashboard or cupholder. The silicone rubber flaps for the earphone and USB ports feel cheap and they are held in place by the plastic shell.The buttons feel stiff because Otterbox did not extend the rubber material underneath the buttons. Looking at the Prefix and Defender rubber buttons, they are thicker and contact the phone buttons sooner thus they are more tactile. The Commuter requires more force to push down because they were made too thin.Overall: 4/5 stars. It would be 5/5 stars if the plastic shell wasn't so slippery and if the buttons were made properly so they wouldn't feel so stiff.

reviewText: I was comparing the Incipio 2-piece case with the OtterBox Commuter case, both of similar design.  Frankly, the OtterBox fits the Samsung Galaxy S III more snugly, which is a good and bad thing.  It is very difficult to take off.  The Incipio slides on and off more easily, but I could see a possibility that in taking it out of a snug pocket, both of the pieces, which fit together, could come off.  I always put it in a jacket pocket, which fits loosely, so I don't anticipate the problem.Both cases use a polycarbonate exoskeleton over a silicone inner.  Both silicone inners create a lip on the front, so if you do drop the phone on the front, the lip will protect it.  The exoskeleton on the OtterBox is a slightly more rigid and thicker, so perhaps it might be a bit more protective.  Furthermore, the OtterBox has tabs which fit over the headphone and charge ports, making it more protective against the elements.The killer to the OtterBox deal for me, though, is the button material that is used over the volume rocker.  The volume rocker on the Galaxy, itself, is soft and quite easy to use -- almost too easily touch.  The material that goes over the rocker on the OtterBox is terribly stiff.  Both the salesperson in the Verizon store as well as me had to turn the phone on its side and really push down hard on the top or bottom of the OtterBox button in order to get the volume rocker switch to respond.  Neither of us had good luck using a one-handed approach to the phone in that regard.Contrast that, not only to the Incipio, but to OtterBox's own Defender case, which has a button which is MUCH more pliable, making it far easier to manipulate the volume rocker underneath.  If I needed a really a hearty, super-protective case (If my phone were to be in physically perilous situations a lot), I'd definitely consider the Defender.  But the Defender case adds considerable bulk - both weight-wise and size-wise.  If you think you bought an elegant phone with nicely curved lines, fogeddaboutit.Which brings me back to the Incipio.  Perhaps it doesn't cross the 't's and dot the 'i's the way the Commuter case does, but it otherwise gives the normal user a substantial amount of protection -- quite adequate really.  I have already dropped the phone twice in two weeks, including once on its face on my ceramic-tiled bathroom floor.  No problem.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - White

reviewText: $16 today? Jump on it! I payed $26 last year.In principle, the Otterbox Commuter is the most confidence-inspiring case that's also practical. You need a soft shock-absorbing bumper, but by itself a gel skin picks up lint. Encasing the gel inside a smooth plastic case is the perfect solution, making it easy to slip into a pocket. You also get strong build quality and incredible customer service.But the Otterbox Commuter has problems: the flaps wear off, there's no kickstand, and similar cases are half the price.Unlike some cheap competitors, this case has protective flaps covering the USB and headphone ports, which adds some spill resistance, one would hope. But over time, those flaps wear out and rip off. Which leads me to the biggest positive: Otterbox has incredible customer service.I placed a warranty claim for torn port covers on the website. I got an email requesting three photos, which I sent. Two weeks later, a brand new case showed up at the door, completely free. Thud.The bad news: there's no kickstand.The Otterbox Commuter protects against drops, but it "causes" half of those drops, if you will. With the case installed, the edges of the phone are smooth. It needs a rubberized bumper around the edges, so I can prop it up on a table to watch video. As it is, if I try to prop up the phone to watch video, it very easily slides on its back. And off the table. I had to buy a wire book stand just for my phone. Of course, it's not like the phone would do any better without a case, but when there are so many cheap kickstand cases out there, the Otterbox Commuter just offers less functionality.Also, the stiff rubber makes the buttons very hard to press down. That's a nitpick, but it might matter to you.And the price. Normally this case goes for $25 and up, $35 list. Hybrid cases from Amzer, Emax, and Reiko offer the same shell-over-gel confidence for half that.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - White

reviewText: I own a pair of S3's and use a commuter on one. There is a very reasonable explanation for some saying their buttons are almost impossible to use while others say there is nothing at all to mention on that "issue".I first noticed on my 2 S3's that the Power Button on one is almost flush with the silver rim that goes around the middle of the case. The other protrudes about the same as the volume rocker. The "almost flush" unit power button is difficult to activate but works okay when the commuter is installed on it.The unit with the protruding power button is quite easy to use with the same Commuter case on it. Google "Galaxy S3 loose power button" and you'll see what I refer to. Also, next time you''re at your carrier, look at the display units and compare power button protrusions or lack there of.In short I am relatively sure both those that are having an impossible time activation some buttons are as correct as those saying they have no issue. Samsung has sold and has or is producing 10 million units and I suspect there is a different manufacturer for some of the same parts.This doesn't help those with an impossible to use Otterbox but does explain why some have that issue and others do not. Samsung isn't noted for their build quality (usually). Case makers can't offer varying degrees of contact points on the silicone case button so the only suggestion is get a different case.Solved my problem and again, PLEASE don't take my word for it. Compare with your own eyes. It doesn't ruin the S3 but makes getting a decent case more difficult.

reviewText: OtterBox delivers on quality protection, as usual. When you tap the back of the case, you can literally hear and feel it absorbing the shock.
