The rubber that covers the inner plastic shell is a lot harder, meaning it doesnt wiggle around. It is a little bit tougher to pull off and put on, but it gives that extra protection that I'm looking for. its also made a little different than the rubber outing compared to the iphone 4 defender case, making it easy to put into your pant pockets as well as making it easy to pull out. the one downside i can think of is that the front camera and receiver are exposed, as well as the back camera, flash and mic. in the previous defender case series, these were covered by a see through window. so if you've used your previous iphone 4 otterbox defender case in some light right, you would of been ok, but this new version has those areas exposed. But with the iphone 5, you dont need to look at ur iphone to respond to texts or to post to twitter/facebook, you have siri to do that for you, even to write emails.another big improvement is the clipcase that houses the defender casing. Its built a lot better to hold your otter box in place while its clipped to your waist line. I didnt used the previous one because it just didnt feel like it would hold my iphone 4 in place in the belt clip.All in all, this is a huge step up in quality, with that one minor issue, but its definitely worth a purchase. Oh this defender case is actually thinner than the iPhone 4 defender case, and doesnt feel as heavy. hope this helps you all.

reviewText: The iPhone 5 Otterbox Defender case is much better than its predecessors.Pros:1) The external rubber layer has some plastic element to it so that it is easy to slide in/remove from your pocket without collecting any lint/dust.2) the external rubber layer is super snug around the inner plastic layer case.3) the entire case does not add bulk to the iPhone like its predecessors did.  Its amazingly much thinner and stronger than the previous Defender cases.4)  The front and rear cameras are wide open so that the case will not interfere with flash or cause any unwanted vignette.Con:1)  It is extremely hard to open and the port covers for all ports (mute button port, charging port, and ear phones port).2) It is difficult to access the mute button.  The case has a tiny opening to access the mute button & makes it difficult for a person like me with big fingers to mute my phone.2) The built-in screen protector reduces the image quality of the retina display.  (This can be resolved easily by removing the Otterbox screen protector itself. It sounds crazy, but you will love your iPhone and Defender case much more.  The native iPhone screen is already extremely anti-scratch resistant, finger smudge resistant with a tempered glass.  Ive never had problems or scratches on my screen. The built in screen protector for the Defender case may be redundant and not worth losing the image quality on your screen.)I definitely recommend this case to any iPhone user.  If you want a thinner case and not have the difficulty of 'breaking into Fort Knox' to access your ports, I would suggest looking at Speck Cases.  They manufacture lighter and thinner cases that also give excellent protection, but not as superior as the Otterbox.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for iPhone 5 (Discontinued by Manufacturer) ( Not for iPhone 5C) Retail Packaging Bolt - Grey

reviewText: So I will be completely honest. I have gone through 2 other otterbox defenders for the iPhone 5 and was a bit hesitant to even bother trading the 2nd one in for a 3rd one via warranty replacement.The first one I received quickly failed on the top left/right plastic insert the actual phone sits in. It would not clasp together anymore and I had to send it in. Also the built in screen protector became detached from the housing and let a lot of dust in. First OB gone.The second one I received the holster clip that the actual case clipped into made the silicon housing tear a bit. Also with both when I would plug the phone in to charge it seemed like there was a little play inside the case and you could actually shake the case and hear the iPhone sliding around inside of it.Third time...ITS THE CHARM. On this one the screen protector has stayed in place and even is sitting flush with the screen, so no little poof or getting used to having to hit the screen a bit harder when texting. Also there is no play inside the case and it even feels a lot more sturdy. The plastic housing snaps in place perfect and and even makes a snapping sound that sets my mind at ease. The one thing I noticed as well as on the other cases they said made in china somewhere on them and this one inside the case, and even on the clip says USA. Does the China versus USA assembly have something to do with the difference? I would say so in this case.Definitely recommend this case to anyone. It is leaps and bounds better than the case for the 4 and much slimmer. The silicone is a higer grade and does not loosen from obsorbing the oils on your hands.Definitely a 5 star product!

reviewText: I got this for my wife's phone so that it would match the case I got for her iPod Touch 4. She loves purple and loves Otterbox so it seemed like a no-brainer. All was good for a few weeks, but then the rubber portion of this case started to stretch and flop around. It no longer stays in its little tracks around the plastic portion of the case, and frankly it looks like hell.  Not sure if we got a bad batch of material or what. The case for her iPod is still going strong after around a year's use, but this case started showing problems within the first month. I don't think she's putting any undue stress or wear on the case - she hasn't yet taken it back out since the initial installation so it's not that. The only thing she does with it is stick it in the back pocket of her jeans. I'd expect an Otterbox to be able to handle that and not stretch out of all proportion to itself but that does not seem to be the case.We're going to be contacting Otterbox for a replacement - hopefully it will be an easy process and the new one will far outlast the original. reviewText: I have tried numerous cases for my new iPhone. The silicone cases look a bit cheap. The thin hard plastic cases give the best form factor but they do not offer enough protection; my phone suffered two scratches on the bevel with the hard case, and there is little drop protection.I tried the OB Defender but that was just too excessive. It makes the phone huge and bulky, and it just doesn't look good. The silicone exterior is too sticky.But the OB Commuter is the perfect compromise. It is sleek and looks good without adding too much bulk. And it offers superior protection. This is the perfect case.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for iPhone 5 (Discontinued by Manufacturer) ( Not for iPhone 5C) Retail Packaging Bolt - Grey

reviewText: The cover protects the phone while still allowing the screen to be sensitive to touch, unlike the Ballastic case I had before this.

reviewText: From the standpoint of pure protection, I would give this a 5.  I have dropped my phone several times with absolutely no effect on the phone or the case.  Easy to assemble.  Like all Otterbox Defender cases, it seems high quality.  It does add bulk to the slim IPhone, but I knew that before I bought it.  I'm ok with the form factor.  All buttons are covered by the case, but I found the effect on the clickability of the buttons to be miniscule.  Also, the outer screen protector built into the case has only a minor (almost unnoticeable)  effect on the sensitivity of the touch screen.  Overall, well designed.I do have 2 complaints thought.  First, somehow moisture or condensation gets between the outer screen protector and the actual IPhone screen itself.  The result, at least for me, is that I get strange rainbow effects on the screen or the screen protector (can't tell which, and it doesn't matter, the effect is the same).  It's more of an annoyance than a major flaw, as the effects are relatively minor, and sometimes not even noticeable, depending on what is on the screen at the time, how the light is hitting the screen, etc.  Still, I do notice them from time to time, and they are slightly distracting. Second complaint is that the screen protector gets pretty dirty pretty easily pretty quickly. I am constantly having to clean the screen, more so than when the phone is not in the case.  Not sure why this is the case, but it just is.Am I keeping the case?  Yes.  Would I buy a different case if I had it to do over again?  Probably not, although it would be close.  For me, solid protection is the main reason I bought the case in the first place, and as noted above, I give this case a 5 for protection. My other complaints are relatively minor, but still, an irritation factor.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for iPhone 5 (Discontinued by Manufacturer) ( Not for iPhone 5C) Retail Packaging Bolt - Grey

reviewText: I bought this case for the iphone 5 because I want the best protecting possible for my phone for a few reasons. Firstly because buying a good case is a lot cheaper than potentially haveing to replace the phone, I can be rough on my phones and it makes me feel more confident holding my phone while doing demanding activities because I am not as worried about dropping my phone or getting it scratched. This particular otterbox offers the highest level of protection the company offers. I like the fact that it does not add a ton of "bulkyness," to the device while still being pretty protective.There are disapointing aspects though. Firstly the case was not made as well as it could have been. There was some access rubber that had not been properly removed during production. The case seems to become weaker and does not fit together as it did the first time if you take it on and off your phone a few times. Also, the part of the phone that would touch the phone in the front above and around the screen is just solid plastic. It would be nice to have a rubber coating there to increase shock absorbsion and make sure the sureface of the phone is not scratched. Otterbox definitly has a superior product and they know that due to the high demand. For what it is, it is extremly overpriced but considering supply and demand it seems to be working out for the company. It just sucks knowing that I paid a lot more for a product than it is actually worth to get the "otterbox." I had a case on my droid x2 made by Incipio that was a full silicone case and then it had a second stage that was hard plastic that fit around the rubber. It was almost identicle to an otterbox, I found it on amazon for $12 I think and it lasted 2 years and is still in great shape and I have dropped my phone quite a bit; no scratches or anything on the phone. Overall though, good product and worth it considering the cost of replacing the actual phone.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for iPhone 5 (Discontinued by Manufacturer) ( Not for iPhone 5C) Retail Packaging Bolt - Grey

reviewText: I give this case a 3/5 because it is true to color and looks great and offers nice protection. It seems as though it was made in a rush due to the iPhone 5's coming out so suddenly because the dark purple rubber does not fit the phone and doesn't mold to it very well at all. It's stretched out and almost doesn't stay on the upper sides of the phone.The flap that covers the headphone jack and the lightening cable port are so poorly designed. They barely stay shut when I first put it on so I assume the more I use those flaps the more loose they'll become and eventually wont close at all. The sleep/wake button is difficult to press but not as hard as the last case that I tried by another brand and returned to Amazon. This is so frustrating to me because obviously that's a button that is pressed very often and they makes it VERY annoying. The volume buttons however are not terrible. They're alright to press through the case - slightly hard. Overall a DECENT case. The color and protection is on point, unfortunately the design and molding to the phone are very disappointing. I have yet to find a case that I love and that offers great protection. I don't think this case is bulky by any means. If you're looking for protection, it's a good thickness. I shouldn't have expected anything spectacular because there were no reviews prior to me purchasing this item but I did expect a great product from OtterBox. I assume it's a knockoff since they are not usually this poorly made. Hope some of you found this helpful!

reviewText: The case itself is great - the combination of soft and hard layers provide protection from just about every bump and jolt. reviewText: Although I like several of the other case styles for the IPhone 5 and certainly recognize their utility in protecting my investment I just could not get past the bulky chunky look of them and the ease (or not!) with which they can be pulled out of a pocket or purse to answer a phone or text. This very cute Otterbox is the middle man that really is perfect for my needs.I have an IPhone for my work which means it is in and out of pockets, my purse, and my hands all day long. Therefore the case had to be durable, attractive, easy to use, and not prevent typing or otherwise viewing/using the phone. Although this case does bulk up the phone a bit it still maintains a more streamline style when you consider the protection. I love that the hard case is on the outside because that plastic means I can pull it easily from pocket or purse. Of course that also means it is more slippery in the hand as well. I'm fine with sacrificing that for the overall functionality but please do note it IS slippery - so if you are a female that wears those jeans that only come to your hips with shallow pockets this case might be problematic as it is more likely to slide out.I found it easy to put on, the ports are all either uncovered or covered appropriately, and the color is mightily pleasing. I am very satisfied. If something happens I'll update this review but, so far, this is my favorite phone case in years!

reviewText: This is my second otterbox case, the first being a defender. I found that there were serious problems with that particular case.The commuter offers good protection, but the smaller size makes it easier to carry around and the decreased thickness of the case makes texting far easier.My main concern is with build quality. The case simply looks and feels cheap. The inner rubber case simply does not hold it's shape. Even when placed inside the plastic shell, the rubber case still does not form straight lines along the edges. The rubber does not grip the sides of the case, it simply sits alongside the case, flopping around and moving easily.Another annoying aspect of the design is that the top power button is extremely difficult to activate with the rubber case attached. If you use this button regularly, this case design will frustrate you.The bottom line is that the use of cheap plastic and floppy rubber is anathema to the beautiful aluminum and glass design of the iphone itself. This case can be had for under $20 on amazon, but truth be told, you're getting a product with about a dollar or so of manufacturing materials.The case should protect the phone from drops, but it looks and feels cheap.

reviewText: I tried out 3 cases for the iPhone 5: the Speck PixelSkin HD, the OtterBox Commuter and the Otterbox Defender. I thought each of them was well designed and useful, but they serve different purposes.The Speck PixelSkin was my wife's favorite. It's very slim and unobtrusive, highlighting the sleek design of the new iPhone. However, I didn't think it offered very much protection. I was afraid that it wouldn't protect against the inevitable drops. If you're just looking for a minor amount of protection and a little extra grip, this is a great case.The Otterbox Defender is at the opposite end of the spectrum. You could probably throw your phone out the window if it's in one of these and it would be okay. But that protection comes with a cost -- it added way too much bulk for me. This case is big and thick, and probably more than most people need.I ended up going with the one in the middle: the OtterBox Commuter. It offers what I hope will be a sufficient amount of protection, without adding so much size and weight to the phone that it becomes unwieldy.It's not a perfect case. The plug covers are somewhat annoying (as they always are on cases like this), and the mute and sleep buttons take a little extra effort to engage. But I haven't found those drawbacks to be terribly significant.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Blue/Lime Green

reviewText: I love the otterbox cases, they seem to add the most protection for the minimum added bulk. I use them on my Samsung Galaxy S3 and Iphone 4. This is perfect for us since we use the iphone with a USASpec Honda adapter to listen and view song info in our car.UPDATE 10/8/13: This case has not held up as well as our previous 4S case or my Galaxy S3 case, both of those lasted multiple falls and some harsh toddler treatment. this one began to break off pieces. first the bottom section cracked on one side, and eventually came off. than just a week ago it dropped and the whole top section broke off. I am not sure if this item came from a more brittle batch of polycarb. It still has protected the phone during these falls, but with pieces coming off, I am not sure how much longer it will continue to protect the phone. reviewText: For those who want a quick review: I'd HIGHLY suggest the Commuter case if you want moderate protection, it worked very well for me. I would not recommend any of the Otterbox color combos that have inner part as white rubber. The rubber becomes unsightly very quickly.More detailed review:I bought this case in December 2011 from Best Buy Mobile (and therefore paid almost double this price). I bought this case in the pink and white color and found it to be exactly as this picture shows. My first case was a lemon, and broke (without dropping)in less than a month and I contacted Otterbox with a picture and they instantly replaced it. They sent me the exact same one and I continued to use it from January 2012 until yesterday (beginning Jan 2013). I will not lower my opinion of Otterbox for my first case being a lemon, as my whole family uses the Otterbox products and that is the only factory defect we have had, which, to me, makes it an understandable, random bad egg not a consistent pattern of defect.Pros-The case did an incredible job of protecting my phone. I am a klutz, and I dropped my phone...a lot... and my phone was safe and sound.-The pink plastic case is much more attractive than some other case colors I have seen, and this style Otterbox comes with better color combos than the Defender.-For the amount of protection given, it did not add much bulk. I'm not one of those people who wants protection for my phone and then complains it's no longer as skinny as the iPhone is on its own. That's ridiculous. It was a reasonable compromise on bulk for protection. Still slips into my pocket (and I'm a woman).-The camera works perfectly with the case onCons-The white becomes FILTHY very quickly. I clean my case frequently, and am a hygienic person, but no matter what I did the white became a very gross gray. I would NOT suggest this color combo when purchasing this item. The pink case itself is wonderful (LOVE the color), but the white becomes unattractive VERY quickly, and I could not ever get it to clean up back to white. It was especially embarrassing to have it look so dirty during business meetings, etc.I just switched from this case, as I dropped it so many times my case has fragmented and cracked to an unusable point -- but my phone didn't get damaged during any of those falls and it took a year of me (and my pets) knocking it to the floor (and constantly having to take it out of the case to put it in my music player dock) for it finally cry uncle. I don't think that's the fault of Otterbox, I think that means Otterbox did its job. A year of protecting my phone from me! I have now purchased and am using the Defender, since I apparently am in need of full blown body armor on my phone.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Blue/Lime Green

reviewText: Bought and Otterbox Defender series case for my iPhone 5, and got this Communter Series for my partner's iPhone 5.  The fit and quality just isn't the same.... sorry to say.  This is the first time I've gone with the Communter Series, having always used the Otterbox Defender Series cases for my iPhone 3, then iPhone 3Gs, then my iPhone 4s.Problem #1: The screen protector was a pain to put on, and I've used these kinds of screen protectors on other devices before.  I think it was just a hair too big, so when you put the silicon liner on the phone, it would lift the one edge of the screen protector, creating a bubble.  Moved the screen protector over a smidge, and the other side began to lift.  In the end, I just dumped the screen protector in frustration.Problem #2: The silicon liner is NOT a perfect fit.  The edges don't come up around the front glass quite right, so the edges are always curled or not straight.... When you put the hard shell on, it protects the phone quite nicely.... not as well as the Defender series case, but then, this one is not meant to be as thick a case.  So the really annoying part is the two flaps at the bottom of the case, that cover the headphone jack and the charging port, are not long enough to cover the whole port, and so you cannot close them.  I've pulled on them to try to stretch them to reach the grove in the case top where they are supposed to latch, but after a while, they are half open again.  I'm of the mind to just cut them off.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Blue/Lime Green

reviewText: This is a great case.  Rugged enough to protect my wife's iphone 5, but not so big and bulky that the phone becomes a huge brick.This is not a slim case.  If you love how thin the ip5 is, this will make it MUCH thicker - maybe double the thickness.  There is a huge ridge around the front of the screen which adds a lot of depth - but also makes the phone a lot easier to hold.There is an included sticky screen protector, but I already had a Zagg installed, so she is still using that.All functions are still available.  The button on top is a bit had to push.  The side buttons work much better.There is a flappy thing on the bottom to cover the lightning connector and another for the earphones.  She'll probably end up cutting off the lightning connector flap since it is really just in the way.  Since she doesn't use earphones, she'll probably leave that.  The protection offered by the flaps is negligible.I have no idea why the apple logo on the back is left open.  Very vain if you ask me.

reviewText: After reading all of the reviews, I decided to go ahead and get the Commuter series case vs. the Defender. This seller sold the real thing and I wonder if the people who had so many issues purchased from a legit seller. I've had this case for a couple of months now so I thought that it would be time to review.Pros:*Fits the iPhone 5 like a glove. There were no issues getting the case on and off the phone.*Unlike some of the reviews that I read, the buttons (lock phone, volume, etc) are not stiff at all. They had a little give to them which I expected from a great product. No stiffness like the other reviews that I read.*The covers for the earplug and charger cover well and do not muffle the sound of the speakers. After a couple of months using this, they are not loose and still fit into the grooves. I read some reviews that complained about this but I haven't come across this problem.*The case is durable and does not add bulkiness. I dropped the phone on a hard surface (not a long distance or on purpose) and it was fine. No chips to the case and it stayed white shockingly. In fact, the case is still white which is an added plus.*The shipping was fast and came way before the promised date.*The cut out hole for the camera is great and there is no blurriness in the photos or reflections from the side.*There is a cutout for the apple logo so you can still show off the shiny chrome colored apple.*It looks pleasing to the eyeReally if you want an honest seller with a great case this is the way to go. You can compare it to the OtterBox website and find the same thing.

reviewText: Personally I've always had good vibes with the Otterbox commuter series.  I had one on my Ipod, which held up great, and I had one on my Galaxy S3 that was massively great protection without all the bulk.  So I felt fairly good about my purchase of the Otterbox commuter case for my new Iphone 5S.  I purchased the color Punk, which comes with a hard outer shell in a light neon green color, and a soft rubberized inner lining that is dark blue in color. I immediately put my case on as soon as my phone came in, and it was a breeze putting it on.  All the ports are covered, such as the power button, volume keys, and the bottom audio jack as well as the lightning connector.  The only thing visible is the screen, the speaker, the little button above the volume keys, the camera, and there is a hole in the back so the Apple logo can appear through.  This also came with a screen protector, but I chose to purchase a separate one simply because the one that came with the Otterbox had large cutouts so some of the screen was unprotected around the earpiece/sensor, and home button.  Just as a little lagniappe the screen protector I bought had a back protector too, so I made sure to put this on so the logo area doesn't scratch up (brand was Spigen).  I see people had issues with pressing the power button, and mine is a little hard to press, but it isn't bad at all.  My Otterbox commuter case for my Ipod was way hard to press down, but over time it loosened up, and I'm guessing this will too.  The volume keys are very easy to press, and offer no resistance whatsoever.  The area housing the screen does have a small lip to it so you can put your phone screen first on a table, and the lip raises the device so the screen won't touch it.  All in all this is a nice light case, but I will say the protection does leave something to be desired.  The commuter case I got for my Galaxy was pretty darn impressive with hard plastic over the silicone lining that covered even the sides, whereas this case for the Iphone has more rubber than hard casing.  I'm afraid if it does drop from a sizable distance that it will definitely break my phone. Not something you want with an expensive device.  So currently I have the case on my phone to prevent it from scratches, and it does look great, but I think I'll try to find something else that has a little more drop worthy protection.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Blue/Lime Green

reviewText: My wife drops her phone a fair amount. With her 4S she had a soft Amazon Basics case that did great. Now with her new 5S she needed something that protected her phone yet wasn't too bulky. We think this OtterBox Commuter is the perfect compromise. Contrary to other reviews, we don't think this case bulky at all. Anything thinner or lighter I'd question its ability to protect the phone. This is a dual piece case, with a rubberized inner case that snaps inside a harder outside cover. There is a fairly robust lip that extends higher than the glass to protect the phone when laid or dropped on its face. In addition, there are two soft, thick flaps that cover the lightening socket and the headphone socket in order to help keep dust out.  Again, this is a rock solid, highly protective case without all the bulk you might get with other high protection cases. Oh, my wife LOVES the grey/green case. It looks great.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Blue/Lime Green

reviewText: I bought this case for around $23. About a month later the price was $12.99 so I returned the case (still unused) and planned to buy it again for cheaper. reviewText: I got the Otterbox Commuter for the iPhone 5 in glacier and overall I wasn't happy with it. The first case I had didnt fit too well (silicone layer didnt match up with the plastic shell and was jagged in certain areas) so I opted for a replacement. Amazon told me to keep the one that didnt fit all that well and they will send me a replacement right away. They overnighted me a new case but I noticed that one had the same issues, and was actually worse than the first one. I decided to cut my losses and I gave the cases away. Otterbox needs some better quality control, however, Amazons customer service is awesome!!Quality control issues aside, there were some things I liked and didn't like about the case. The case's plastic shell feels like a plastic cooler type of plastic so it is very slippery. Match the slipperiness with the fact the sleep/wake button takes some force to press, and you end up with a device that may just slip out of your hands every time you go to lock/unlock or turn the device off. The volume buttons and silent switch were easily accessible.  This case does add tons of bulk to the device, but not so much that it is unmanageable. The bulk of the case didnt actually bother me at all. I did like the protection it offered and the significant sized lip on the front of the case providing a great lay on the table design.Overall, if the hard shell matched up nicely with the silicone layer and the case wasn't so slippery, this would have been my new favorite case. With the combo of the case being slippery and the sleep/power button being harder to press, it was a disaster waiting to happen, and it wasn't going to happen to my phone. I think with the protection the case offers it would have been fine even if it did slip out of my hand 100 times but I would rather not take the unnecessary risk.

reviewText: Let me first open by saying that I DID NOT purchase this product through Amazon, but through the Otterbox website as the preorder was not yet available on Amazon at the time ordering. That being said, here is my take on the case. When first opening the box and looking at the case, it looks and feels like it is well constructed and uses high grade materials. However, it is somewhat bulkier than I expected it to be. After putting the case on the phone (I did not apply the screen protector as I will be using a wet application type) these were my initial observations:-The inner silicon layer (before adding the hard shell) is a tight fit and the buttons appear line up just right as well as the port covers on the bottom.-The lip around the edge is of the screen is extremely pronounced. Not enough to hinder usage, but enough to make you wonder why they didn't take it down at least a tad. It does look like it will come over the edge far enough not to obstruct a screen protector if one is applied.-The hard plastic cover fits very snug over the silicon layer and lines up just right with the buttons and port flaps.-Volume buttons are just firm enough and have a very nice "click" feel to them, but the power is button takes noticeably more exertion to press.-There is very slight bulge at the corners on the silicon layer when hard case is on, not enough to detour the overall protection though.-Port flaps stay tucked into the plastic case.-Just dropping the phone about a foot or two above my table gives the impression this phone is EXTREMELY protected.I have now had the case on for over a week with regular usage and these are a few things I would add:-The power button is much easier to press now, I assume this is due the silicon softening up a bit.-The port flaps are still staying tucked in nicely, but I am thinking once I purchase the adapter, these flaps will be a bit hinder-some.-The slight bulge of the silicon layer at the corners, oddly enough, seems a little less now.-While there is still a good seal between the screen and the lip of the case, a LOT of dust and lint gathers around the lip, though it's hard to blame Otterbox for this.I think it would have been to Otterbox's benefit to consider using a TPU inner layer as opposed to silicon, it stays much cleaner, though I realize this would make the port flaps harder to work with. Having now seen someone with the iPhone 5  Defender case, I understand how progression-wise the Commuter is the "sleeker" version, because it definitely is less bulky. However, my main reason for only giving this case four stars is because I feel the size of the lip could have been reduced which would have thus resulted in a slimmer case just as equally protective.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Blue/Lime Green

reviewText: I asked the salesman not to remove my new iPhone from the packaging because I didn't ANYONE touching my phone before I protected every angle of it. As a carpenter, dog lover and constant outdoors person, this is the ideal type of protection for my iPhone but.. it interferes with my fingers and the bigger iPH5 is now huge.I really liked the 'Commuter' series for the iPhone 3G. That, like this one, was softer rubber bumper with a clip on hard outer. ..but it was much more sleek.I'm not knocking this cover. It is all I'll need for the rougher times. It seems well suited for a drop and sticks out far enough above the LCD as to protect the front. I believe this is a good cover, that comes with a screen-protector also. It's professional, big-name and pretty good, just not for everyday - too much for gently people - too much for the rare what-if - but just right for my job site, when I'm working outdoors or when I plan on being rough for a bit and bringing the phone.I took away one star for the large bulk for a 'commuter' series protection. I wish the iPhone was still rounded like the 3GS, those covers were smoooooth.-Buy one if you need the protection, otherwise a gel TPU cover for a few bucks is a better deal and likely all I'll need for day-to-day use.

reviewText: After having a Reflex on my iPhone 4 for over a year, the only logical decision for my iPhone 5 was to continue using one. Thankfully, OtterBox has delivered another great product. In form and function both, the Reflex is everything you could possibly want in an iPhone protective case. (Having dropped my iPhone 4 on concrete a few times in its case, there were no scratches or blemishes when I traded it in for my 5, which allowed for an amazing buy-back amount from the carrier.)The fit is extremely tight, and I have not experienced any of the slipping or case-unexpectedly-coming-apart as other reviewers have. OtterBox has improved the design over the previous model, and the silicone border over the front allows for easy on/off without destroying the screen protector like the 4/4S did.The headphone jack outlet could be a little wider to accommodate some larger headphone jacks (my L-shaped connector worked just fine), but I can't take points off when I have no problem accessing the jack or the Lightning outlet with OEM material.As with other reviewers, I originally found the volume buttons and sleep button to be difficult to depress, but if you work those and break them in a little before installation, they should be easier to use once on your iPhone. The depth of the case at the ringer/silent toggle is deep, but not too deep or prohibitive to switch modes if you have any length of fingernail.Overall, it's as close to perfect as a case can be, and I'll continue to use and recommend OtterBox for future protective case needs.**UPDATE**This case stayed together for about six months, until the bottom bottom portion cracked at the headphone jack. As it kept bothering me, I finally cut off the entire bottom front guard until I got on here and purchased a Spigen Tough Armor. Spigen has now replaced OtterBox as my go-to case brand.
title: OtterBox Reflex Series Case for iPhone 5 & 5S - Retail Packaging - Translucent Green/Blue

reviewText: This case just showed up today for my iphone 5 and man am I impressed.  I didn't know these existed, no one carries them locally, but they should.  For me finding the perfect phone case is difficult, while I want to have a reasonable amount of protection for my phone I don't want to add bulk to it because whats the point of buying a sleek new phone if you just wrap it in a bulky case.I have bought an Otterbox Commuter for my last 2 phones.  On my Evo it lasted a while but that was a bulky phone already.  On my iphone 5 I ditched it after a few days because the lip around the screen was too tall and made typing harder.  I ended up getting a basic Belkin case which didn't offer much protection but it was better than nothing.  I have found that I like the slider type cases because they are hard shelled but don't add too much bulk.  The Belkin case also didn't allow docking the phone in my alarm clock with the lightning adapter.This is the best of those type of cases by far because it has a little bit of rubber around the phone for a little added shock protection and its stylish.  I also was thinking to dock it I would just have to remove the bottom half of the case but as it turns out it docks with the lightning adapter perfectly without removing anything!The only downside I have found with this case is that I bought the Vapor edition which has a semi transparent back.  Like the picture it has the Otterbox logo and a box looking thing which one would thing is to tell you where to push to disengage the two pieces but in fact you push the other side so I can't figure out what its purpose is.  But in addition it has a bunch of other markings like 4 patent logos, made in china, and [...]. With all of that it really defeats the purpose of having a semi transparent backing because it all totally blocks the back of the phone.  I'd be fine with only name like in the picture but wish the rest wasn't there.
title: OtterBox Reflex Series Case for iPhone 5 & 5S - Retail Packaging - Translucent Green/Blue

reviewText: I've been using this case for about two weeks, and really enjoy the relative slimness and sturdiness of the case. I wanted something that was not too bulky and could easily be removed for docking. This case meets both of those needs perfectly. There are, however, a couple of drawbacks that some users may be able to overlook; others perhaps not:-While the case easily slides on and off of the phone, the two halves often separate during normal usage. That's not to say that the case would pop off if dropped, but rather when taking it in and out of my pocket it will separate a bit and I have to push the halves back together. There is no "click" when the halves are joined around the phone.-Some users her have complained about how the volume and home buttons are hard to press through the case. This is true for the volume buttons; the home button is not hard to press as long as the top half of the case is firmly against the top half of the phone. This relates back to my first point where the case can sometimes become dislodged during normal usage.-To address another point regarding the area around the lightning port and speakers: this part of the plastic does seem a bit thin and I could see how it would break easily if dropped directly on this location or if it catches on something.-Lastly, a note about the screen protector. There is a little tab glued to the protector that allows you to hold it while you apply. Amazingly, this tab is attached to the protector using that annoying glue that does not peel right off (think of a price sticker that leaves the white backing when you try to peel it off). I was floored by this, but with some goo-gone I was able to get the reside off.Bottom line, I feel comfortable that this case would protect my phone against a drop, but consider another product if you prefer firm and tight cases that don't budge during normal usage. I also think that all things considered, it is a bit overpriced. It seems that you're paying more for the OtterBox name than anything else.
title: OtterBox Reflex Series Case for iPhone 5 & 5S - Retail Packaging - Translucent Green/Blue

reviewText: Thought Otterbox was high quality. This is my second Otterbox case and they are all not good, especially considering the price. reviewText: I'm a huge fan of Otter Box and have used thier Commuter line on an older Razr and iPhones. reviewText: I definitely like this case over the Defender also offered by OtterBox, as it's way too bulky. reviewText: I odered this to project my Motorola RAZR MAXX HD - 16GB.  Problem is that Motorola has different camerea/connection layout for 32GB vs 16GB phones for this model listing.This listing does differentiate between the two and i did not catch it in the picks as I was not looking at it in that great of detail.  The 32GB has the camera more in the center top of the phone where as the 16GB has it in the upper left most corner.Be careful and utilize pics to validate case alignment to phone.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Motorola RAZR MAXX HD - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: I explicitly waited for this case to become available and I am very sorry. If your primary concern is to protect from drop damage then the case is spectacular, as would be expected from Otterbox. But in all other areas I expect better for this price.My main problem is that the wraparound edge on the screen side is too deep and instrusive. Some overall bulk was expected but I can't help feeling that this is just an innefficient design flaw. I have a hard time using the touchscreen around the edges. I almost need a stylus now. It also seems unnecessarily bulky on the front, adding a 3mm lip all the way around the screen. That alone increases the total depth of the phone by 33%. Add another 3-4mm on the back (the case tapers slightly from top to bottom on the back) and the phone has almost doubled in size. And this is the commuter version. I shudder to think about how massive the Defender series might be.Another advertised feature is the dust protection. This is half true. The headphone jack has a cover flap and the side buttons are covered but there is no protection at all for the USB or HDMI slots. I really don't understand why not. I thought, "Maybe it was intentional so you could use the motorola car dock?". Nope, it doesn't fit in the dock anyway.The case also comes with a screen scratch protector... but it is not specific to the RAZR MAXX HD. In fact, it really only cover the touchscreen area but leaves small gaps on the sides and large gaps at the top and bottom. The screen protector does not have any overlap with the case itself. The spaces inbetween have become dust magnets within a day. The plastic used also seemingly magnifies and highlights fingerprints making them much more noticeable requiring me to clean the screen almost obsessively. Why, after spending upwards of $40 do I need to then re-shop for a screen protector that covers the entire glass surface?The cutouts for speaker, camera, and microphone are spot on. Other than the size, the asthetics are also well done.The decision to return this thing was solidified when after installing the case, someone asked me, "What happened to your new phone?" thinking I had lost it and had reverted to an old blocky phone from 4 years ago.It will protect your phone from drops but I can't name another redeeming quality.  Also, I had a terrible time ordering this directly from otterbox and then also in returning it. If you are going to try it out, I would buy it here on amazon or from another retailer instead of direct from otterbox.Update 12/18/12:  for those looking for a smaller profile protection, I am really very happy with the Diztronic case:Diztronic Matte Back Black Flexible TPU Case for Motorola Droid Razr Maxx HD [ONLY FOR MAXX HD MODEL] (Verizon) [Retail Packaging] and a skinomi screen protectorSkinomi TechSkin - Motorola Droid RAZR MAXX HD Screen Protector Ultra Clear Shield + Lifetime Warranty

reviewText: I bought this for my wife's phone because she had dropped her previous phone and shattered the screen. I don't see any way to effectively glue it back in, and the 2 halves are starting to come apart now without depressing the little latch, too, so it's pretty much done. My friend had one that he got rid of because the 2 halves wouldn't stay together after a few months, too.I've purchased LOTS of cases for phones (literally dozens) and I can say this is clearly not worth the money - there are other cases half the price or less that have similar quality and technically a better design.Skip this case unless the phone doesn't get moved much and you must have the Otterbox name.

reviewText: So this is my second commuter case, I previously had a Droid RAZR regular with the commuter and loved the case. There are some substantial differences between this case and that one.Before that let me say this... If anyone from Otter Box happens to read these reviews, I don't know what you guys were thinking but that stupid little remove after installation decal on the screen protector certainly didn't need the rubber cement adhesive you used on it. It almost destroyed the screen protector during removal and took like an hours work of thumb rubbing to get all the left over glue off. Horrible. Fix it.Difference 1:The "silicone" inner cover that everyone is familiar with the soft squishy semi sticky feel of silicone is no longer made of or at least no longer resembles silicone. Its something much harder a very firm rubber very much like the rubber of a car tire. So far this has been give or take for me, the good thing is that lint and pocket crud no longer clings to the case like it did on the old one, however I believe this may have reduced the shock absorbing properties of the case as it is much firmer rubber borderline plastic hard. It still has a decent amount of friction if you put it on a table face down like the last one did but not near as much. The outside of the case is unchanged.Difference 2:The port cover for the charger is gone... This may be important to some people but honestly that stupid flimsy rubber flap on my last case almost got cut off on multiple occasions it would always pop open in your pocket and you'd have to push it back into its hole every time you looked at your phone, You lost some I dunno "rain" protection for your ports however that is probably unnecessary as this phones charging/hdmi port is on the side now where the last phone had them on the top. The headphone jack is still on the top and has a much more functional very firm never comes undone cover on it still.Difference 3:Cool new colors, definitely a plus I got the pavement it looks so much better than just a black brick.Impressions...Well I don't like that the outer plastic case has an extremely thin section around the charging port I am sure it will be fine but it looks easily breakable.The harder plastic makes it harder to push the side buttons as well but you get used to it quickly it doesn't take away anything from the function.I really like the lack of pocket lint on the phone. Its a fair trade for the harder rubber.I personally like the lack of flap over the charging port. I still fits and works in the lapdock 100 as well.Cover doesn't interfere with any functions of the phone.4 stars because screen protector made me want to fight people during install and I would like to see more colors available for such a popular phone. I get tired of standing in line at the coffee stand with 2 people in front of me and one behind with the same exact phone and case.-------------------------------------------------------------Review after a couple weeks usage... 2 Stars.The colored "rubber" case or whatever the inner part is made of now, it no longer appears to be silicone... Collects dirt and grease and disgusting crud like it was meant to I have to put my otterbox in the dishwasher every 3 days as it turns brown and looks like I used it to wipe after that amount of time... I never had this problem with my old silicone black one on the razr regular. The extremely thin bar of plastic near the charging port that I mentioned, while it hasn't broken YET, I hate it, it flexes constantly and makes you nervous that you will break it, and the big cut out around the charging/hdmi ports really throws the lines of the phone off and makes a beautiful phone ugly. This case is also noticeably thicker than my razr regulars commuter seemed to be. The included screen protector is a joke gets scratched up in a week ordered a skinomi screen protector that's working great for me. The bottom of the phone near the mouth piece has a sort of skeletal construction built into the rubber inner sleeve that while offering excellent protection makes the case seem ill fitting and sloppy near the bottom.Bottom line the only improvement on this case over the old commuter is the headphone port cover the rest of it is a joke and may have ruined the company for me which I once swore by.If you must buy it get the all black one or you will hate life, I would also recommend the defender if you must have an otterbox for your razr hd while it may be larger it fits and looks better, I am switching over to the driztronic TPU case I have geeksquad insurace against any actual damage the phone is going to incur anyway and the TPU will save it from cosmetic stuff.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Motorola RAZR HD - Retail Packaging - Black

Stuff like sand or larger stuff could get in there and scratch the screen I guess...-Not water-tight/water-proof)Overall the is probably the best case for the Galaxy Note 2 you will find (especially for the price).

reviewText: I had an OtterBox for my old phone, an HTC Incredible, and it performed greatly beyond expectations with drops, bumps, and impacts. Maybe the design for the Galaxy Note 2 is just a poor one for this case since on the first drop of the phone it not only cracked the screen (slightly) but also fried the internals of the device rendering it un-usable.I had been rather careful since it was such a large screen I wanted to make sure it was safe, I went with the larger OtterBox thinking it would be better protection against falls. I was getting out of a Honda Civic when the phone fell from my lap, maybe 2 feet, and the impact rendered it useless. I think maybe if I had dropped it previous times it would be reason for it to die but not on the first drop, very very disappointing since I carried around this huge case for seemingly nothing. I would have been better off with the "commuter" case since it's slightly smaller and the benefit of the larger case is not impact protection (apparently).I would give this product a 1 star review for the fact that the first drop killed my phone and for how annoying the dirt and dust problem is, but having an OtterBox before makes me think that the design for this phone just isn't as top-notch as the others and I do still trust the brand. I would regrettably like a refund or even an offer to exchange for a commuter case since I don't see the point in having such an enormous case if not to protect from short falls. maybe I just got a defective case that was a MM off or something and that caused my Note to rattle it's brains out, maybe not. All I know is that I have dropped phones WITHOUT cases from that height and they have worked fine for years to come.

reviewText: * Four updates below:This is a nice case that will very likely protect my phone and its screen.  I will continue to use it despite its flaws because there is nothing that comes close.If you are familiar with the OtterBox Defender series, this case holds few surprises.  This is my first and other reviews point out some things to think about.If you are not familiar, then you should know you are buying a hardshell case with a slight foam panel inside to help protect your phone in the event of a fall. On top of that shell snaps a screen protector that has a cut-out for the home button. Make sure your screen is clean and that the protector is clean on both sides before putting it on because it is somewhat hard to remove the top. It is this piece that is the most objectionable part of the entire case.  The hole for the home button simply extends the faulty design choice Samsung made when they included the button.  I'm not sure OtterBox had very many real choices on how to deal with the button, so I don't blame them for the hole in the screen protector.  The protector does not lay flat on your screen, but that air gap has yet to cause me any real issues.  The largest problem with it though is that it isn't very clear.  I used lens cleaning wipes on it hoping that it would be better, and it was--slightly.  The result isn't real bad but as others have pointed out, if you are picky about such things--and you deserve to be at this price--this will disappoint you.(* Update:  The s pen can leave scratches or trails on the plastic and it does seem to affect some touch sensitivity.  This coupled with making my screen harder to see in sunlight prompted me to remove the screen protector. If you press carefully along its edge, you can remove it as well as its adhesive.  A normal screen protector will replace it.)The next piece to the case is a soft shell cover that gives it some grip.  The total affect at this point doesn't give you as much bulk as you might expect, but it does increase the bulk considerably.  It will not fit in the Samsung dock with this case in place.  The soft shell has those bothersome dust covers for the power and headphone ports, a pair of scissors will remove them easily if they bother you.  Yes, you might get some dust in them, but they will be no worse than the external speaker.  One reviewer mentioned an echo while using the soft case and I cannot see how such an echo is possible considering the location of the microphone.  Either way, I have not gotten any reports of an echo yet.Lastly you get a belt clip holster that is one of the most secure designs I've seen for such a holster.  It doubles as a stand by opening the clip all the way until it clicks.  The piece of plastic that it clips to though has sharp corners that can dig into you uncomfortably and I an concerned that it may wear a hole in my dress shirts.  I've tried sanding the corners with some slight benefit.(* Update:  The piece of plastic mentioned above broke within three months of ownership.  It broke while lifting it to close the belt-clip--in other words, it broke during normal operations in three months. The case and holster are still functional, but three months takes product quality into the one-star range.  I'll leave it at two stars because its main function is to protect the phone, but breakage this early is inexcusable.)(* Update again: Shortly after writing that last update the top part of the hard shell broke (tore slightly actually) as I was trying to remove it.  While it still works, product quality can no longer be excused by saying that it still protects the phone.)(* Final update:  The belt clip broke making mine a pocket phone.  That makes its useful life somewhere around 8 months.  Mine did not have a rough life. I will not buy another. The case BTW is still usable except that as a pocket phone the case is too bulky.)In spite of my low rating, this case can only be sold at this price because it is in a category by itself.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: Lots has been written about OtterBox cases... and I find that people either like them, hate them, or over expect something about this case... bottom line... IMO, this is a strong case. Yes the over protection does change the nature of how my touch screen works on the Note II as well as the general hand and finger operation of the phone itself. The tactical feel of the screen is different (after all there is another layer of plastic on top- why would I expect it to be the same?). The important point here, is that this tick heavy case has a purpose in that when the need calls for layers of protection- this is the case to have at hand!.The case fit is very good- and for a big phone like the Samsung Galaxy Note II... that's a selling point all to itself as other case manufactures try to make their cases just a bit bigger to try to fit this phone. The only ding I would give this case is difficulty at times getting it apart either to mount the phone in the case or to remove it... it does indeed take a few minutes to get the phone in or out the Otter :) But, that's not really a major ding.So, why not a 5-star? Well, it has to do with (and keep in mind... THIS IS MY OPINION...) the ports around the phone that are not really covered... Now, I'm not expecting water-proof... water-tight... completely sealed from the atmo case here... nope, not at all (there are other cases for the deep under-sea dive). But, lets talk dust and lint particles... the areas around the case that are open to the outside, as I count them, there are five... the two microphone ports- top and bottom, camera lens and flash, stylus port, and the rear speaker port. Now I understand the design need to make these ports uncovered, of course. The ding is not about that, but rather that the openings in the case are recessed to the point that I suspect long term the phone being in this case you would see the crud collect in these areas. That's not what I would expect for a case that states to be "particle" and "dust" resistant... these recessed holes are weak  points in that effort. I'm sure that with regular phone un-mounting and cleaning you could manage the "crud" from collecting in these port caverns, it's something to be aware of - as you mis-treat your phone in less than clean environments.So, that's what I know...
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: I have had this case for roughly one month.The Pros:It's sturdy, durable and very tough (already dropped the phone twice with absolutely no damage to the device or case)The case does make the phone SLIGHTLY bigger. Not by much though. It does a great job at leaving as much of the front of the phone as open as possible while still keeping a tight grip on the device. The opening for the S Pen is big enough to slip it right out with no problem. (Other cases had a very small opening not much bigger than the S Pen itself making it difficult to get it out). The belt case is very large so it can accommodate the phone which for me is no problem however, I can see it might be a problem for some people. Belt clip doubles as a viewing stand. Awesome. There is a hole in the case on the back of the phone for the phone's built in speaker. This case does NOT hinder the sound quality coming from the phone in any way shape or form.The Cons:This case like all other ones made of rubber synthetic material does collect dust over time in between the case and the phone itself. The outer rubber housing of the case comes off easily and without difficulty however, the inner hard plastic layer that actually come into contact with the phone holds on for dear life to the device as if it was never meant to come off. This is a good thing until you try to take it apart to clean the dirt/dust out of the inside of the case. Takes some time but it does come off as long as you are careful. The built in screen protector is for lack of a better word GARBAGE. The phone has a lot of trouble picking up where the S Pen is over the screen and when browsing the web with the S Pen the phone can't always tell what you have touched. This is probably because the built in screen protector doesn't actually touch the screen. Instead it kind of hovers over it giving you a rebound when you touch it with your fingers. BUT there is good news on the horizon. The built in screen protector comes out. You can then use your own screen protector with this case.Now for some important info. I am not one to drop my phone. I can't afford another one if I break it hence me buying this case. I have dropped my Note 2 TWICE and both times were when I was trying to slip the phone into the belt clip without directly looking at it. My brain told me the phone was in the belt clip and it wasn't and slipped out when I let got of it with my hand. You'll hear a very distinct clicking noise when it snaps into the belt clip. Just make sure it's in the belt clip before you take offOver all this is a GREAT case for the Note 2. I highly recommend it. Only reason it doesn't get 5 stars is because of the crap built in screen protector, Well played Otterbox, Well played indeed
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: After reading many reviews on the OtterBox cases, I initially ordered an OtterBox Commuter because a lot people were complaining about the Defender's added bulk and the screen protector getting dusty.The OtterBox Commuter is an excellent case, no question about it. But for me, there was one problem: the Galaxy Note 2 in an OtterBox Commuter is still too big to fit comfortably in your pocket. In fact, you're going to eventually wear a hole in most pants if you keep your Galaxy Note 2 Commuter in your pocket all day (the corners of the case rub and stretch the fabric when you're sitting down, and digging the phone in and out of your pocket all day puts stress on the pocket seams as well).So I ordered an OtterBox Defender to try out. Having used both, I prefer the OtterBox Defender over the Commuter. The Defender's outer shell has a nicer grip that feels better and more secure in your hand. The built-in screen protector has not been an issue (I was worried about it after reading some other people's reviews, but so far I have no complaints about dust or its usability). And the Defender's belt clip allows you to wear the phone on your belt instead of in your pocket. Granted, phone belt clips are not ideal but it's better than ruining your expensive dress work pants. Also, the Defender belt clip is very high quality and it positions the phone flat against your side so it's not that bad looking.In terms of added bulk, the Defender is really not much larger than the Commuter (certainly less of a difference than I was expecting).Finally, the Defender does offer more rugged protection than the Commuter - although the Commuter is probably more than adequate protection for most normal situations.Overall, I really like the OtterBox Defender case and am very happy with it.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: I've had OtterBox Defender cases for my last three Smartphones, and I am a fan.  However, I am slightly disappointed in this latest case for my new Galaxy Note 2.The fact that the GN2 has a hardware HOME button and softkeys for BACK and MENU on either side requires that the transparent screen protector portion of this case be die-cut to allow for operation of the HOME key. Unfortunately, this die-cut opening is an entry point for dust and debris.  I am not a fan of these built-in protectors anyway; they reduce both screen fidelity and sensitivity, finger motions drag on this surface, and they smudge much more readily than a bare screen, even more readily than high-quality adhesive protectors. I used the case for the first few days with the screen protector in place to see if my previous complaints were no longer valid, and found that I couldn't WAIT to get rid of it on this case. It's easy to remove, but OtterBox may void your warranty if you do it. It's attached to the top part of the case with a fine bead of the stretchy sort of adhesive that you can roll up if any remains in place on the top part of the case. In my experience, it separated cleanly with all of the adhesive remaining attached to the clear protector. You carefully apply increasing pressure at one point on the edge of the protector until it begins to pull away from the rest of the case, and then work it around the entire edge until it falls free. I understand that in an industrial environment, the reduced screen fidelity, additional surface glare, and reduced sensitivity might be an acceptable trade-off for the protection. For me, that's not the case, so I removed it.Removing the screen protector left me with two more minor complaints. The rubber exterior sleeve that pulls on over the hard interior parts of the case is quite hard. When I broke the last belt clip on my previous phone, I purchased a Seidio Active case for it, and I much prefer that slightly softer, tackier rubber material to this harder OtterBox material. I'm sure that this OtterBox material is very durable, and the fit (openings) for camera, stylus, speaker and ports is perfect, but this harder material slides more easily on smooth surfaces...it's just not as grippy in the hand, either. Also, it is a stiffer material, making the right-side activation button and the left-side volume buttons quite difficult to press. Getting them to detent actually makes the case creak a little where the two halves are joined.All that said, this is a tough, high-quality case that will take a great deal of punishment. It does add bulk, but I actually like that. On a phone as large as the GN2, a little extra thickness is no big deal. Taking care to protect the Gorilla Glass screen, I'm confident that the rest of the phone is very well protected by the Defender case. I would have given 3.5 stars if I could have.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: I'm very pleased with this case. It fits the Samsung Galaxy Note II perfectly and doesn't detract from any functions of the phone. I like the protection of this case, makes me not worry so much about dropping the phone. I did purchase a Spigen SGP ultra clear screen protector. I am seriously considering removing the built-in screen protector and applying the Spigen. Zagg HD is also a great option if you can deal with its wet installation technique and the possible bubbles. You would think that Otterbox would address the numerous complaints that users have about the Defender built-in screen protector. Read all the negative reviews about so many people removing this ill-fitting thing and applying their own screen protection.  Maybe you should remove this annoying garbage from your Defender cases and include a excellent separate screen protector. Are you listening OTTERBOX? I don't think so, because you always include the same built-in garbage. I have been removing these things from other Defender cases like the one I had for my Droid Razr.  The thing is I don't like having to pay so much money for a case and then have to proceed to rip it apart. The case protection the Otterbox Defender gives is unbeatable. The built-in screen protector should be scratched completely from the design of this case. Then, OTTERBOX, include a decent separate screen protector and keep your high price point or no screen protector and lower your price. I highly recommend this case, but I am sick and tired of the annoyance and necessary modding of the built-in screen protector. You would think that a company with such a great reputation would be listening to its buyers and responding to their complaints, especially when such a majority have a problem with a flawed design.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: I purchased this case to help protect the screen of my Galaxy Note 2 (given that I dropped my first one and the screen cracked...).  PRIME shipping was great.PROS:Product fits the phone VERY WELL.  All necessary ports available and protected.Does not add too much heft to my phone.  The Note 2 is a big phone.  This case is no bigger than the Seido case I am replacing.  The Seido case was very good too but no screen protection and putting films on without all the bubbles was just a waste of money.Phone clips very securely to the Holster.  (that's how my first note broke, it was not secure in the holster and popped out when I got out of my truck).Looks very good.Good grip with the rubber sheath.CONS:Make sure your phone is CLEAN before putting the screen cover on.  Otherwise you'll see every speck of dust or hair.  Use a lint free cloth to clean both the phone and the case.My screen has a manufacturing defect in the center of the screen, about  1 inch below the top edge.  Very annoying.  I have sent an email to Otterbox and we will see how their RMA process works.  I will post more at a later date.Summary:Good case, looks like it will protect well.  Price I paid was not out of line with other good name-brand cases.  I'd buy again **Depending on how they handle my issue with the screen.04/18/2013 - Follow Up:The Otterbox review process has you sending some detailed pictures to the company specifically pointing out the manufacturing flaw.  Once I did this they way they wanted it to be done, the company sent me a replacement case that had no imperfections in the screen cover.  From a customer service perspective, 5 STARS.  However, my overall rating stands because i have to periodically take the unit apart to clean out behind the screen.  I would buy again because I have dropped this phone a couple of times now and no issues and nary a scuff on the Defender case.Thanks for reading.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: This is the 3rd case I've tried (after the Samsung flip case and a Ballistic case) and this is the one I'll be using.It's sturdy and the rubber outside casing feels good in my hands. This was my problem with the Ballistic case: the inner silicone cover was catching on the edge of the screen protector and separating it from the screen. This is not an issue at all with this case. (I removed the built in screen protector because I already had a Zagg protector. I just ripped it off, the glue and protector came off easily.)The belt case stands up on a desk, so I use it at work as a stand. I don't wear the belt clip, though.This case is big but if you have the Note 2 size probably isn't an issue for you. I keep mine in my purse and I like that the Defender case makes it easier to find my phone by feel.The only con is that it isn't quick and practical to remove the case so I can no longer use my Samsung dock, but that is my only issue with this case.

reviewText: The "holster" portion has broken twice. They replaced it the first time, I have not attempted to get it replaced a second time. So, it lets a bunch of dust under and makes the screen tough to see. It's like a dust magnet under there. Due to this, I take it apart probably 2 - 3 times a day to clean it so I can see the screen. After about 3 weeks of that, several of the clips that hold the case together have either warn down or broken off. This of course creates more of a gap at the screen which allows even more dust inside. I do not recommend this. I have purchased cases for $10 or less with similar issues but thought I would go ahead and spend the money, and hoped to not have to purchase anymore cases, but this case has the exact same problems all of the other inexpensive cases have.

reviewText: So, I wanted the Glacier color and none of the Sprint stores within a 2hr radius of where I lived had it, none of the local retail stores carried this color and I wanted this color since my Note2 was white. There was no bunching or bulging in any areas, and the entire outer casing fit smoothly.The thickness added by the case is about 1", maybe a tiny bit less, but that's to be expected with an Otterbox. The covers for the charging and headphone ports are a little stiff to open and replace but again, not a very big issue. I would rather them be stiff and prevent debris from entering than not. reviewText: You can drop it, scratch it or bump it but your phone will probably still be OK. Everytime  i get a new phone, i make sure i buy a new case to cover it and keep it safe. I work a job that requires a lot of physical labour and i'm always bumping into things, dropping my phone on hard surfaces. It doesn't help that i'm an inherently klutzy person. I wear Khaki's with huge pockets, so i never use the holster. But it does bulk your phone up quite a bit, i'm a big man so i've got big hands. It might make an already large phone even harder to deal with for those with smaller hands. If you're not incredibly klutzy or do alot of physical work where it may get bumped, i'd suggest a smaller case. To me, it's worth the size to protect this expensive phone. I don't believe in contracts, so i paid for my phone full price and outright.It comes in two layers. First, a hard cover is snapped over the phone where the phone fits snuggly. then a rubber covering is placed over the hard cover to protect the back of the phone and more importantly, the corners.Pros:- Protects the phone, very, very well.- Scratch protector prevents scratches effectively.- Has built-in coverings for the ports, Mini-USB and the earphone jack. providing tons of extra protection for your phone yet providing easy access.- Will probably save you 100's down the the road when you want to resell it for a new one and protects it so that you don't break it prematurely.- Doesn't effect vioce quality, sound quality or the ability to use the flash or camera. There is an opening for the stylus pen, that makes it easily accessible but provides extraordinary protection for it.Cons:- The screen covering, the one that provides protection from scratches, is loose. so there is a small but noticable space between the screen protector and the screen. This may annoy some. I've learned to ignore it. Though it can be removed if necessary with steam if a really irritant.- increases the size of the phone dramatically, which may make it unwieldy to many users. more so than it already is.- There is a hole for the home button. Dirt, grime and dust likes to be sucked through this hole into the small space between the screen protector and the screen. making frequent cleaning a necessity. It appears to me that pushing on the rubber-like screen protector with that hole there seems to create a suction that forces tons of junk into that small area over a period of time.Overall:Great, worth the price with a long-term pay off. I'd only suggest it to those who intend to be dropping or bumping it alot, however.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: Arrived on time, package was intact and undamaged. reviewText: This is a sturdy case with rubber skin layer around the phone and an external hard shell that covers the rubber layer. It's pretty easy to remove and put back on the phone.  My phone was not charging so I had to replace the battery on the phone at least once a day and it's a quick 10 second job to do so. There's cut outs for the S-Pen, ear phone, Mics, speaker, and camera flash.  S-Pen comes thru the cut out without any problem.PRO: durable and sturdy.cut outs are done properly.CON: Price was could be lower.  A friend showed me a similarly constructed case that he bought for $12.liquid spill can slip down and gets trapped in the rubbery layer, which then seeps thru the back cover of the phone and gets inside the phone. Which is what happen to my phone that caused it to not charge anymore.  So make sure to take the phone out and check for liquid trapped in the rubber layer if you spill any liquid on the phone.overall I think it's a good buy.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: Ok I bought this case because the screen is expensive to replace on this phone and the skin case I was using didn't offer enough protection.  The Defender case was too big so I ordered this one instead.  Also, I don't like the gel exterior of the Defender case, this one has a plastic exterior that should feel better going in and out of my pocket.  I was also excited that this case came with a screen protector.So here is my opinion.  The gel rubber interior part of this case is much harder than I was expecting.  The plastic outer skin looks and feels very cheap.  Also the outer plastic shell is super super slippery.  My last case was plastic, but it still had some grip to it, not enough to resist going into my pocket though.  This case is super slippery.  The plastic shell and the inner layers don't really fit together perfectly, its just a thing I notice, no one else probably would.  Also, this case is MASSIVE!  It is basically the same size as the Defender case, its about 2-2.5 times thicker than the phone, you can definitely see it bulging in your pocket.  My old case was slim and you could not see it in my pocket clearly.  It doesn't seem to really protect the ports.  This case has annoying covers that protect the ports, however water or debris can easily get to the ports through the lip on the screen.  Up by the headphone jack, the lip actually is cut away allowing even more to get by and into the port area.  I'm not sure why it is designed that way.  The top and bottom mic, S-Pen area, camera & flash have absolutely no liquid protection.  However they are set deep within the case to they are safe from falls.  The rubber push button parts build into the rubber are nice and feel good and responsive when you press them.  Also randomly, my phone's speaker seems to be much louder in this case over my last case, and both had cut outs???  This case is in no way attractive, it seems to look a little worse in real life than the pics of it look, IMHO.I understand that this case offers superior fall protection, and that is thanks partly to its bulk.  However... This is not a Defender case, in my opinion this one should be designed to be more slim and pocket-able.  Whatever.  And the exterior plastic shell just feels cheap in your hands.I love the plastic screen protector that came with the case.  Its fits perfectly and was super easy to install.  I bought a invisibleSHIELD screen cover recently and immediately hated it, and returned it.  This one is great!  I got a couple small fibers stuck to it, but its my fault.  It feels nice to the finger too, and I hate screen protectors as a rule, but this is alright.  This case feels very solid.  The Defender case for the iPhone 4/4s has that crappy outer later they isn't really connected and feels like trash, gets torn up... This case is solid and does not have any silly loose layer or anything.  The covers for the headphone port and charging port were difficult to open at first, but now they are easier, and I like how they feel.If you need uber protection then I recommend this case or the defender case.  If you hate the feel of a rubber cover going in and out of your pocket then get this case.  However, if you want something less bulky look elsewhere.  I will use this over the next few weeks and update my review if I feel I need to.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black
