reviewText: Like a previous reviewer I had purchased the Defender series case for the NOTE II, but found that in doubling the device's footprint, it made an already big phone ginormous. I have a Commuter series case for my Galaxy S4 so I figured I would give one a try for the Note II.Case is the same as the Galaxy S4's case - a bit too plasticky and slippery (especially in comparison with the rubbery feel of the Defender series) for my tastes - but I knew that was what I was going to get, so no complaints there.My complaint is the too small screen protector. Yes, it protects the main area of the screen, but there is a 1/16-1/8 gap between where the screen ends and where the case starts around the entire edge of the screen. Within minutes I had accidentally peeled up a corner of the screen and - yup, you guessed it - dust got under the screen protector so it wouldn't re-adhere properly. Very disappointing and not all what I expected given my previous experiences with Otterbox (I've bought/used more than twenty Otterbox cases over the years for a number of various devices).3 stars - nice case, but substandard/poorly-designed screen protector knocks two stars off.

reviewText: People complain about the bulk and the size of the Otterbox Note 2 case.  I have watched people drop their unprotected Ipads and smart phones on the ground and crack that glass numerous times.  Do you hear them complain when they drop their phones or Ipads on the floor or on concrete and it doesn't have a dent or a scratch?  This case was made to protect your phone from exactly that.  If you want a cheaper made brand go for it.  Otterbox is the only brand I trust to protect my electronic devices.  Why?  Cause it has always outlasted all my toys.

reviewText: I got this to replace a Speck case that was an enclosure style of case.  I've owned other Otterbox cases on my iPhone so I was familiar with the brand.Right out of the box, the case fits the phone nicely.  The power port and headset port covers work nicely.  Additionally, the corners are well shielded so that the phone can take a drop or two.  I should know as I have dropped it and been lucky thus far.The screen is protected by a rather high bezel so that you can put the phone flat without any concerns about scratching the ginormous screen.  That's a real plus.Lastly, I feel that it adds enough protection without being overly bulky.  I keep my phone in a cargo shorts pocket almost 90% of the time and I don't have any trouble getting the phone in or out (because of the case).  I do have trouble sometimes because the phone is huge, but that's not the fault of the case.  I think this is going to be the case that I keep for the life of the phone.  Or until I get bored.

reviewText: This case offered a wonderful slimline protection for my note 2. There is no protection for the screen, but what a lot of people don't understand is that the films that a lot of companies try to sell you for phones and tablets are not actually protective for any reason other than smudging.The great thing about this case is that it keeps a somewhat slimline profile for the phone comparative to other otterbox products. It also offers about a 16th of an inch buffer from the screen to where it would fall onto a flat surface, offering you a good deal of protection against screen smashing. Obviously if you drop it onto an uneven surface, or maybe a driveway that has a rock on it, your screen is still a goner.The back is a hard shell of plastic...I think this case is wonderful.

It slides out of the pocket easily but most other times its sliding around on whatever surface its sitting on. I promptly decided to find another case that isnt overpriced and has poor fitment. Ive been using the Acase case thats similar to the Commuter. reviewText: I would of thought that i'd be the last person to buy an otterbox case for such a large phone. Ive always been the "style" kind of guy so for all my previous phones, id get a super slim cover. Those are great looking but dont offer drop protection. only scratch protection. When looking for a case for my beloved note 2 that i paid full retail price on, i wanted something more than just scratch protection. There are PLENTY of unique flip cases out there and i really wanted to buy one of them to add some style, and some protection. But knowing the fact that my phone would most likely break from a drop just wasn't reassuring to me. So i turned to Otterbox, the most well known brand when it comes to serious protection. I wear pretty slim jeans (the skinniest a man can go without feeling uncomfortable/skin tight). So i knew an otterbox defender wouldnt fit and im not much of a holster fan. Hoping that this case would fit my pockets, i decided to dish out some cash and buy it.Pros:-IT FITS IN MY POCKET!!!!!-It actually feels great to hold onto and gives my phone a rugged appearance-Unlike the Defender, the Commuter is made of an inside rubber and outer plastic shell. this is great for all the people  who want to slide their phones in and out of their pocket with ease.-There are flaps that cover the 3.5mm headphone jack and the charging port so no dust can get inside.-There is a nice even lip so that if the phone dropped face down, the screen would not make contact with the floor.-UNLIKE the Defender case, there are no problems pressing the volume buttons! (i was really scared that the buttons would feel mushy because many people with the Defender series were complaning of that issue.)-it comes with a screen protector (i havent got to test out how clear it is. Will update if i decide to install it)-Gives me peace of mind.Cons:-Make more colors! (although i love the black color on my grey Note 2)-Although the flaps covering the headphone and charging ports offer great dust protection, it makes it slightly less accessible. it takes me a couple extra seconds to insert the charging cable, however, its definitely a worthy tradeoff.-Does add thickness, bulk, and weight, but all these are tradeoffs for protection.Conclusion:There is absolutely nothing i could change about this case. It does exactly what its suppose to do: offer the maximum amount of protection that will still fit in your pockets (unless you wear skin tight jeans).This is for the people who want true drop protection.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: Awesome case. Has plenty of protection without covering the screen. Thick lip protects its from drops. My personal favorite series of cases

reviewText: This is my first Otterbox case ever and I'm really impressed by the quality of the materials and the overall protection that this case provides to my Note 2. I purchased the black case for my titanium gray Note 2. I didn't use the included screen protector as I bought thisMobC Galaxy Note 2 / N7100 Screen Protector HD Film - 99.9% Clarity Japanese Film - Retail Packaging - Fine Crystal [2-Pack] before I decided on a case for my phone.I only have a few minor issues with this case. The soft inner lining doesn't fit as snugly as I'd like and it's loose in areas where the hard outer shell doesn't clamp onto the phone. These aren't huge issues for me, but I can imagine how dusty the phone will get after some time in my pockets. Another minor issue is the amount of pressure needed to press buttons covered by the case, but I expected this due to the amount of protection this case provides. The last minor issue concerns the cutouts in the soft lining for the headphone jack and micro-USB port. The cutouts make it a little more difficult to plug in things, but it's not a huge pain.Despite these minor issues, I think this is a great case for the Note 2. I feel at ease knowing that my phone has a better chance of surviving a drop without much damage.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: I had previously been using the OEM Samsung hard case for my Note 2. It was a very good case that was sleek/stylish however it lacked any real drop protection. I picked the Commuter since the Defender would be way too much overkill. That, plus the built in screen protector on the Defender has always been an issue. The Commuter is a nice balance between looks and functionality. While it does add some bulk to the already large phone, it's worth it IMO. With this case you get added protection from drops/bumps, increased front protection in case you drop the phone screen first as well as ports to cover the charge/headphone plugs.The plastic back cover is a little slippery but it's nothing too bad. I'd prefer a little more grip with that but it works fine as is. Only other concern is that since the back cover is plastic, it doesn't grip well if you lay it on an inclined surface. It'll slide around alot if you're not careful. All the ports are easily accessible however the only issue I've come across is with the headphone plug cover. If your earbuds/headphones have a large 3.5 plug, it may not fit properly with the cover that hides the port. Most of my headphones work fine however a couple won't fit due to the tight squeeze of the plug cover.Overall, really like this case and feel a little more comfortable should my phone get dropped or whatever. For those of you that want a slim/sleek looking case, you're in the wrong place. If you want a sturdy case that will protect your investment, look no further.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: I love the Otterbox commuter series cases.  Lots of protection.  Makes the G Note 2 a little thicker, but it still fits in my pocket.

reviewText: The case itself is great.  However, now I understand why the YouTube videos demonstrating the case don't include a demonstration of the screen saver.  The most serious flaw is that the screen cover came with a piece of tape marking the back side and the front side.  The back side tape came off cleanly, but the tape on the front side tape left a thick, goo area on the screen.  Another problem is that the screen cover doesn't come with a scraper to help put it on, and a credit card just isn't strong enough to put it on without bubbles.Other than the tape issue (which is serious) I must say that I am surprised by how much the screen saver improves the touch screen.  Before I put on the screen saver I thought that the Note 2 screen was too sensitive; I often had extra taps register, and sometimes the screen reacted before I actually touched it.  It wasn't very good for games for that reason.  I also didn't like the S-Pen.  It actually magnified the excessively touchy screen problems.  The was also the unpleasant feeling of writing on glass with plastic.  The screen saver made all of the difference.  It throttled down the hyper-sensitive screen, and the surface provides a very nice writing surface for the pen.  I don't keep leaving stray marks on the S-Note app.  I have left the screen saver on despite the glue spot because it greatly improves the operation of the phone.EDIT:  I wrote Otterbox about the screen issue.  They wanted photographs.  I sent in the pictures and they shipped me a new DEFENDER case.  It was interesting being able to compare the commuter and the defender cases.  Honestly, I like the commuter case better.  The defender has a rigid screen protector, and there is just a tiny gap between the screen and the phone in some places.  That gives an unpleasant bit of give in some areas of the screen, especially when using the stylus.  The holster on the defender case looks secure, but it popped off my belts too many times for me to feel comfortable carrying it on my belt in the holster.  Also, the defender case has rectangular attachment points for the holster right below the sound and power buttons.  The commuter case doesn't have the attachment points, and I found it much easier to orient right side up in my hand just by feel; the attachment points make that quite a bit harder with the defender case.  Since the holster for the defender case is now in a drawer there is only a slightly greater amount of drop protection with my defender case.  I am actually considering trying out a third-party screen protector and going back to using my commuter case.  Still, I have to give a great deal of credit to Otterbox's support system; they were fantastic!
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 2 - Black

reviewText: This has been a great case for my Note II.  It fits very well, and gives a very secure feeling that the unit will be protected in the event of a drop.  It is just thick enough and tough enough to give that sense of security, but is just flexible enough to go on and off easily.  And even though it increases the bulk of the already large Note II, it still fits very comfortably in my front pants pocket.  I usually forget that the phone is even in my pocket.  The only drawback to this product is that the screen is not protected, but I have added a MediaDevil screen protector, and now the unit is protected against everything other than a direct blow to the screen itself.  If you are concerned about that, you will want to consider a case with a flap across the screen, but I didn't want to hassle with one, and have never felt that my screen was at risk of damage.  Highly recommended.

reviewText: This is the extreme case I’ve been lusting after.  My phone is my office and contains more valuable tools and information than any of my other possessions so no protection is too much for it.  People comment on this all the time about how big and bulky it looks.  I’m fine with that because I’ll choose function over form every time.Compared to other extreme cases this does the job:  waterproof seals and a hard shell that protects the device against scratches and drops.  However the waterproof function does not support use of headphones and you must remember to seal the headphone and docking ports while in transit.  Some people complained I sounded a bit hard to hear with this case and adjusting those port seals sometimes helped.  Competitors have adapters for the headphone jack which is a blessing and curse.  I like Otterbox’s approach because there is less to lose and I’m rarely worried about listening to the music waterproof (got Bluetooth for that).  All switches are easily accessible except for the fingerprint sensor on the 5s.The killer feature of this case is the ease of removal.  Most other extreme cases, including the Defender are a pain to remove the phone from.  This has two metal latches you disengage and your phone is available.  This is of particular interest when I need to use a credit card reader on my phone.
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for iPhone 5 - Retail Packaging - Orange
categories: [['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Accessories'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Basic Cases'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Waterproof Cases']]

reviewText: I got this case to replace my Defender case and it just doesn't do it for me. It certainly does seem like it would repel a nuclear explosion! I had several gripes with this case, the first being the screen protector. It sits too far above the screen and affects the touch sensitivity, plus with the small screen cutout, keeps you from being able to touch the edges of the screen. The port plugs are hard to install and remove, plus I can see the o-rings wearing out prematurely with normal use. Also, the case will NOT keep out dust if any of the plugs are out! I was mowing the grass and had headphones plugged in with the phone in my pocket. When I was done I had to take the case apart and clean all the dust and small grass pieces from between the screen and screen protector. I never had this problem with my defender case! My major gripe about the case is the size of the opening for the lightning connector. If you use anything other than the cord that apple gave you, it won't fit. I charge my phone on a nightstand with a 6' RND cord and have an Amazon basics cord in my car, neither of these will plug in with the phone in this case. I also had an issue with the case messing up the phone's tilt sensor, which turns off the screen when you hold the phone up to your ear. The phone would constantly go on speakerphone or mute while I was talking. Out of this case or in my Defender case, that feature works fine. Bottom line, I'm probably going to send it back.
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for iPhone 5 - Retail Packaging - Orange
categories: [['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Accessories'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Basic Cases'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Waterproof Cases']]

reviewText: I work in manufacturing with lots of dust and end up wearing a dust mask for half the day.  I started carrying my wallet in a ziplock so the dust (mostly silica) wouldn't ruin my cards.  My defender case wasn't keeping out the dust and I worried about the health of my iPhone, so I took a chance on this case, and I am happy to say that it does what it is supposed to.  Not only is it totally waterproof (I tested it for 30 minutes as the instructions indicate without the phone inside), but it keeps the very fine dust away from my phone completely.  Yes, it is bulky, but it's only slightly larger than the defender and much easier to get on and off.  No multiple layers.  Open the box, insert phone, close box, latch.  Just that simple.  As for sound quality, I was expecting worse with a waterproof case (the others I've seen required Bluetooth) and I find it totally acceptable, and I use Bluetooth often, at work and while driving.  As one other reviewer wisely said, there is no "one case to rule them all", and I would use another of my many cases in circumstances where my clothing was light and I wanted to slim down my accessory.  But for my work environment, I needed a work case, and this fits the bill nicely
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for iPhone 5 - Retail Packaging - Orange

reviewText: First let me say that this is the new revision of this product and it does have the fixed screen protector so that you can hear from the earpiece.  So those the complained about the sound had the older version of this and it was indeed a problem.Now to the good stuff:I know, you got this great phone and you want to keep it new while working outside... How do I ensure my beautiful phone will still work when I work in construction, electrical, etc?  The answer is this case...I wanted to know if the claims about this device were true so I put it through its paces.  I submerged it, I buried it, I drove over it (with my small light car) and I finally put my phone in it and used it.Pros:I can't think of another case that protects as well for so many different items than this case does.  It's very good at protection.It is waterproof (I have no idea how deep, but for accidentally dropping it in a puddle or answering your phone by the pool, it works great), it's sturdy (if you dropped it in said puddle and someone ran over it, chances are it's perfectly fine) and nothing gets through the case.Cons: These are somewhat picky (after all, with all that protection, there has to be some trade off), but work noting.The sound is reduced (but surprisingly clear) by this case and don't count on the noise cancellation to help much when talking.  The case is also quite bulky and roughly doubles the size of your iPhone 5.  Also, the screen cover is notoriously difficult to keep clean and the really picky one is that since the ports are all covered, getting any charging cable through the hole besides the Apple one, probably isn't going to happen.Overall, I am impressed with this case.  I don't like the bulk, but hey, this isn't my primary case, just the one I use on job sites...
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for iPhone 5 - Retail Packaging - Orange

reviewText: I'm going to review this as a "as needed" case, not as an everyday case. I personally couldn't imagine using this sort of case all the time as I find it too bulky and uncomfortable to hold/access but for those times when your phone might be subjected to extreme conditions I think it's an excellent accessory to own.Upon opening it and reviewing the paperwork the first thing you'll see is that they recommend testing it in water for a full 30mins before placing your device inside, anyone who just tosses their phone in here and throws it in water is insane in my opinion. I filled up a large bowl with water, put a folded paper towel into the case, sealed it back up, and submerged it into the bowl (weighing it down so it was fully under the water) I waited about 1/2 an hour and then dried it completely, opened it and was very happy to see my napkin was dry and there wasn't a drop of water in the case. Now I personally never intend to submerge my phone whether its in this case or not, but I'm happy to see that if it was, and fell into some water I wouldn't need to worry. I also dropped the case several times on both carpet, tile, and cement flooring and it appeared perfectly fine. I repeated the water test after these drops and still bone dry inside. So I'm also confident that if my phone fell out of my pocket while I was out about about it would survive.All this said I'm confident this is a great case for trips to the beach, when we go roller blading or bike riding, or any other situation where I wouldn't trust my flimsy day to day case to actually protect my phone, heck I might even use it when taking a bubblebath so I can watch a show on my iphone w/o worrying about it slipping and falling in.One thing to note for the ladies, I see lots of comments about how fast & easy it is to get your phone in/out of this case... I wouldn't say that is untrue but you will need to use your thumb nail to release the hinges, and I felt like mine might break if I wasn't really careful.

reviewText: Hi,I've had this case for about a week now and I'm pleased with it.  Over the years I've had a lot of cases for my iPhones (Otterbox Commuter, Otterbox Defender, H20 Audio, Pelican, Amphibian, Speck, PowerMat, and many more).  It's occurred to me that cases are like jackets. There is no single one that's great for everything.  This case reminds me of my North Face Double-X Parka down jacket.  The Double-X is bulky, not particularly stylish (unless maybe you're a gear-head) and hard to get into the pockets but under harsh conditions it is exactly what you want.  The Armor case is pretty much the same story.I would generally not recommend this case for an every day walking around case.  However judging it against the other waterproof cases I've tried it is the best.  Below are some additional notes for you.Pro's:- Construction is good quality.  I was disappointed in the Otterbox Commuter and Defender cases for the iPhone 4.  The iPhone 3 models were much better.  This Armor case is better than the Otterbox iPhone 4 cases.- It's not a bitch to get the phone in and out of the case.  You just open the latches and pop it in and out.  This is important since I don't want to use the Armor all the time.  With the H20 Audio case I literally worried about breaking the phone in half every time I used it.  The Amphibian case was a lot more trouble too.- All the controls are accessible.  This is not true with the Pelican or H20 Audio.  It's not as easy to access them as a typical everyday case but it is possible.- For a waterproof case it's actually not too bulky.  The other three I've used have all been as large or larger.Cons:- Price.  This baby is expensive- Weight.  The Amphibian case for my iPhone 4 is considerably lighter.- The sound quality is a bit muffled/muted but it's usable.  Headphones or a Blu-tooth are good options when making a lot of phone calls.So if you're climbing Mt. Hood consider the Armor case, and a perhaps a Double-X Parka too. ;)Best regards,John

reviewText: I've always put my smartphones in an Otterbox case.  Tradition, perhaps, but I've come to trust the OtterBox name.I'm also not a 100% fan of the iPhone, so that may taint my review a bit.My first OtterBox for the iPhone wore out after holstering an unholstering dozens of times daily, so I gave this case a try.  It is heavy duty, and it is waterproof.  However, the case and screen protector mean you will have to adjust the way you do some things--namely type on the on-screen keyboard.  There is just enough resistance on the screen protector to make it more difficult to type.  That is the last thing I needed, considering I have fat fingers and had a hard enough time without a case.I also am not thrilled that this did not come with a belt clip or holster of any sort, but I've become used to simply carrying the phone in an available pocket.It's strong.  It's bulky.  It's a pain in the can  (especially if you leave it in your hip pocket too long).  But, it will protect your $500 iPhone.

reviewText: This case is marketed for the iPhone 5. I got it for my 5S. In regards to the 5S, everything fits as it should, except that the hole for the flash is too small since the 5S has a dual flash. That's not a problem for me though since I won't be using the flash when I use this case.The case is amazingly rugged. I feel like I could throw my phone at a brick wall and it would be fine. I won't try that though. But it's reassuring that it will protect my big iPhone investment no matter what.My friend has the Lifeproof case, which is $20 more and not as rugged. I prefer this one, even though it's bigger.I bought this case for the beach, considering it's water and sand proof. So far I have only tested it in the bath tub and pool and it holds up to its promises at this point. It's a bit big for regular daily use though.....unless you have big pockets. Can't wait to use it again.

reviewText: I got this for my sons phone and I am so happy I did, your reason for getting this phone should be ultimate protection without caring that there are trade-offs, because there are a few. WE got my son a 5S for Christmas, constantly worried that he would drop it, break it, step on it, leave it somewhere where anyone else might do the same, etc. Btw, my son is 10, and while he is very responsible, he is still only 10. Also, he does not have full access to the phone, but will use it when he goes on sleepovers, trips, playdates, etc....and these are probably the most likely times that risk damaging the phone.That being said, the Otterbox Armor provides a level of protection that makes my wife and I very comfortable. This case os as close to Fort Knox protection as possible. It is thick. Very thick. So thick that it will muffle the vibration of the phone quite a bit. It will also muffle the sound a little, but not as bad as the vibration. It is easy to miss a call if it is only on vibrate.The Armor turns the iPhone into a little brick. You cannot access the fingerprint scanner, however, Otterbox does have one specifically for the 5s, you can check their website. I love the screen protection as well. My wife and I have Defenders for our Galaxy S4s, and for us that is fine, but for my son, we feel much better that he has stronger protection. The entire case is very rugged looking, though I wonder how crush protective it actually is. I hope not to find out, but if someone steps on it, I will let you now how it turns out. We also have no intention of putting the phone underwater, but it does seem like it will provide protection in the off chance that it falls into a puddle, etc. He has not complained about it, so I think he is happy with it, and as long as it protects his phone, so are we.
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for iPhone 5 - Retail Packaging - Orange

reviewText: Otterbox does make some excellent phone covers.  And, I have purchased more than a few covers before and I always Otterbox was of very good quality.This box is certainly NOT the Otterbox commuter!1.  What's in the box?:  You receive (in an impressive box) the cover.  Also, there are brief instructions and, buried inside the bottom plastic wrapping, is a lanyard.2.  Aesthetic:?  I received the Neon Armor cover.  First off, this thing is built like a tank.  I would not say that this cover is built for the looks, as this is a form for function item.  You will let everyone know you have a phone in a tough cover with this thing.3.  Use:?  It was quite easy to place the phone in the cover.  First, you simply unsnap the hinges and this cover will separate into two pieces.  You simply place the phone inside, and snap the cover closed.  That's it.Did I mention this thing is built like a tank?  A plastic insert informs you that this is built to US military standard.  And I believe it because there is a lot of plastic material here.  Dropping the phone (not with my phone inside during tests by they way as I am not willing to do this) clearly causes no issues as the plastic is robust.  The phone is also waterproof according to the specs.  I have tried putting this in water and not seen any leakage so it appears to be waterproof.  However, while the cover is incredibly robust, the seemingly weak plastic cover on the front.  While these is a lip around the front cover, it sure seems like a weak link.  I recommend not throwing out the plastic insert as this will protect the inside of the phone if the phone is not inside.  It sure seems that the cover could be breached in water.  So, as for this item being waterproof, this would NOT be my primary motivation in purchasing the item as this would protect the item from a drop but not being submerged (in my opinion).  This is an important point to consider.  Otherwise, this cover is fantastic for its purpose which is a fairly indestructible cover and an ability not to be easily damaged.Use of phone?:  Okay, this is not the cover to purchase if you expect to have long detailed conversations with people!  While the cover allows the touchscreen to be used easily (and that are naturally buttons for the home function and volume and ringer), talking on the phone is a mediocre experience.  I would think using Bluetooth devices would be a better approach, but then again this is a protection cover for the phoneOne quibble:  On the bottom are two removable tabs for headphones.  These have some nice seals and do not seem to breach the waterproof aspect (the front cover is my main concern).  However, be aware that while the headphone jack is not an issue, the average lightning power jack may not easily fit inside the cover to allow a charge.Overall:  This is not a cover I would use for everyday use as this is far more robust that I would require.  But for those workers and people who need a great phone, but are conscious of needing a robust cover than this is a great choice. I would caution a buyer somewhat on the waterproof issue (seems fine but I wouldn't go out of my way to put this in water and dropping it off a boat and letting it float for a while seems risky (but heck electronics and saltwater don't mix anyway - just ask the Navy).  While I did not test the cover with my phone inside during crush tests and drops, the cover is really tough and it will protect the phone.  Going swimming is probably not a great idea. Accidentally dropping this in the sink  will probably not kill the phone with this cover.For me, this cover is probably overkill, but for others this can be a awesome cover to protect the phone.  A bit expensive, but for the considerations above, still a small price to pay instead of a new phone I suppose.  I am giving this three stars based in my immediate use and examination, but I think this is more of a 3.5 star item.

reviewText: This case provides a ton of protection for your iPhone. Sound quality is good. Unfortunately, the case is too large for every day use. I'm a big guy and I wear cargo shorts for work most days and I found lugging the Armor around to be cumbersome at best. Removing the case from your pocket while seated is almost impossible. The grippy case and the square edges makes for a difficult time removing it from your pocket.The screen protector started scratching up on the first day of use. Two weeks in and the screen protector was scratching up at an alarming rate. This case could use a built in tempered glass screen protector like the Incipio Atlas(HORRIBLE audio quality) instead of flimsy plastic.After a few days of pocket time, my Otterbox Armor developed a loose rattling latch with the case closed. Otterbox replaced the front part of the case quickly and that solved the problem.Ultimately, I just couldn't justify spending so much on a case that was just too hard to carry and didn't have a more durable screen protector. The case went back to Amazon.Otterbox Armor audio quality combined with the Incipio Atlas design and glass screen protector would be the perfect rugged, waterproof iPhone case.

reviewText: ***UPDATEOtterbox bought Lifeproof 5/22/2013. This confirms that even Otterbox knows they didn't make a winner. If you can't beat them... Buy them!********The case plastics are finished well but the pieces do not interlock with any precision. Once "sealed", a 1/16" and greater gap all around remained where the back plate meets the case. The case felt like a prototype and is in need of refinement.  The amount water trapped in the gap between the case and backplate (even after shaking and wiping dry) left me questioning if  a water-tight seal had been created.  Several drops water found their way inside on the water test prior to installing the phone. I could not confidently discern whether it happened during the test or from separating the case.Once the iPhone was enclosed calls seemed clear and the touchscreen remained very usable without any significant decrease in sensitivity. Buttons like the volume, home, power and mute all seemed functional and responsive.The Lifeproof Fre case also didn't impress me, but I do like the Fre over this plastic brick. I would find it difficult to recommend this case due to size, weight and questionable functionality of being truly water-tight.

reviewText: I got the Otterbox Armor off of Groupon for $25. I am not kidding when saying that the case itself weighs about the same as the phone does, put them together and it's like you have a brick in your pocket. For this reason, I don't think this is a good EDC (every day case), but if you can get it cheap it's definitely worth picking up for trips where you are worried about destroying your phone (camping, boating, swimming, construction, etc.).

reviewText: Purchased on a Groupon deal after seeing Angela's fantastic video, I'm very pleased with this rugged, protective case for my iPhone 4S.  No, it's not particularly pretty, but it does meet US Military Standards for protection against water, dust, accidental drops and crush protection.I usually use theOtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for iPhone 4/4S - Frustration-Free Packaging - Blackand have been very pleased with the protection it has provided.  I've dropped my phone a few times and thanks to OtterBox, no damage done.  The OtterBox Armor Series was always out of my price range, but when I saw it so heavily discounted (only paid twenty-five for it...)  I decided the additional protection it offered was worth considering.INSTALLATION:This case is easier to put on your iPhone 4/4S than the Defender two part method.  Once you release the two metal clamps on the side of the case, you can easily slip your phone into the case and reverse the process to secure it.  Port covers waterproof the phone when in place, but they have to be secured for this to be so!PROTECTION:From Water - down to 6.6' for 2 minutes and 30 seconds.  That's enough time to fish it out of the toilet or a koi pond, but you won't want to take your phone scuba diving!From Drops - up to 10'.  This case provides excellent protection from drops out of your jacket pocket or car, but you won't want to toss it from the roof of your second story house.From Dust - provides a dust-free environment for your phone.  If it's clean when it goes in the case, it'll be clean when it comes out!From Crush - this case is designed to withstand your vehicle running over it with your phone inside, assuming your vehicle is under 2 tons.SUGGESTIONS Per OtterBox Insert:+ Test your case in water for 30 seconds prior to installing your phone.+ Inspect case after every impact to ensure protective properties are not compromised.  (Always good advice.)+ If you remove your phone, check the inner seal for dust or debris prior to re-installing to ensure protection.Overall, the 4-layer protection offered by the OtterBox Armor Series is superior to any other I've found.  It can be charged in the case using a standard 30-pin cable and the on/off and volume buttons work well.However, it's bulky, and call volume on my end suffers when in this case.  The ringer on/off button is very stiff and difficult to maneuver.  The built-in screen protector sometimes negatively affects the touchscreen responsiveness.In my opinion, no case is perfect in terms of style and function.  This protective case is very good for active people who want to protect their expensive phone from drops and liquid, but it is hefty, obscures phone call volume and not waterproof for long periods of time.
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for iPhone 4/4S - Retail Packaging - Neon
categories: [['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Accessories'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Basic Cases'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Waterproof Cases']]

reviewText: I tested this phone out on an iPhone 4S and found that while it is really rugged looking, there are some strange gaps in the phone that allow the introduction of dust and water into the inside edges.  There is no absolute flush connection on the phone around the edges.I first tested the case by soaking it for about 20 minutes immersed in a pot of water with a weight on top.  It kept the inside dry but moisture got into the gaps between the top and bottom.The buttons on this phone are hard to maneuver (especially the mute switch which is at many times unusable because the mechanism that is used to "catch" the switch does not always work and is not consistent).  The clips on the side are a little chunky too.I use the Lifeproof case too on my iPhone 5 and although the Lifeproof feels extremely light compared to the Armor it is able to retain my retina display quality and also provides good audio output.  The Armor dulls audio output and screen quality -- there were several calls made where people on the other end said I sounded muffled (and this was expecially true on speakerphone.  I did not have this problem with the Defender or the Lifeproof.Otterbox, I know there was a delay with the Armor release ... but I still don't feel this case was ready for primetime yet.  There are some engineering snafus that need to be addressed.  Hopefully Otter can improve on this one!

reviewText: OK, so i wanted to get this case for my 4s for the longest time. After all the negativity on here i decided against it. then i regretted that, bought it in a local store for full retail and wish i had NOT listened to the people on here. I upgraded from a Defender series case. i have NEVER used my phone without an otterbox... EVER.Here's some facts from a normal person. I use my phone as a (shocker) PHONE. I also use it for mapping, weather, Facebook, and gaming. Occasionally i will watch a youtube video on it, sometimes i will use it to show someone an awesome song. I have done all of these things since i got this case and here are the facts:Calls - I have made and received calls using just the handset and people i spoke with had no clue i had a case on my phone. I was able to hear the conversation with no problem whatsoever.Gaming - I have had no loss of functionality anywhere on the screen. Anywhere i touch for my game reacts the same as if the case wasn't thereMusic/Videos - Is there some sound loss? yes. Is it "omfg horrible!" no. If you are using your phone as a portal music device with no external speakers, i submit there is something wrong with you to begin with. But lets not go there. If you are using your phone for the occasional youtube video now and again or listening to a song to show a friend then listen up. 1) pop the plug cover off the bottom, the sound returns to normal. don't complain "then its not waterproof anymore" why are you listening to music in wet conditions anyway? WHY?! If you are a sane person, go indoors, pop the cover open and you have full sound again. However even with the cover on, i was able to hear my wife watching a video i showed her on facebook, from 3 ROOMS AWAY (vol max) So showing someone a nifty new song or video, and you require super max volume, then yes pop the cover on the bottom. otherwise the sound volume will be reduced by about 30%.Ringtone, while in an area with loud ambiance (like in the cab of a tractor trailer, traveling down the highway) you are going to miss calls... UNLESS you also have vibrate on then you will be fine. Truth be told i couldn't hear the damn thing even before this case. However if you spend most of your time at home or in quieter situations like the office or what have you. you wont noticed a problem at all.  Furthermore i submit some of these reviewers require a dictionary, as the sound "quality" is NOT reduced. the sound "volume" is. so your music and videos sound just fine only slightly quieter.Pros:-Dust Proof? YES this was tested to the extreme recently when several pounds of cement dust poured onto my pant leg and subsequently my phone. the case kept it all out, and was easy to clean-Water Proof? i have not thrown my phone into a bucket of water or went surfing with it (seriously, scroll through the reviews, some dingbat went surfing with their phone); However i am 100% confident that in a rainstorm if i had to make a call with it, or if i was splashed with water in the pocket i carry it in, i wouldn't worry.-Crush Proof? I have leaned on it, laid on it, and various forms of putting pressure on it while at work (my job can be rough some days) and at 350lbs, i can assure you this case did not give. would i run it over with my car? why on earth would i do that?-Drop proof? my defender survived multiple bounces (in one drop) and falls from up to 8 feet; i feel confident this will too.-Normal Everyday use (by which i mean, you use it normally) while protecting against a beating of external forces, absolutely.-Easy to remove. In the event you wanted to use a dock, or other phone accessory temporarily (ie: the iphone mount for nerf guns; or a docking station for a party) the phone can be removed by unclasping the 2 clasps that are there, and removing the back. its just that simple.Cons:-Sound Volume? It is reduced by roughly 25-30% Why? because to be water/dust proof the phone must be completely 100% encased. Between thin layers of plastic and thick outer layers to defend against shocks, drops, spills, and thrills, this phone is 100% protected from anything but bullets and explosions.-Buttons. Home button is no issue. Volume + - take a little more pressure to activate; and admittedly the Silent Mode switch on the side is "troublesome" or more accurately takes a little effort to work. But to me that's a small price to pay for a water/dust proof phone.-Carry. While the defender comes with a nice belt case, this one requires an additional $20 purchase to get a belt case for it. Out of the box it is strictly a case. However in recent months i have been carrying my phone in a pocket anyway, so this transition was flawless when i got this one. It fits in a standard (t-shirt) pocket, Pants pocket, or even an AR mag pouch (my tactical pants have magazine pockets in them) snugly and securely.So all in all this is a case that every iPhone 4/4s or 5/5s (different case) should be in. While there is a couple cons, the average person will have no issue at all with a case like this. if you are using your phone as a radio all the time, then get an external speaker or headphones if its that big of a deal to you.

reviewText: After my first S3 went through the wash cycle, finding a decent waterproof case has been something of a quest. I've tried several; some were promising, but had fatal flaws, while others were just downright stupid concepts.I had really high hopes for this case; Otterbox makes really good cases, and I felt sure they'd knock it outta the park with this case. While it does have some good features that I liked, it also has some flaws. One flaw in particular is fatal flaw, and for that one, I'm returning the product.Pros:It IS waterproof - I kept it submerged for over an hour in my bathroom sink, and the inside stayed dry.The case is surprisingly easy to open and close back up - I REALLY liked that.Ports are easy to open and close.No 'moisture spots' developed between the inside of the case screen and my device screen. That was HUGE in my book.Exterior speaker worked really well. In fact, was louder than the built-in S3 external speaker.Touchscreen was very sensitive.Cons:The thing is HUGE beyond reasonable.When I latched the case shut, the back piece was 'bowed'. Let me try to explain - the case is in two pieces - the front piece, where the phone lives, and the back plate. The back plate has teeth along one long edge that fit into matching slots in the front piece. Align the teeth and slots, and press the two pieces together. Then use the metal latches to fasten them tight. That's when the 'bowing' shows up - at least it did with my unit. After closing the latches, I'd look at it from the top and bottom edges, and could see that while the two long edges were drawn tightly together, the middle of the back plate was bowed outward, so there appeared to be a gap between the two. The gap apparently didn't leak, but it was an obvious side effect of the latching process that constantly made me nervous.While the external speaker worked well, it is a weak spot. It is made up of a lightweight screen on the exterior of the case, and a rubber-like diaphragm on the inside. The diaphragm vibrates like a speaker cone, and transmits music or telephone conversations really well. My fear is that this could easily be punctured, allowing moisture in that could ruin the device inside.The buttons are STIFF, and required hard presses to get them to work. The Back and Menu softkeys are hard to reach and not responsive. Surprising, since the main touch screen is so sensitive.Telephone - this is where the case really sucks. Be prepared to literally shout to make yourself heard. If you actually intend to listen to the other party, you better put in your headphones. Absolutely the worst thing about this case, and for me was the dealbreaker.The S3 has a proximity sensor feature that turns off your display when you hold the phone to your ear, and turns it back on when you take the phone away. This feature is disabled entirely while the case is on my phone. In fact, I'm not able to disconnect from calls until the other party hangs up. I refuse to start turning off phone features because my case renders them unworkable. At $95 this case better allow my phone features to work correctly.Maybe Otterbox will fix these flaws - another reviewer said he contacted Otterbox customer support who sent him out a new case that fixed the proximity sensor problem. Hopefully one day they'll fix the issue where I can't hear the caller or shout so the caller can hear me while on a phone call.
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - Neon

reviewText: This case is beefy.  Metal hinges/clasps on the side hold this case on your phone, and that is your first clue that this means business. The S3 is not a small phone to begin with, and this case adds a lot of extra width, some height, and a lot of heft.  If you need protection this is great, but be prepared for the size.
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - Neon

reviewText: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for the Galaxy SIII will certainly keep the phone dry.  I tested the case by putting some paper inside and closing the case.  Then submerging it in the sink and holding down the case with a lotion bottle.  No bubbles came from the side and after wiping off the outside found the paper inside nice and dry.  Two clips on the case lock the back down tight and make for a nice waterproof environment for the phone.  I haven't checked to see if the phone would overheat but I wouldn't expect this to be a problem.  The case is strong enough to keep the phone from breaking or shattering the screen if dropped under normal conditions.  There probably would still be cases where the phone could still get broken but these would have to be some pretty abnormal areas like dropping it out a car window at 75 mph and running over it.  I'm not going to test that.All this protection comes with a price and these are that the case makes the phone bigger and the buttons require more effort to work with the phone.  Sound quality was good and there is a waterproof cover for the headphone jack and the USB port.  The price seemed a little high until I considered that it is cheaper than what it cost me to replace the screen on my second daughter's phone. The OtterBox is a must for those outdoor adventurists and definitely worth getting to protect the smartphone investment.

reviewText: Well I'm not going to go over all the good things about this case because it does exactly what it's supposed to...drop, dust, water, crush proof. Only slight problem I noticed is when you're actually on a call. Imma try to explain best I can...for all you with a Galaxy S3 should know what I mean. Ok so normally when you're on a call the phones proximity sensor detects when you have the phone near your ear/face and turns the screen off so you don't accidentally press buttons and what not. But when you take the phone away while still on the call the screen turns on again and you see all the in-call options like speakerphone, etc. Now the reason for 4-star rating. Apparently when the Otterbox Armor case is installed and you get a phone call the sensor activates and turns the screen off immediately whether or not if you have the phone near your ear/face or away. This becomes a problem because first of all, you can't end the call because none of the buttons work, so you have to wait till the other party hangs up. Second of all if u need access stuff like internet, photos, etc while on a call you can't because the screen stays off and the buttons don't work while on call. My first theory which is probably is correct is that the built in screen protector is not flush enough to the sensor and/or since the front of the case makes the sensor recessed it blocks or interferes with the  amount of light the sensor receives. So far I found 3 ways to remedy this: First, take phone calls outside when its daylight cuz outside its bright enough to detect when phones not near your face. Second, use a Bluetooth or headphones during a call, this leaves the screen on, or Third if inside building or home rush to a nearby light or window and put the front of phone close to the light, this will simulate that the phone is away from your face and turn on the screen momentarily then once on, quickly press the speakerphone button then the screen will stay on. So far I haven't reported this issue to Otterbox.com as this is where I ordered my case. I could just have a defective one or this could the issue with all the case, I dunno. I'm just waiting to see if anyone has this problem yet. I took some photos and the digital camera actually picks up the IR sensor light which u can see... it actually stays on even when not on a call. I will post the pics on here.UPDATE::: Ok several hours after posting this and tinkering with some settings on the phone i found the in-call setting to turn off the proximity sensor. This completely resolves the problem. So now when im in call i just tap the power button to off/on the screen manually. No biggie...easy fix to have the ultimate protection of the Armor case :):):) Updated to 5-Star as well. :)5/30 UPDATE: Contacted Otterbox on 5/23 about this issue and as of today i have brand new one just shipped out via FedEx....apparently others have reported this problem too and the replacement fixes this issue. The thing is...its not really a big problem cuz doesnt affect the protection performance at all. So i just gonna keep this as a backup case. :) Otterbox Warranty Service is the best!!! No Hassle Fast Service!!
title: OtterBox Armor Series Waterproof Case for Samsung Galaxy S III - Retail Packaging - Neon

reviewText: For those who want to use a smartphone but live in perpetual fear of destroying it, this case is made for you. There's simply nothing that can afford a higher level of durability without making the device unusable. There are actually rugged phones out there, e.g. some of Motorola's IDEN network devices, but they aren't available for all networks and are permanently clunky. Also, those don't help if you already bought a phone and can't (or don't want to) send it back. If you must have a rugged phone, this is about as close as you can get to having your cake and eating it too as far as high-end functionality + durability goes. This case affords excellent protection for the S3, which although no longer the best in class, is still a very capable device.As you can probably tell just by looking at it and reading the specs, this case turns the S3 into a tank. You can drop it, kick it around, dunk it in water, rub it in sand, take a shower with it... it'll not even faze the phone in this case. And yes, I did try doing most of those things. Basically, as long as this case is on you have very little to fear as far as damaging the phone. This does come at a price though- both literally and in terms of usability. Here's the general pros and cons of this product:Pro:As noted, nothing short of a direct hit from a tactical nuke will kill your phone in this thing.The speaker and camera work surprisingly well inside this case. I was especially impressed by the camera: comparing shots side by side I couldn't tell the difference with or without the case.The touch functions also work very well, and the screen is not impaired visually by the built-in protector. Note however that getting the protector wet makes the screen act up- screen's fault, not the case; these capacitive touchscreens aren't designed to function underwater.It enables use of all ports and buttons while in the case. The charge and headphone ports are protected by rubber caps.Con:This is one of the most expensive cases you can buy, especially now that the S3 is no longer top line and most other case makers have cut their product costs.Inevitably, the case adds a great deal of bulk and heft. In fact, I'd say it makes the S3 viable for use in hand to hand combat due to how much bulkier, heavier, and harder it gets.The buttons are considerably harder to press while the case is attached. This goes for the home/power keys, volume rocker, and the softkeys. The softkeys are fine when you touch them, but they're so deeply recessed that this is hard to do.While in the case, the microphone is muffled. This is unavoidable due to the level of protection, but it also makes the phone much harder to use as a phone. I called my wife with it on and she could barely understand what I was saying even when I raised my voice. You'll probably need to use a bluetooth headset when making calls.The case is difficult both to put on and remove. It's a two-piece design and you have to work these big metal clamps that snap the two halves shut. This is probably unavoidable to ensure watertightness, but it kind of kills its utility as a 'grab and go' travel arrangement. If you need to swap batteries or SD cards, this also makes it more of a pain to do so.So who and what is this case for? Straight up, I'll say that this level of protection is unnecessary for typical everyday use. Unless you're either obsessively terrified of damaging your device or the clumsiest person in the world (or I guess, both), you're not going to need a case this robust carrying your phone to work and home. It also impairs functionality enough that it's very awkward to use on a regular basis. I've had a Caseology TPU case on my S3 for about 5 months now and it's protected it just fine- literally not a scratch on the phone. This case retails for a whopping $9 at the present, considerably less than the OtterBox Armor even with the latter on sale. It's protective enough to keep the device safe despite short drops, and actually affords some spill protection as long as you don't dunk the whole thing. And best of all, the phone is still thin and light and easily usable despite the case being on.There are only a few situations I can see where you'd really need a case like OtterBox Armor:1. If you're going to take your phone into a very harsh environment, e.g. a trek into the Amazon rainforest or climbing Everest. This will ensure the phone survives even if you don't. It doesn't matter that it impairs functionality because you probably won't be making many calls from the boondocks anyway.2. If you know your phone is going to be handled in a place where it's very likely to be dropped, crushed, or spilled on- i.e. anywhere in the hands of a child.3. If you want to use your phone in the bath or shower.4. If you're too lazy to take your phone out of your pants pocket, and prefer to drop both into the washing machine.So basically, this is a 'sometimes use' case for most people. Get a cheap, lightweight case for everyday use, and when you're doing one of the above then change it. If you never do any of the above, don't buy it- in all likelihood you'll never use it. Personally, I've found one good use for this case so far: turning my S3 into a waterproof baby monitor in conjunction with an IP camera. This way I can watch the baby while taking a shower. Yeah, probably not your typical use case, but it is kind of cool- your mileage may vary.Side note: the 'neon' color on the dark case is pretty irrelevant. It's neon on the inside but you can't see it when the phone is there, so aside from the port caps it's pretty much just a dark gray case.

reviewText: I find this case to provide excellent protection, to be easy to install, but difficult to remove and to allow dust into the case.The case consists of a hard plastic shell that snaps into place around the phone, with a flexible soft gel case that then goes around the hard shell. The entire assembly then can be held and removed from a belt holder.Pro:+ This case provides excellent protection.+ There are openings for all the major connectors.+ The camera lens is well protected, and does not have any plastic over it, so it does not impede taking pictures.+ The dual speakers of the HTC One (which are a major feature of this phone) do not have plastic covering them, so the sound is great. However this does lead to the one major drawback of the case (see below).+ The phone is very secure in the hand while in this case - not slippery at all.+ Once snapped into the belt holder (correctly, see below), it will not come off.+ The phone fits into the belt holder face first, providing excellent protection for the screen.+ There are plugs for the power and the ear jack, although the power button is not protected because it also serves as an IR remote control.+ The built in screen protector does not impede the functions of the capacitive screen, although it can be a bit of a press when swiping the top menu bar.Con:- The case bulks out the otherwise thin HTC One, but this is needed to provide the protection. However some people won't like what it does to the beautiful thin design.- One has to be sure that there is a final "snap" when inserting the case into the belt holder. The first couple of times I used it the phone fell right out. I discovered that one has to be sure and push the two together firmly until a second "snap" is heard.- Otterbox made a design choice with this phone that causes a problem. The front of the case has a built in screen protector, but unlike other phones, it has cutouts for the two speakers. The top cutout is fine and flat, but the lower cutout is somewhat large, and allows dust to get into the case. I found that I needed to install a conventional stick-on screen protector under the otterbox in order to make sure that nothing got in there and scratched the screen. I understand why they did the design this way - to provide great sound - but it does sacrifice some protection from the elements. One can remove the screen protector with difficulty (try a hair dryer to soften the glue), but it actually has another purpose - if dropped on the face of the phone, the protector assists in keeping the impact lighter than it would be without the extra plastic.- Along with this, the case is VERY hard to remove, which means that those specks of dust are hard to get rid of. To remove the case, one has to ignore the large plastic pieces at the center of each side (those are used to hold the case into the belt holder). Instead there are two small snaps on each side and one on the top and bottom. They can be unsnapped, but it is hard and they were obviously not meant to be undone often. But the design of the screen protector means that they will be unsnapped periodically.Summary: For protection, I'm not sure this one can be beat. But the dust under the screen may cause some irritation - not to the screen, but to your eyes. Recommended if you can live with the screen protector design.

reviewText: If you want the best possible protection for your HTC One then it's clear the Otterbox Defender Series case is it. Overkill might be a word I'd use in describing it, but sometimes, especially when it comes to phones that cost hundreds of dollars, that can be a good thing. There' no doubt this case will protect your phone from pretty much everything your daily routine can throw at it or be thrown at.One of the things I really like about this case is the fact that the audio and microUSB ports are covered, most every case I've seen just doesn't do that.There are two things that might be considered `cons' for this case.The first is the size, this case is probably three of four times as thick as the HTC One, so you really lose that nice slim profile.  So you have to sacrifice something for that great protection right? It's not exactly bad, but I just felt it needed mentioning.The second thing is that once your phone is in the case it's very hard to get back out of it. The HTC One really has no reason to come out of the case once it's in there though as there is no removable battery or microSD card slot. Still though if you want to take it out you're in for a big fight. It took me quite a while to figure out how to get my phone out of the case, but I got it, and yeah it wasn't easy. For most people I think they'll put their phone in the case and leave it there so I don't think it's a big dealPros:+Excellent protection for the HTC One+Built-in screen protector+Screen protector in case can be used with screen protector on phone+Heavy duty and durable belt clip+Covers seal out dust and dirtCons:-Large case-Can be very hard to get your phone out of the case
title: Otterbox HTC One Defender Series Case Black 7726377

reviewText: I decided to pick up this Otterbox Defender for a discount on the Otterbox website a few weeks ago in anticipation of my HTC One's arrival. It comes with a hardcase, a silicone exoskeleton case, and a belt clip holster. The hardcase interior fits just snugly around the phone and has several tabs to keep it together, and the silicone outside case is thick and feels durable.With the case itself, there's not really much wrong. I found the tabs really hard to pull apart at first for those instances I wanted to take the case off, but I found out I had been forcing them all wrong and just had to be a little more dexterous with my fingernails. However, the biggest problem with the case is the built-in screen protector. It doesn't sit perfectly flush with the screen, creating a gap between the screen protector and the screen itself. When pushing your finger onto the screen with this screen protector, you can feel the two making contact and it's just very unpleasant. I absolutely hated the screen protector because in those instances where I took off the case and put it back together, I was always guaranteed to see some speck of dust or debris make its way under, requiring me to take the entire case apart again just to clean it. Very inconvenient.I eventually punched out the screen protector and wore out the adhesive with rubbing alcohol to use an Invisible Shield, which is not the greatest, but definitely better than the built-in solution. If you don't really plan to do anything like that with this given case, I'd shop elsewhere. The main reason I got this case at all was because it was on sale before the phone's launch and has great overall protection. I still use it for now because it makes me feel more at ease carrying such a nice phone on the go. The case is kind of thick, but I would say it isn't too thick. It does add size, but it's still overall reasonable in size.

reviewText: There are many reviews telling how well the case is so I am just going to talk about the few questions/concerns I had with this case in case anyone else may want to know as well.Wireless charging:  I installed this wireless charging receiver: B00D2V9XFCand tested it with this charging pad:B00DQDE1K8I linked the two products as I would imagine (I haven't had a whole lot of experience with wireless charging) that the results you get depend on the charger and receiver you picked.  Anyway, It worked just fine in the otterbox case.SPIGEN glass screen protectors:  I purchased the .23 mm version of the glass.  After applying it the Otterbox case was significantly harder to snap together.  I stopped trying to force it for fear of damaging something.  I think the .15 mm version of the glass might work with this otterbox case but I can't say for sure.Other thoughts on quality:  I have had Otterbox Defender cases in the past.  With the S4 case I feel as though they used a cheaper material to make the rubber shell that goes around the plastic one.  It still protects and this is just a personal observation/opinion.The reason I docked one star is because of the plastic film that is built in to protect the screen.  On any of the otterbox cases I have owned this screen isn't that great as I feel it gives the screen of my phone a filmy look ( I hope this makes sense.)  I have heard others just remove it and substitute there own but I have never personally done this and I do have to admit that you can get used too it.  I still dock the star though because in this case where the phone has an HD screen I feel it matters.Bottom line: I do like this case but sadly am returning it since I applied that glass screen protector.  I really do feel like I am giving my phone some serious protection as it takes me forever and some sore fingers to get that dang plastic shell apart even when the phone isn't in it.

reviewText: This is the third protective case I have tried for my Galaxy S4 and it is definitely the sturdiest and appears to offer the maximum protection.  The back, sides and corners of the phone are well cushioned and the included screen protector covers the touch screen without affecting its performance.  There are protective flaps over the charging port and headphone jack, which close securely when they are not in use.  The on/off and volume buttons are completely covered by protruding buttons which operate without any problems by pressing on them.  There are openings for the Home button (it is the only button not covered), earpiece, light and proximity sensors, both cameras, flash, speaker and microphones.The holster holds the phone very firmly, so firmly that it is difficult to release the phone from the holster with only one hand.  This is not an issue for me, however, because I do not use the holster on my belt.  I have used the holster on the sun visor of my car and it keeps the phone close while driving.  The kickstand on the holster performs its function well and holds the phone at a comfortable viewing angle when the phone is on a table and I am seated.When the phone is laying on a flat surface its back, the rubberized material of the case keeps the phone firmly in place.  However, the phone slides easily when placed face (screen) down on a flat surface.  I therefore usually lay the phone on its back when putting it down on a flat surface and rely on the screen protector to prevent any potential damage to the screen.Installing my phone in this case was challenging.  Although the process was fairly intuitive, I had difficulty removing the screen protector from its holder.  The directions included in the box, which consisted only of a simple diagram, were useless and the on-line directions on Otter's website were not any more helpful.  Unfortunately, by the time I finally got the phone installed in the case, there was a permanent scratch on the membrane of the screen protector, but this does not interfere with viewing the screen.  I eventually found an instruction video by a user on removing the membrane on YouTube, but only after I had installed the phone in the case.This case substantially increases the size of the Galaxy S4.  I usually keep my phone in my side pants pocket and inserting and removing the phone from this pocket is somewhat difficult with this case on the phone - considerably more difficult than with other cases I have tried.  On the other hand, this case offers excellent protection for the phone.  I think it would be most effective for those who leave their phones out in the open for long periods of time or who work in dusty or rugged conditions, such as in construction.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: My wife breaks phones. She breaks a lot of phones. I finally got her to convert off of a keyboard smart phone onto an S4 and then wrapped it in this Otterbox. reviewText: It was a bit of a challenge to get the Defender open to insert S4 but that might be a good thing in the long run..Total weight on digital scale with the holster attached reads just over 7 ounces.  Over 4oz without the plastic holster attached.When the clip on plastic holster is not attached it still fits into a pants pocket which is how I like to carry my phone.  If you like it on your belt or waist band the holster with click can be put on the front or back of the case...  that is, screen covered or showing as it's clipped onto your person.Yes, the buttons on the edge of the phone are a bit harder to press through the protective surround, but nothing horrible and serves as a reminder that your S4 is protected well.  Charge port and headphone port have flexible parts of the case to seal them, but attached on one side so can't be removed and lost.Don't expect the "vibrate" function to be as pronounced and useful as it was before as the S4 is that much more insulated from your person to feel the vibrations as before...This Defender is not waterproof rated even if it seems that way.Otterbox has a new case that is waterproof if that is what you need.  It's the new "Pursuit Series"Clear part that goes over your screen is very clear and touch screen feels just the same as without to me.it is attached to a snap on frame that is part of the case and NOT a press on static type film.Although, with the new Gorrilla Glass 3 Samsung is using on the new S4 I never had a worry about screen scratches even with nothing over the glass.  More protection is welcome as long as it works as well as the Otterbox design.One BIG thing I like about this case that I didn't expect was that the sides stick up far enough above the screen that I don't press screen icons close to the edges by accident just from holding the phone. Hooray!I'm sure I won't be the only person that will find this as an unadvertised feature...If you can't find the "Kickstand" feature, just open the clip as far as it will go and press the latch on the case, it will catch on that part and hold it open so you can set the Defender at an angle on table etc.I do like this case so far and hope that it saves the insurance deductable if I ever drop it... at that point I would raise my review to 5 stars "I love It" rating.Now for long term field testing...  I always update my reviews if need be.

reviewText: I just recently purchased this product and so far, I love it.  I have not had any problems with the holster.  It holds the case pretty well.  I do have some trouble trying to open the case to access my phone, but I think it's because I suffer from arthritis.  The screen protector is not meant to fit like a screen protector that fits snug on the screen; therefore, I purchased a separate clear lifetime warranty screen protector and placed it on my cell phone screen for added protected from scratches. I highly recommended purchasing an additional screen protector. The holster has a clip on the back if you want to clip it to your belt bucket.  I have not tried doing that, yet.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: The OtterBox Defender is the best case for the Galaxy S4 in my opinion. It is bulky, but makes it easier for me to hold the phone. The Galaxy S4 is so light and thin on it's own, I always feel like the phone will go flying out of my hand at any moment. I had a thin silicone case before I got the OtterBox and I was always worried about dropping it because it was very slippery, but the Defender has the rubber part on the outside which provides for an excellent grip. I never worry about dropping my phone anymore because it's easier to hold, but if I do drop it (or my daughter) I know it will be protected.It is very hard to get the case off if you need to clean it. I like to clean my phone about once a week because with these cases dirt and dust tend to get trapped under the built in screen protector. Those are my only complaints (hard to remove and collects dirt very easily under the screen protector). But I'll gladly deal with those minor problems to have my phone protected from drops!
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: I heard first hand and read many a tale of phones that survived significant falls due to this case and I did not want to pay for insurance any more (especially now that I have multiple android phones available as backups) so I decided to give this a try.The two plastic pieces snap together nicely and come apart well (lift at the tabs).The rubber that wraps around these two plastic pieces seems to be a very good material and should last a long time and should have no problem with being removed and replaced many many times.  Plus it make the phone feel good and non-slippery in hand as you use it.The clear screen protector was okay, but I did eventually remove it and the double sided tape that held it into place came off quite well with little to no residue.  I put on a Steinheil Spigen SGP Ultra Crystal screen protector instead.  There are many advantages to having a screen protector of the highest quality and physically attached to the screen, but the biggest one is that should the screen crack, it will still be usable.  My wife dropped her phone and was able to use it just fine for months with a very cracked screen.  It is now our daily alarm clock.I had to shave and round off and the prongs at the bottom around the USB port so that it would fit into my modified SmartDock, which also has 3 parts removed so that I do not have to take off the case for either my S4 or my wife's Note II.  Well, I have to take the rubber part off of this case, but that is no real issue.  It was also required for the MHL 2.0's rather large MicroUSB plug to fit without removing the case.I am generally afraid to handle my phone without this protector on and with it on, I feel I can use my phone all I want without fear.The belt clip fits well and does not seem like it would break or slide off as easily as past ones have for me.  Update: It has slid off a couple of times these past few months, however the phone is none the worse and I have a tracker enabled should I discover it missing.One negative is that I can never feel it vibrate (keep reading for an update on this point)Another is that the clip is uncomfortable when I do not have a shirt tucked in.Another negative is that, while the clip allows you to stand it up in landscape mode, it is at too sharp an angle (about 85 degrees I'd say... I think 60 to 75 degrees may be better)After getting this Case, I purchased the Samsung EP-CI950IBUSTA Wireless Charging Cover and found that this case does not work well with the thickness of the new back cover.  I finally got it to snap together by removing the inner lining of the plastic case for the back of the phone.The unexpected bonus of the tight fit is that I can now fell the S4 vibration alarm when using the Otterbox case. Very nice side effect.Overall, now 5 months later, I am very pleased with this purchase.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue
