reviewText: I always take care of my smart phones.  They usually look new when I am done with them.  My last phone was a Motorola Droid, which I housed in a TPU case.  It looked nice and protected well for scratches. However, when taking one of my walks I tripped. The phone did not fall far - but it was far enough.  Devastation!My new phone is a Samsung S4.  I love the phone - but it does not seem as sturdy as my old Droid. And that Droid shattered. So I need to protect my S4.  I purchased two top rated cases to see what is best for my needs: the OtterBox Defender and the Trident AMS Kraken.Summary:Both the Kraken and the OtterBox Defender were real close for my needs.  The one that I ended up using is the Trident AMS Kraken.My final choice was because I felt the Kraken to be somewhat better than the OtterBox.  I got quite frustrated by the proximity sensor not working correctly with the OtterBox.  This prevented me from accessing the phone after the screen turned off during calls.  I also felt that the body of the Kraken would protect the phone better.If interested in my reviews, I have another write up for the Trident AMS Kraken case.Detailed review of the OtterBox Defender case:Appearance:  I chose the blue color.  Very nice shade.  The case consists of a colored polycarbonate shell covered with a slab of black silicon. Of course the case made my thin phone look huge - but that is the price that one pays for protection.  I feel that the OtterBox Defender looks plain.Physical characteristics:The inner polycarbonate shell acts like a skeleton, adding strength to the phone.  The outer silicon liner cushions the phone and absorbs most of the shock.The inner shell goes together easily and has a good fit.  Taking it apart to clean the phone was at first hard.  After a few times it was not so bad.The silicon is stiffer than that used in many products because it is so thick.  It extends over each corner of the phone.  The silicon is easy to install. If you place the phone face down the surface is protected by the silicon.  This seems to be a very high quality silicon and will protect the phone against most small accidents.The silicon provides two additional features: the volume and the power switch are covered, and there are plugs for the headphone jack and the USB connector.  The volume and power switch are well protected, but they are also hard to use. The silicon is just too thick and stiff.  At least the odds are that the power switch being accidently pressed while in one's pocket is slim. Of course a substitute when the screen is off is to press the home button. But you really should be able to easily use the power switch as needed.  The headphone jack cover works great.  The USB connector cover fits well - but it is sometimes difficult to guide a USB connector into place.  This sometimes is frustrating connecting power to the phone.There are no cutouts or other consideration for ventilation.  Most of the time the Samsung S4 runs cool.  But at times it did get very warm.The polycarbonate front bevel extends enough to protect the screen, but not too much to obstruct any of the active portion of the screen.  Unlike other cases, the notification bar can readily be accessed without any extra effort.  No fear of hitting wrong buttons because there is not room for your fingers.The soft silicon outer shell makes it simple when you put the phone down on a surface.  It will not slip.  It will not damage the surface. Yet it is sufficiently smooth to easily slip in or out of your pocket.The silicon does not pick up pet hair.Other factors:Sound quality - phone calls:  The phone speaker worked quite well.  When talking on the phone you can easily hear the other party.  Now for the bad news. The microphone does not work well in this case.  The other party can hear you, along with echoes and muffled sound.  I got continuous complaints from people that could not hear me properly when on calls.Sound quality - phone speaker for music: no degradation of sound quality.  Not that the S4 speaker is that great in the first place .. but the case does not make it any worse.Sensor access: The S4 proximity sensor does not work with this case.  Once activated, the sensor gets stuck (confirm with the CPU-Z and AndroSendor tools).  Why is this important?  One use of the proximity sensor is to determine when to turn off the screen.  If you get a phone call and you put the phone to your ear, the proximity sensor will turn off the screen. Access to the touch screen is prevented so that you cannot accidentally press buttons. The problem is that the sensor does not detect when the phone is moved away from the ear.  When you move the screen away from your ear, the screen should become visible and you should be able to use the touch screen. With the proximity sensor not working, the screen does not free up until the other party hangs up from your call.  If the other person does not hang up you cannot use your screen again! During the call you cannot look up contacts, or do any of the other multi-tasking that your phone is designed for.  On some S4 forums, I read that black cases do not seem to have as much of this problem.  I also read that some people claim use of a black magic marker around the opening where the sensor is located helps.  I tried using a black magic marker and the sensor worked better - but still not consistently.  Carefully applied you can hardly see the black.Screen protector: the top portion of the polycarbonate shell has an integrated screen protector.  This is the thickest screen protector that I have used.  It seems quite rugged. It resists fingerprints and cleans up quite easily.  The phone's touch screen worked surprisingly well behind this plastic.  However, it felt different - the screen was close, but not as responsive as with other cases with more pliable films. I did feel comfortable that the screen was well protected.Support: I called OtterBox support because of problems with the proximity sensor.  First contact had a new inner shell that was shipped immediately.  There was no attempt to support beyond that.  When I continued to complain, they readily permitted me to return the case for a refund. So good news is that they took responsibility to provide a refund. Bad news is that they did not actually try to solve my problem.  If this was a unique problem I could understand.  However, looking at other forums I see that the sensor problem is fairly widespread. I would think that it would be more responsible of OtterBox if they would solve the problem.  That said, my son-in-law has an S4 with an OtterBox defender (grey case).  Works perfectly for him.Belt clip:  Sturdy and works.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: Solid construction and great protection of both the phone itself and its screen. The accessibility of all the buttons and jacks, as well as the camera lens and speaker/microphones is perfect.This is a terrific case. My only criticism is the case is a bit difficult to take apart for cleaning (dust can accumulate on the inside of the front screen over the period of a month or two). I feel one of these assembly/dis-assembly runs is going to break the locking tabs that hold the hard plastic portion of the case together). the rubber surround is a great shock absorberI do not comment on thin versus thick or aesthetics. reviewText: I made the mistake of first purchasing an i-Blason case for $13.99 from Amazon. The pictures of the case made it look very solid, but once I got it, I was VERY disappointed. It did not fit correctly at all, and the holster supplied with it only allowed you to put the phone into it face down, meaning once the phone was holstered, you had no access to the screen anymore.I carried my Motorola Electrify phone for about 1.5 years, and from day 1, it was in an Otterbox Defender case. I loved it. So, after I sent back the cheapo case, from i-Blason, I decided to spend the extra money and get the Otterbox Defender.I ordered my defender case from Ebay, since I was able to get it there for $29.99 shipped, and at the time, Amazon was $38.50, but as I write this, Amazon is now at $31, which I would have paid the extra $2 to buy it from Amazon (faster shipping with Prime, and great customer service).I have used the case now for a few days, and really like it. The case fits the phone perfectly, and was easy to install. The phone, once in the case, slides into the holster both face up, and face down.The reason I am taking away half a star is because the power button is extremely difficult to activate. You have to really push hard to get the screen to turn on and off. On my old Otterbox case, with the Electrify phone, it only took a small amount of force to get the button to work.Other than that, the case is well worth the extra money you will spend over the cheaper, inferior cases.

reviewText: Let's face it, most of us will be wedded to our current smartphone until our contract runs out. And high end smartphones are very expensive to replace if you damage them. This case gives you the best shot at making it past the two year mark without damaging your phone through inadvertent drops, scratches, flexes, and the like.This case appears substantial, and cradles the Galaxy S4 without any pressure points. By all accounts it looks well made and capable of doing a good job of protecting its contents (though I've not tried the protection by dropping the phone yet).The main drawback of this case is that it takes a slim, good looking phone and makes it look like a kid's toy. There's a thick rubberized cover completely covering five sides of the phone. All buttons and ports are accessible, but the whole thing looks like its more fit for a worksite rather than a corporate setting. Elegance and beauty are lost in the quest for protection.Its a tradeoff of elegance versus protection. I traded off the former for the latter.

reviewText: 6/10/14 update: Still going strong folks. This is the best case I ever got....and I don't even care that the price has dropped to $26. It was worth every penny then, and an even better bargain now. I should also note that the plastic screen protector is still great....and that's with two kids who love to jump on me constantly. I haven't found anything better for my S4. I think enough of this that after a year I am updating it. Good job, Otterbox! :)Price update June 14: Saw it drop to 31 and change, then back up.Update 6/11/13: Just an FYI folks, this is currently at 34.82 and free shipping! This is a no brainer, and a steal. None of the stores around me are giving any kind of discount....if they have it.I still love this case, but I did want to let you know that if you rely on the vibration to notify you, you might miss some calls. This does soften the vibration quite a bit. If you are holding it, it's not a problem, but sometimes, when it is  on my belt with a shirt tucked in, and I am walking, I do not feel the vibration. There is no problem if I am still. I also think that this is in part due to the phone. The vibrate strength, even on full, is not as strong as my old phone, so the extra cushion from the case just softens it up even more....but you know what, this weekend I have seen three people with this phone and Belkin cases and they all had cracked glass!After getting a Belkin case for my S4, it took me only an hour to go out and buy theOtterbox 77-27434 Defender Series and Holster Case for Samsung Galaxy S 4 - 1 Pack - Retail Packaging - Black. The difference is night and day and while this is more than twice the price of the Belkin it is totally worth it! Plus, you don't need to spend money on a screen protector, so it really isn't that much more.The Defender is really a three piece, full coverage, case. It provides full coverage for your S4, corners, back, front, screen and it has flip covers for the charger connection, etc., and those flips flip up easily, even without fingernails. The case itself provides excellent grip all around without being intrusive. It is a little difficult pressing the buttons on the face, but my fingers are a little big. One of my FAVORITE things is the screen protector....NO bubbles! Yup, you heard me right, no bubbles. That's because you don't actually have to "apply" the protector to the screen. This is awesome. If you look at every screen protector I have reviewed for my iPhones and iPads, they all had bubbles....I have come to hate bubbles, and thought I would have to learn to live with them. I am here to tell you, I am now bubble free (and so is my wife)!!!When pressing the side buttons you do have to press a little hard, but for the protection you get, it's fine. Also, the openings for the camera are angled so that the thick case does not appear in the pictures. The case itself is micro-textured to provide good grip without feeling rough.There is NO interference at all with using the IR when reading and scrolling down by nodding my head or turning a page with a wave of my hand. Sharing pictures and video work equally as well with no perceptible interference. The only real issue is that I did notice a slight difference in wi-fi reception in our house with the case on. It is slightly weaker, but nothing big, and after one day I don't even think about it. The entire screen isvisible and nothing is blocked.The only thing that I would knock half a star for is the clip is uncomfortable and digs into my skin when it's on my belt, and is especially bad when my shirt is not tucked in. They could have made this better, and I wonder ifI will come and downgrade this to 4 stars later because of this. For now, I will say 4.5 stars with an easy round-up to 5.Instructions when installing your phone:CAREFULLY remove the rubber gasket, using your fingernails. There are little spaces along the sides. You need to use these to seperate it or you risk breaking it. Once that is done, the rest is easy. Try not to touch the inner portion of the screen as it comes perfectly clean (at least it did on both of ours). Putting everything together after this pointis easy and takes less than 30 seconds. Gently click everything together and you are ready to go.We both love this case and I highly recommend it.

reviewText: ****I'm not sure this surprisingly complicated device has ever been explained adequately in the 2,397 reviews that have preceded mine, so I'll take a shot at it.When disassembled as far as you're supposed to go it consists of four pieces.  You need to disassemble it in order to insert your phone, then reassemble it.1. HolsterStart by removing the piece with the spring-loaded clip, called the holster, by pressing on the big tab on one side.The holster is designed to carry the case proper.  You can insert the phone into the holster so the screen faces out for ready use or in for better protection of the screen.  For example, you might want the screen facing in if the mine shaft you're at the bottom of is about to cave in and there would be lots of coal dust floating around.  On the other hand, if you're expecting a call from Barack Obama in the next few minutes, as I always am, you'd want the screen facing out so you could just flip the phone a little towards your face and know whether it's he.  Or is that He?You attach the holster to your belt or your waistband or your tool belt or your love handles using the clip, which then doesn't want to let go, which is good for your phone's health but which also means sometimes it won't let go when you want it to, which problem you can sometimes solve by pushing down a little as you open the clip.Unlike the other three pieces, the holster is optional.  For example, if you're about to engage in a bout of sumo wrestling you might want to ditch the holster altogether and just tuck the phone in its case into your mawashi.The holster adds considerable bulk and a tiny bit of weight (58 grams), but there are three benefits to the holster even if you never clip it to your suspenders or your right eyebrow region when you're drunk to see whether you can simulate Google Glass.  (Answer: No.)-- Kickstand.  The holster also acts as a kickstand so you can set your phone on a table in landscape orientation and watch a movie or something.  To deploy the kickstand, rotate the clip so the top of it, the part nearer the "r" of "Otter," not the "O," is resting just above the big tab you used in the step above.  You may rotate the clip 180 degrees and your SG4's display will re-orient itself, but the whole device then teeters a little bit after you set it down and is not really designed to be used this way.-- Grabbing point.  The holster's clip when aligned in the non-kickstand orientation also makes it especially easy to hold the phone.  In your left hand you place your thumb along the left edge of the phone in the usual manner but you can wrap the pads of your other fingers around the far (right) side of the clip instead of having to reach all the way around the back to the much thinner right side of the phone, which also risks that you will click a live spot on the screen.-- Shock-resistance.  Although I'm no engineer, my guess is that the holster adds protection against damage to your phone if it's dropped onto a hard enough surface from high enough up.2. Rubber shellOnce you've removed the holster you need to remove the rubber-like shell that will surround the back of your phone and wrap around the edges to barely encroach on the phone's screen.  This is a precisely engineed piece of neoprene or whatever it is that because of its elasticity provides most of the resistance against impact damage.To remove it, start by opening the two very sturdy port covers -- one at the top and one at the bottom -- so they don't impede your progress or tear in case you get too rough.  Then choose a corner and pry away at it till you see how the rubber shell is attached.  If you've chosen the upper left corner, use the pad of your left thumb to push the very outside corner away from you, towards the back of the case.  Eventually you will see how the rubber shell can be pushed away a little bit from the hard plastic clamshell it encases.  Once you've broken a corner loose you can open up more and more of the rubber shell along the top.  Then you can push the rubber shell away from the top right corner, and then the next corner along, and pretty soon it's loose.Although the manufacturer doesn't says so anywhere, this precisely engineered shell is gluten-free and contains no trans-fats.3 and 4. Two clamshell piecesThe two mating, hard plastic pieces of the clamshell are what most interiorally enclose your phone.  The front and the back pieces are connected by tabs on the back that fit into slots on the front.  There is one at the top, there are two equally spaced on each side, and there are two at the bottom, for a total of seven.To disassemble the clamshell, press on the back piece where a tab is so it no longer lives in its slot on the front piece.  You're going to gradually separate the pieces, and you have to start with any tab or pair of adjacent tabs that works.  Just keep pressing on one tab or another and trying to separate the pieces till they come loose at that point.  Once you've separated that tab and its slot, use your fingers to make sure that little gap doesn't close and move along to the next tab, then push it in and separate it from its slot.  This is kind of fiddly, but you can do it.  After a few of these separations of the tabs and their slots, pretty soon the two clamshell pieces will come apart.****Whew.Now, here's how to re-assemble the whole thing with your phone inside, which is why you spent so much money for this product.  Lay your phone carefully into the back piece (mine is labelled "MADE IN MEXICO" for those who care, although I don't know why you would) of the clamshell and then press the top piece of the clamshell onto it, making sure to engage all seven tabs you just so laboriously disengaged.  Unlike some of the steps of disassembly and the next step, this part of assembly is easy.Re-attach the rubber shell.  Shove a corner of the encased phone into a corner of the rubber shell, then start fitting and smoothing with your fingers in one direction and the other.  Eventually you'll get the clamshell entirely inside the rubber shell.  Check every millimeter of all four edges around the screen to make sure there are no gaps.  If there are, just push the rubber against the plastic till it behaves.  If it doesn't, I recommend beating severely on the plastic with a 5-pound sledge hammer till . . . fff Wait, no I don’t.  Re-write this.You're done.  You've disassembled the OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4 - Retail Packaging - Black, you've inserted your phone, and you've reassembled the whole thing.  Attach the case to the holster if you want and you're ready to go.****If you bought this product without having read this very review on Amazon, would you be able to perform these necessary steps based solely on the instructions included with the product?  The answer is an indisputable No unless you have as much free time and patience as I have.  For this I subtract one star.

reviewText: Okay so you can read all the reviews and they all say the same thing...great case, great protection (second to none), fits is dead on, can't get a better case...etc..I wanted to point out some basic things and then let you the reader who is currently in the buying mood for your new expensive smartphone...here goes.1) All the happy loyal customers say one thing more than anything else, it's a great case for protection.  Don't read this, buy the case and then write a crappy review that says, "love the case but it makes my phone too BIG!" or "love the protection but my smartphone no longer fits into my skinny jeans..."  you get the point.  This case is about PROTECTION.  You simply can't get a better fitting case for PROTECTION.2) You just invested in a $700 or more smartphone/tablet/device that can do anything and more than most desktops found in many homes across the planet.  Why would you not invest a few bucks into PROTECTING your investment?  It takes one simple drop to chip the sides or paint not to mention that the front case could crack.  Yes, there are plans now that allow you to replace your phone, but why go through the hassle of starting new again.3) Yes, the plastic screen protection that comes with it is not that great, but if you have owned an Otterbox before you know the deal.  Peel that one off, invest in a real screen protection film or better yet, get a Tempered Glass Protection screen.4) And as everyone who has owned an Otterbox before knows, the hard clip case is either useless and you never really carry it or you are someone who carries their phone on your hip all the time.  I myself, do not.5) The rubber grip is just enough to be able to shove the phone in your back pocket without too much trouble and yet it has enough grip that it doesn't jump out of your hand while using it one handed.All in all, an excellent case.  You just bought yourself a pretty expensive piece of technology, protect it and forget about the fact that it doesn't have cute little bunnies on it or it isn't olive or baby blue.

reviewText: This is an excellent product that does exactly what it sets out to do, protect your phone.  The reason I give it a three star rating is because for the protection, you seriously compromise the phone's sleek profile.  Make no mistake about it, this case is bulky and heavy.  Two other factors that make it unsuitable for my use:  First, the built in glass protector.  I haven't used one of these in years.  The advent of Gorilla Glass makes this kind of protection unnecessary, in my opinion.  Plus, when smudged, I like being able to clean glass, not a plastic membrane.  Second, and more distracting is the belt clip, or more specifically, the top of the belt clip.  This may not be applicable to those who are more svelte but for me, it's constantly digging into my side.  Last, the port covers sound like a good idea in theory however, I found the inconvenience of having to pry open the cover to the respective port, then keep it open with one finger while trying to attach the charger or headphones, not worth the effort.  So, for me, as good as this case is, the bottom line is, it's overkill.  However, if you can live with these factors, and it seems like, according to the reviews, a lot people can, than you can't beat The Defender.

reviewText: Simply put OtterBox Defender system is pretty much the best protection you can get for your phone.  For protection against splashes, spills, drops and falls nothing really compares.  You have easy access to all the ports, camera and flash while still getting tons of protection.  The screen is also covered by a very strong yet sensitive to touch polycarbonate covering.  In fact the only thing I didn't like was screen protector as it was just slightly raised form my phone screen so it gave touching the screen a popping sensation.  Other than that it is great.  If you have any questions, please feel free to leave a comment below and I will try to answer it.

reviewText: I was a little reluctant to spend the kind of money on "a stupid cell phone case" as this seems to command, but two things had me go for it:  (1) my sweetie wanted the one with the trees on the back plus the holster, and (2) Amazon had the best price.  And it was still a "stupid cell phone case".  So I got two - the one with the trees and the hornet one for me.Just got these yesterday and I am changing my assessment to "amazingly well engineered cell phone case".  Few aftermarket things fit a product as well as this does, and it is both functional and beautiful.I was really reluctant to have a case that impeded sliding into my pocket because of it's sticky material (silicone rubbers, etc.) and this case does NOT suffer from that problem.  Yes, it makes the phone marginally larger, but it slides right into my pocket without resistance.  Very helpful for when it rings in your pocket while you are driving - slips out easily.All in all, very worth the cost; everything fits so precisely.  You can tell that they spent a LOT of time in design and craftsmanship; truly a no-nonsense provider that makes really incredible stuff.  What a refreshing situation.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: This is the third one I buy for my galaxy 4s phone, like to change them around and really great item to have.

reviewText: It's worth the investment to protect your $600 phone.  I've dropped my phone from about 4 feet and no issues. If moisture gets near the menu button, you can get rainbows under your screen protector.  Easy fix is to take the phone out and clean it up.  I'd definitely purchase again.

reviewText: I'm the type of person who's sometime afraid to just take something apart by unsnapping it without directions.  This is one of those products.  There is/are no directions for putting the phone inside the case.  You're just supposed to instinctively know to just man handle it until you get it open.  Hope you don't break the plastic part.  I elected to replace the snap in back part with the clip with the BLack Leather Belt Holster Pouch Clip,B00D6NRRD6.  Turns out it was the right decision for me.  Especially considering the phone comes off the holster with a flick of the wrist.  No real warm and fuzzy feeling with the holster.  More protection with the pouch with a belt loop as opposed to a belt clip.  Not going anywhere!Only real issue with this product are the two side buttons.  They have to be pressed especially hard to engage but it also prevents accidents.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: I can't get my phone in my pocket with this on. reviewText: Case works great!  I bought a GS4 at full retail for my wife so we could keep our grandfathered unlimited data.  Since it was a full-retail device I needed nothing less than full protection.  Perfect solution!My kids can drop this phone while they play their Angry Birds all they want and I don't freak out.  It can be thrown into my wife's bottomless pocketbook without concern of getting damaged by whatever it is that attacks my hand whenever I need to search for her car keys.The included screen protector is connected to the hard plastic shell and there is a slight oily haze between the device and the protector.  I expected this and purchased a Zagg screen.  Haven't installed it yet, but when I do I will remove the included OtterBox screen protector and just use the Zagg protector.I tested out mySamsung Wireless Charging Coverwith this Defender case and can report that it DOES NOT fit.  Don't use this Defender case unless it's the OEM GS4 battery cover.The purple color is true to the pictures.  Looks good with the black mist GS4.I like that this cover provides a good grip to the phone.  The stock GS4 is very slippery.This Defender case works fine with mySamsung Galaxy Universal Car Mount.  It grips the case well with a slight squeeze of the side clamps.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: I'd tried another heavy duty case and the Otterbox is definitely the best.  I mountain bike and like to have my phone with me to track my rides and as a GPS mapper, so I need something heavy duty.  It's construction is solid and sound and it attaches and removes easily from the phone.  Much better than any other heavy duty case I've tried.  I ordered mine in royal blue and it's paid off - recently I finished a ride, went to turn the ride tracking app off, and my phone wasn't in the holster (that's the only thing - you have to make sure the phone snaps securely in to the holster!).  Thankfully, I hadn't ridden too far since I'd last had it out.  I backtracked, and found it sitting on the trail with no harm done other than being a little dirty.  Other than that, I haven't had any real occasion to evaluate how well it protects - and hope to avoid that!  But I'm as confident in it as I can be in any phone case of this type.  Definitely recommended.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: I originally purchased this for my guy's S4 Active. I even went on the OtterBox website to research which case type would fit the S4 Active. I tried fitting it on my S4 (not an Active) and it fit like a glove. My guy loves OtterBox but it looks like they don't currently have a case that fits the Active phone. Even AT&T, the only carrier selling the Active, doesn't sell a case for it; neither does Samsung, which is unheard of and we looked everywhere (Radio Shack, BestBuy, etc.). title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++January 2014 update: While this is a good product, I think it was built for those the do NOT change batteries.  If you put it together, and don't take it apart to change batteries, then it will last a life time.  But, and a huge but, if you change batteries, as I do, then the little clips that hold the case together, will start to break and render the case useless.  That is if you don't use the rubber outer protector.  This will keep the inner case together.Bottom line is I will order another one as the price has dropped.+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++I guess I should read descriptions more, because I didn't realize this comes with a screen protector too.  Well made and about 15 bucks cheaper than buying it locally from my provider.This is an awesome protector for any phone, and the plastic screen saver doesn't seem to hamper the works of the original touch screen at all.  Cleaning is easy, just wipe it without worry about messing up the screen of the phone.  The belt clip takes some getting used to, but after about two days use, I have figured out the best way to wear it with my daily activities, (the clip swivels so you can rotate it 360 degrees.At first, it was aggravating with the very tight fit of the case and holster, because the first time I tried to change the battery, it actually took some negotiation and patience to get everything back off.  Yes, it's that much of an exact fit. But, as the saying goes, "practice makes better" so have I become with changing batteries and thus, it's not that much of a hassle anymore.I don't like the fact that the only way you can clip it to a belt if via a "pin" contraption, instead of both, the clip and a "loop", gives this a thumbs down. I prefer a "Loop" while at work and also out in public as it makes it really difficult to accidently become unattached with the phone or to have it "lifted" from you by a thief.The main reason I am so adamant about a "loop" over a clip is that it is easier than most will admit to dislodge a clip from your belt and you will not even know it until it's too late and you have totally lost your phone. Once, while getting out of my vehicle to pump some gas, I accidently dislodged my phone from my  belt and my phone fell to the pavement while I was pumping gas... After returning from paying for it, I just happened to look down and low and behold, there laid my phone right under the door of my vehicle. If I had been I a hurry or wasn't so attentive, I would have drove off and thus, been out of a phone and would have had to pay full price for a replacement, not to mention what the increased bill could have been if someone had found it and decided to dial 900 numbers on my account.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case and Holster for Samsung Galaxy S4  - Carrier Packaging - Navy/Blue

reviewText: Ok, maybe it is age related but I'm reasonably technical.  I found the pictograph Welcome to Planet Otterbox quick start guide grossly inadequate.  I would recommend actual photos as opposed to drawings and close ups as to where to push, pull or stick your knife blade to get the darn thing open.  If it offers as much protection as it takes to get the thing on your phone it will be super.  I was able to get it open and as I mentioned, my trusty pocket knife was invaluable getting the darn thing open.  Once it was open it was easy to get my phone into it.  It does seem that it is well constructed but it is very bulky with the belt clip.  It isn't too bad without the belt clip.  I'm not overly fond of belt or  pocket clips.  With all of the publicity of nut jobs grabbing peoples phones, I feel better having it in my jeans pocket.  I have trouble getting it out so a thief would have to a very attractive female and overly friendly to get it out of my pocket.This does seem to offer a great deal of protection.  If you are a belt or pocket clip person, I suspect you would love it.  I do like the flaps that protect the ports but it was a bit of a push to get the power port open wide enough for my charger.

reviewText: When I purchased my S4 Active I expected that it would handle bumps and am occasion scrape better than the regular S4.  After a couple of scrapes on the glass screen (I've never scraped a screen before - always owned iPhones) I decided to put away the cheap case options and go for the tried and true.  I ended up with the Otterbox Defender for the Active and I am pleased.  I DO have an extra battery for my phone and changing out batteries will be a hassle, but that is one I am willing to deal with in order to gain the two layer protection that Otterbox provides.I've been using Otterboxes for the past 4 years and they have continued to evolve and listen to customer feedback.  The result is a well fitting, well made product that is usable in all respects.  Usability when being put on the device and usability when the device is in use.  All of the buttons and the screen are responsive.  The earphone flap fits nice and snug back in it's spot.Everything just fits and works.  Great holster as usual and a great case at a great price (the gray / white was considerably cheaper than the straight black ... so I went for that one).The case looks nice on the Active and will provide the protection I have come to expect from Otter.  I THOUGHT the Active would be a little more rugged ... but I was wrong.  It may have a look that pretends to be ruggedized, but it is not.  Put a case on it and it will fare better.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for Samsung Galaxy S4 Active - Retail Packaging - Gray/White

reviewText: I have one of these on my SIII, so I recommended it for my son-in-law's S4. If you're at all careless with your phone, this is the case to have. The inner case comes in two halves that snap together VERY securely. Getting it apart to change the battery or add an microSD card is really difficult. The face of the inner case has a clear, hard plastic screen protector. Make sure the phone screen and the inner side of the case protector are really, really clean before you assemble the halves. Otherwise, you'll discover just how difficult they are to get apart. The outer case is molded rubber that entirely covers the back and sides of the case, and wraps around to lock on the front. The case is available in several color combinations. OtterBox doesn't advertise this case as being waterproof, but it will certainly withstand full immersion long enough to be quickly retrieved from a toilet bowl or sink and a subsequent rinse-off. We have 6 Otterbox Defender Series cases -- 4 for various phones and two for tablets. I wouldn't buy any other.

reviewText: I purchased two cases to try with my Moto X.  An Incipio Dual Pro and the Otterbox Commuter.The executive summary is this, if you can handle having a case that's slightly bigger, slightly heavier, and in general slightly bulkier, the Otterbox commuter is hands down the more protective and better designed case.  The Otterbox offers:1. Cushion zones.  I don't know what else to call it.  The inner corners of the rubber part of the case is ribbed, so that the outside corner of the case is actually lifted off the outside corner of the phone.  This allows the case to absorb some of the fall if you phone falls down.2. Harder rubber.  I think they did this to make the cushion zones in the corners effective, but the rubber closely resembles hard plastic now in the corners.3. Covers for the ports to keep out dust and sand and stuff.When comparing the two cases against each other (Incipio vs Otterbox):1. Otterbox is 10 grams heavier, 44 grams vs 34 grams for the Incipio (as reference, there are 29 grams to an ounce).  It doesn't sound like much but my hand that holds the phone can tell.2. Otterbox is wider and longer.  It's 135mm long on the phone and 73mm wide.  The Incipio is 130mm long and 69mm wide.  Again, the difference is small, but my hands (which are small for a guy) do not like the feel of the Otterbox.3. Otterbox is the better case for protection.  Incipio is the better case for holding the phone.  And they are about equal in price after you factor in that the Incipio does not include a screen protector.My advice is to buy a couple of cases and see what you like.  I "like" the Incipio better, but I bet my phone will get damaged more easily with it.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Motorola Moto X - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: I also own this case for the GS4 also and it looks roughly the same. I only recently got the case for the X, so I can only assume over time it will end up wearing the same as that of my S4. The only difference between the two phones seems to be that the positioning of the buttons on the X requires a bit of trickery to ensure the plastic can sufficiently wrap around the sides. The case comes as two pieces, an inner silicone layer with space made in the corners for the material to squish in the event of impact. The outer layer is a hard plastic that is surprisingly durable. I have not been very kind to the case and it only shows impact damage on the bottom corner plastic from landing in some gravel. The covers over the ports are nice and hold well; the plastic and silicone do not show any signs of wear even after continuous disassembly/reassembly on my S4. The only "bad" thing about this case is the screen protector it comes with. It is thick, cut smaller than the lip of the case(why?) and does that awful rainbow thing when it gets fingerprints and oil on it, which it frequently does.

reviewText: The wallet case would be nice, if it were not so thick.The commuter case is thicker than the Defender case (without the Defender's holster), though the outside is more slick, allowing for easier insertion and removal from a pocket, assuming one can fit it in one's pocket.There is no built in screen protector, but one that must be installed.  Once installed, I did not like the appearance of the screen protector, because it has that oily rainbow appearance that happens with some, thus ruining the appearance of my iPhone screen.  So, I removed the screen protector and trashed it.The plastic sides that hold the softer layer in, which in turn holds the phone, does not mesh well with the soft layer, leaving the appearance that it is not completely in place.  I kept trying to make it mesh or snap in place fully, but perhaps mine is defective.If one absolutely has to have a phone case with the wallet feature, this may be one of the better options, because it has Otterbox protection for your phone, which is worth something significant to the clumsy among us.  If that is an unnecessary feature, but one desires the protection, I think the Defender is a much better option.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: When you buy a case by OtterBox you know it will be quality and protective and this case does that. It is easy to get the iPhone in an out of too, which is nice. It has a flexible inner shell that goes into an outer hard shell that does a great job at protection.My curiosity with this case was the wallet part. I have a CaseMate wallet style case that is great, but it is hard to get the card or bill out of the wallet part. This case is much better. The slider on the back is easy to open, but secure, and it is much easier to get things in and out of. It holds about the thickness of three credit cards, maybe slightly more (a piece of paper). I also like how it encloses your cards and money from all sides, unlike my other case.My only problem is the thickness. The double shell already makes it thick and the wallet portion makes it even thicker. It adds about a little less than 1/4 to the thickness. My casemate case is much thinner. However, thickness comes with the wallet feature, you just have to decide if it is too thick.Not something I want in my pocket every day, but definitely something I would use when I didn't want to carry my full wallet.

reviewText: I tend to like Otterbox products - they may be bigger and bulky but they protect your phone very well. The Commuter for the iPhone 5s held a lot of interest for me. As an urbanite, I'm trying to get rid of the wallet bulk and go with one device, a few cards and a bit of cash. The wallet tray holds 3 cards and 2 folded very well bills. The tray, surprisingly, slides in and out without issues and feels secure.The case also comes with a screen protector, but I didn't use it since I have a Zagg cover on the screen. The phone doesn't seem to take up that much more space with the back tray. The case also doesn't seem to affect swiping and getting to the Notification Center on the phone.Overall for the price, it feels like I get a lot of value for the phone. I get a good degree of protection from drops and I'm able to carry a few cards and some cash at the expensive of size and bulk. It's a manageable tradeoff.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: I am happy with this item. It fits my iPhone 5S and has a small drawer for a credit card. I am also happy to see a Made in the USA mark on the hard plastic outer case that has the small drawer. The rubber like cover is Made in Malaysia.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: As soon as I took the case out of the package, I knew it was bad news. The inner silicone layer looked cheap, used or possibly not even an authentic Otterbox product. It did not fit my phone at all! I'm returning this one of course and just went to my local Bestbuy and got the real thing. There was a very noticeable difference when I opened the one from Bestbuy. It fit my phone perfectly and very happy with the case...as long as it's the real thing!
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: I like the idea of a wallet case for my iPhone and doing away with my wallet.  The fewer things to carry, the better.  But wallet cases are very limited.  The idea is that they are cases for occasional use, such as when you are going out for the night and only want to carry an ID and credit card.  This wallet case can only carry three cards or two cards and three folded bills.Otterbox Commuter cases are two piece cases that have a silicone layer covered by a hard shell.  They aren’t my favorite because the hardshell doesn’t quite fit right leaving tiny gaps.  Two piece cases take more effort to get on and off which is more of a problem on a case made for occasional use.  The black on black color scheme turns the handsome iPhone into an all-black design-free box.Otter likes to put rubber plugs over the jack openings which offers extra protection, but is a pain when you want to charge or plug in headphones.  The volume button covers work well, but the on/standby button cover make it stiff and lacking in tactile feel.  Otter provides a clear screen protector and applicator card.Cards fit in the wallet case by sliding down the back panel revealing the compartment.  The slide is stiff and there is no grip for your finger to press against.  You have to press against smooth sloping plastic.  When you get the slide open, you have to dig you finger nail under the top card so you can pry it up and out.This wallet case is too much trouble for me.  But if it fits your needs, this case should offer good protection and durability.  Two and a half stars.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: While this case does make your phone a little bulkier, I found that it was totally worth it. As a resident of SF that is constantly riding MUNI and BART, having my transit pass in my phone case makes it supper simple. It looks like I'm just scanning my phone as I get on. There's no fumbling for my wallet or through my backpack to get my pass out. It's already in my hand. It also came in handy going out at night, especially to clubs. All I put inside are my ID, my credit card, and my transit pass and I'm set to go. No need to carry my entire wallet. I've also used it to keep an ID and house key inside while running.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: I have used many "wallet" cases, the best of which have been the Cellet Zipper model.  But I get crap for having a zipper on my case.  Apparently that is not what a mans phone has.  So i bought this one.PRO:It is the best fitting of the ones I've used, and i fit my drivers lic. and 2 credit cards in it no problem.CON:Access to the cards is difficult because the slider is hard to push (it is super slippery).  Which means the back of the case is slippery.  Like fall out of your hand slippery.Other than that, it is OK.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: I have had the box for about two months.  The small strip of plastic along the bottom has already snapped in half.  I have superglued it back together, but it's a bad design there.  I don't even know how it broke; got home one day and discovered it was - hadn't dropped the case.  It could very likely have caught on something and snapped; it is flimsy and wiggles a bit (but only in that one spot).  Overall I got the Otter because they don't make an Incipio case for this newer iPhone, and I love having the slide in back for cards / cash.  There is more room in this one; I can fit two cards and a folded bill back there.  It is also more secure in the latching and easier to slide open than the Incipio - BUT - It is extremely hard to get the hard case off the rubber sleeve, which I have to do if I want to listen to music with anything other than the headphones it came with, because the case has a narrow profile near the headphone jack.This case could use some improvements with the hard case, but otherwise I like the spot for holding my stuff - a gal has to have a place for her stuff.  I also like it because I find the new phones so slim it's hard for me to hold them.  My hands are beat up a bit, so those slim, sexy phones just make my hands hurt when I try to hold them.  These thicker profile cases make it possible with much more ease.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: Will buy another one! I love this case. My job requires me to run around from place to place quickly and I hate having to lug my purse/wallet with me, but I need my drivers license and some cash. This does the trick, I always have my phone with me. My only complaint is it is a little uncomfortable on the ear, the ridge of the case is really hard.  The other improvement I would make would be to rubberize the sides of the case for better grip when using or sliding open the wallet. Its funny but I get a lot of compliments, "wow, thats an awesome case!"
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: This is another well made case from Otterbox. I've had Otterbox cases for my iPhones and iPads and they've always performed well. They aren't stylish, but they protect your device. I've used them for travel mostly, and have never been disappointed.This "Wallet Case" checks all the usual Otterbox, um, boxes: Protective? Check. Grippy? Check. 80's Volvo-like Styling? Check. Yep, it's an Otterbox all right.But one with a twist. Because this case resolves that nagging dilemma we all have: how do I carry my iPhone AND my credit and ID cards in one place?Dilemma resolved. This case is that place.Otterbox added a sliding tray on the back of one of their tough cases. From the front and back and the added "bump" isn't noticeable. In profile however or in the palm of your hand it's there alright. Think of the top of a 747 and you'll get the idea. A little curvature on an otherwise continuous line.In that bump of a tray you can fit a pair of credit cards and your driver's license. Great for the minimalist traveler or a night out clubbing. That is if you go to hipster clubs where geeky dual-purpose cases are cool.I don't go to clubs like that. I don't go to clubs. But if I did, this is the case I would take.Go ahead and drop it while dancing crazily to the DJ's Devo dub: both your iPhone and credit cards will be just fine.Just don't lose it. Then you'll never be able to call that girl in the Warby Parker frames who put her number into your phone. Plus you'll have no way to pay for the cab ride home. Double bummer, dude.So there you go. The "OtterBox Commuter Series Wallet Case for iPhone 5 & 5S"--the geek equivalent of the double-edged sword.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: The quality is exactly what you'd expect. I've purchased other wallet cases before and they can't hold a candle to the Otterbox quality. That being said, they've held 4-5, maybe 6 cards. With this case you're pressed to fit 3 cards in there, and the slideout mechanism is a bit clunky as well; I guess it's good that you have a reassuring "click" when you snap the cards back into place, but it's a bit too much effort.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: Like all other OtterBox cases, this is a very durable case that withstands most falls.  Also like OtterBox cases, it is bulky and not very stylish.  Unlike most cases, however, it has room for one or possibly two credit cards.  There isn't room to store cash.  But you really don't need to leave the house with anything more than a phone and credit card, so this particular case can, at times, be used in lieu of a wallet and a conventional phone case.
title: OtterBox [Commuter Series] Apple iPhone 5 & iPhone 5S Wallet Case - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Gray/White

reviewText: **Update 3/30/14**After about a month or so of continuously using this item, the siding case became a bit easier to open. It stays shut pretty well.  I imagine over time and sue, it may get easier and easier to open.  My only concern would be that it becomes too easy, but only time will tell. I have learned to deal with the added bulk, and found that it doesn't add much additional weight.  The only other hassle I discovered was that the cover on the charging port tends to push out the charging cable if there is a bit of movement on the phone during charging (i.e. charging in the car).****Before you purchase this product and plunk down money on this item, you will need to really think long and hard as to why you want a protective case with these particular features. If protection is the primary reason, then this may fit you.  But if the sliding tray featured is what you find tantalizing, you have to be aware of its drawbacks.I personally was very interested in the sliding tray feature because I want to be able to carry my phone and a couple of cards - my credit card, driver's license, and maybe some emergency cash as one unit.  I would probably need to access this tray about 1-2 times per day depending upon the activity I am doing.  My previous case had a pocket sleeve that you would insert your cards into, but it made me a little nervous about slipping out.This tray is very difficult to slide out.  So it does provide good security so it won't accidentally open, even if dropped.  But if you want to access it frequently, you need the grip of a gorilla to get it open.  To do so is also awkward.  You can't really open it with the phone facing you.  It has to be flipped over and then the top part of the tray has to be pushed down with tremendous force with most likely, your thumb.  I almost pooped in my pants with all of the force I had to muster up.  If you have long nails, you'd better get the value pack of prepaid visits at your local nail salon.  And if you got your Galaxy phone because of its slender sexy look, you have to give that up too.  This thing makes your phone bulky and it will be about as sexy as Woody Allen or Larry King. Take your pick.The plus is that the case is very durable.  It has a dual shock protection of a silicone case that slips over your phone which then  goes into the hard plastic case. The silicone sleeve is notched in the area where the charging port and audio jack are.  This lets you  keep those covered when not in use preventing dirt from getting in.This would be a really good case to have as a drug or condom stash, but when I think of "wallet" an easier access comes to mind.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Wallet Case for Samsung Galaxy S4 - Retail Packaging - Black
categories: [['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Basic Cases'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Wallet Cases']]

reviewText: I got this to review because I thought it was a really interesting concept. I'm all for carrying as little with me as possible and I almost always have my phone with me. There are times when I just need my driver's license, debit card, and maybe a few bucks in cash. Why carry everything else around?After trying this case I have an answer to that question. This case certainly provides the Otterbox protection you would expect. It does indeed hold about 3 cards comfortably, so that is nice too. However, there are three main failings with this case.1) It is very thick, even by Otterbox standards. It is also pretty heavy.2) The outer casing is plastic rather than rubber. Imagine the reverse of what you would expect with Otterbox. This makes it very slippery.3) It is not easy to get the wallet compartment open. I found that I had to flip the case over and use both thumbs to slide it down. The first time I got it open I was afraid that I was going to break it.Because it is the commuter series it does not come with a plastic cover built into the plastic. However, they do include a screen protector in the package. This is the kind of screen protector that takes a little bit of skill to apply unless you don't mind a ton of bubbles on your phone's screen.I think that this case might be ideal for someone who was just going out for the night, particularly a woman with a purse. It's going to be very big in a pocket. The good news is that with the Otterbox protection the phone should be OK when it slips out of your hands as you grab it to take a quick photo. It also might be handy if you take your phone when you exercise. You will need a pretty hefty armband if you want to use this case though.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Wallet Case for Samsung Galaxy S4 - Retail Packaging - Black
categories: [['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Basic Cases'], ['Cell Phones & Accessories', 'Cases', 'Wallet Cases']]

reviewText: Have been a longtime fan of OtterBox cases for their ruggedness and overall protection of smartphones. They hold up where others fail, and in that are hard to beat.TheOtterBox Commuter Series Wallet Case for Samsung Galaxy S4is a highly innovative product in that it combines the toughness of a good case with a slim concealed wallet. The concept is great, but the execution may not be so good for some. Will try to keep this simple, and remember that these are subjective points:◆ Strong Points:+ Excellent smartphone protection; very durable+ Self-adhesive screen protector; installs simply+ Good fit; easy phone installation+ Innovative; clever design◆ Not So Good:- Wallet section can be difficult to open- Thick case; thicker than most◆ In Use:This is one cleverly designed and innovative case, quite original and well crafted. But in actual use, it proved to be a bit of a hassle when used as a wallet substitute. The clever wallet drawer holds "up to three cards and one bill," and for some this may be enough, but if you're carrying your ID or driver license, one credit/debit card, another card such as a subway pass, along with a single bill, it may be a bit restrictive.Also found that as many times as I practiced opening the wallet drawer beforehand, when in actual use "in the field" so to speak, it became a true display of klutziness when trying to extract the credit card when paying at the register. Twice I was admonished to put my phone away and stop being rude when trying to pay. It was an attention-getter though, as some had to ask, "What is that thing?" It happens.More than once I had wished that I had been carrying myOtterBox Defender Series Caseand a wallet, and may yet go back to that method. At least there will be more access to cards and bills, along with good smartphone protection for the Galaxy S4.◆ Summary:ThisOtterBox Commuter Series Wallet Caseis a well-crafted product, but for the personal use of this reviewer, it's a 3-star product at best, and probably not a good choice. On the other hand, and trying to be objective here, if one doesn't mind a relatively thick case and can master the access to the wallet drawer and its contents, then this would be a good 4-star smartphone case.JW ▪ 2/20/2014
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Wallet Case for Samsung Galaxy S4 - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: Well, so, I ended up going back to my old case but not for any reason I can fault this case for: it is what it says and does what you'd expect!  It's an OtterBox so you get the quality you'd expect and like all Otterbox cases, it's pretty bulky.  This one is even bulkier than usual because of the storage space so the real question is whether you want that or not.  The case still fit my generic car holder, but it ended up being too thick for my Sony QX100 clamp, sadface.All that said, and 5 stars notwithstanding, the concept is something you might want to pause and think about.  Having your phone stolen is bad.  Having your wallet stolen is worse but your wallet is usually in your pocket while your phone is more frequently out in your hand.  Someone grabbing your phone and running is bad but it would be a lot worse if your credit card is in there.If this is still want you want, I say go for it!  This case is solid.  It's got the rubber lining, the hard shell and the screen protector and if storing a couple things in your phone case (business cards, maybe?) is what works for you, then 5 stars it is.  ....but I still think it may not be the best idea.

reviewText: HOW TO OPEN FOR DUMMIES!!!PLACE THUMBS POINTING UP ON FRONT/TOP OF SCREEN, PALMS REST ON SIDE OF CASE AND POINTER FINGERS ON THE HUMP ON THE BACK WHERE THE DRAWER STARTS AND PUSH UP ON THUMBS AND DOWN ON POINTER FINGERS...EASY AS THAT. I tried 2 of them at best buy and they both were easy..with and without phone installed. You will not break your phone. If it is any harder to open then that..you have a defective one and should get a replacement. Screen protector...who uses screen protectors that come with cases?? They are always junk. Zagg all the way. I can feel the sharp edge that some of the reviews talk about and it is a bit sharp but not cut worthy..I do rest my pinky on the usb cover anyways so not a big deal to me.Had the wallet case for a few weeks now and I love it. It works awesome. I had 3 cards and a folded up bill in it once and it was a bit hard to open. So I def pushed its capacity limit. I have 2 cards in it all the time and leave my wallet in the car. it opens really easy..not quite with one hand but hard enough that I'm not worried about it opening on its own. I am worried with use though that it might become easier to open as it ages. I was worried about sound quality though, from the pictures it doesn't have a opening for the rear speaker...well it actually reroutes it to the bottom of the phone so you can hear it a lot better. It has otterbox quality written all over it.

reviewText: I am a first time Otterbox user, and I love the product.  It was particularly difficult to find something for my LG G2 that was smooth enough on the outside to go in and out of my jeans, but still provide enough protection to keep the delicate phone from being damaged.  The G2 is particularly prone to damage, and I feel like this case will protect it from the abuse I provide.  The plastic is hard and good quality, and the rubber isn't too sticky, and still provides good shock absorption.I don't love how it comes up a little at the bottom, where the internal, rubbery part of the case meets the bottom of the phone, but I dealt with it because of the rest of the benefits of the case.  A bit of glue between the rubber part and the hard plastic would do the trick to keep the rubber from coming out.All and all, good case for sure.  If you have a G2, buy this case.  You won't regret it, because you'll definitely regret not having something this durable if you drop your phone.  I have gone through 4 different cases looking for something like this.

reviewText: The OtterBox case for the LG G2 is more than ample protection for anyone who’s tough on their phone. One good thing about it, is that if you already have screen protection, the case won’t ruin or shift it appreciably. The cutouts are spot on, including the ones for the rear camera lens and the LED flash. The cover for the power/lock key and the volume keys is easy to maneuver.The inner silicone layer will keep the dust out, while the outer polycarbonate one gives that OtterBox protection everyone is familiar with. It definitely will protect against unexpected drops and if you choose to use the screen protector, will prevent scratches. The two layers definitely offer up some heavy-duty protection and, of course, with the distinctive OtterBox logo on the back everyone will know you like to protect your phone in style.FEATURES:► Slim, protective Commuter Series case for LG G2 case guards against drops, bumps, dust and scratches► Slick exterior shell deflects impact and easily slides into pockets► Slip cover absorbs impact and has a good grip in the hand► Self-adhesive screen protector guards the touch screen against scuffs and scratches► Trusted protection from the Commuter Series case for LG G2COMPATIBILITY:► LG G2 – all carriers globally except for VerizonNOTE: Not compatible with Verizon LG G2

reviewText: Initially, my review was going to mention how this case was "a perfect fit," "a breeze to install," "easy to clean," etc. Then, three days ago, I dropped my phone down a flight of stairs at work. It tumbled from my hand when I was trying to return it to my handbag. I was horrified. After cursing myself for not taking the elevator, I rushed to the landing ... I expected to find my phone completely destroyed. As it turns out, my phone was absolutely fine!! The case has a few "dings" in it (the stairs are concrete), but my phone is alive and well.So, I feel like this is basically a "ringing endorsement" and (pretty much) the definition of a five-star product. This was my first experience with OtterBox but definitely not my last. Many thanks to OtterBox for creating a superior product!!

reviewText: When you are choosing a case, a very important question is whether you are looking for fashion or protection. This case wins no stars in the fashion department. reviewText: This is a simple case. Two parts -- one rubber that wraps around the phone, and the other plastic that goes over the rubber. Includes screen protector. reviewText: I was a little conflicted as to how to review this product. On one hand, it seems like it would provide extra protection for your phone, but on the other hand, it just about doubles the thickness of the phone, with the corresponding increase in weight. With so much bulk, you'll probably have to keep removing the case & putting it back on every time you want to attach & detach the phone to a dock/cradle/speaker. Is the extra size & expense worth it?I guess that depends upon what your specific needs are. If you're the kind of person who frequently drops their phone, or tosses it onto a table instead of placing it there with care, then this is the case for you. But if you're someone who's more careful with your possessions, and have rarely, if ever, dropped your phone, then the bulkiness (and expense) of this case is probably more of a hindrance than it's worth.For me, this case is far too much trouble & expense than it's worth. The case I've been using is theJKase DIABLO Series Tough Rugged Dual Layer Protection Case Cover with Build in Stand for LG G2 (AT&T; / Sprint / T-Mobile Only. NOT for Verizon Version) (Black). It's thinner, less bulky, lighter, and about one third the price of the otterbox case.

reviewText: Don't misunderstand.  This is an excellent case for what it is designed for, which is protecting the iPhone from falls, bumps, tosses, and perhaps the occasional hammer.  However, if one does not have a tendency to have these mishaps, it just seems like overkill.It makes the phone about twice as thick, an inch longer, and more than twice as heavy.  (Estimates)The built in screen protector works smoothly, but is ultimately unattractive because of the oily rainbow appearance it adds to the iPhone screen.Slipping this thing in and out of a pocket can be a real pain, which explains why they feel it mandatory to include a holster.The rubber plugs that block every single port are just in the way.  I'm not sure why these are necessary, because from other people I've known with Defender cases, and from these other reviews, this case isn't blocking any dust.In summary, this is wonderful protection for the accident prone or sadistic (or masochistic), but after using it for a while, and noticing any pleasure of using the iPhone get sucked away by the bulk and interfering rubber plugs, I can tell this is not for me, at least.Getting one for free to review has been a good thing, though.  I have had my iPhone 5 for over a year, and even though I am careful, there are a few tiny scratches and nicks in places, and in hindsight, it may be better to have at least enough of a case so that one does not have to worry about where one sets the phone down, and enough of a lip over the front edge to prevent accidentally nicking the screen.  Screen protectors are really not necessary in that scenario, and I haven't used them with any iPhones.So, Otterbox has convinced me to purchase an Apple iPhone 5/5S case, for just enough protection, but maximum elegance.  I think I'll go with RED for my iPhone and iPad Air.

reviewText: The OtterBox Defender is the gold standard in Smartphone protection.  It doesn't pretend to be sleek and sexy.  It's mission in life is to make sure that in two years, when it's time to upgrade to the next iPhone, and you peel the scuffed and dented case away from the phone, the phone will be in brand new condition (assuming you don't drop it in the lake).iPhone 5S dimensions (naked):  123.8mm long, 58.6mm wide, 7.6mm talliPhone 5S with Spigen Tough Armor case: 129mm long, 65mm wide, 11.5mm talliPhone 5S with OtterBox Commuter: 130mm long, 65mm wide, 14.5mm talliPhone 5S with OtterBox Defender: 133mm long, 68mm wide, 16.5mm tallThese are my measurements with a ruler, so they will be close but not exact.  The point in showing these measurements is so you can see what extra bulk there is associated with a complete protection case like the OtterBox Defender.  I was actually pleasantly surprised that there is not an extreme amount of bulk with this case.  I think they have made progress over the years.  My one wish is that the case didn't add 5mm of height to the phone vs the Spigen case.The case is easy to install, fits perfectly, and even comes with a plastic screen protector built in.  The screen protector does diminish the feel of the screen, but it is tolerable.  All of the openings line up perfectly, and it even protects the power port, mute button and earphone jack with moveable rubber pads. The case feels great to hold, and you can still use fingerprint recognition on the iPhone 5S.  The opening in the case for the power port is wide enough that your iPhone should be able to sit on a lightning equipped docking station with no problem.This ought to be standard equipment for anyone who equips a teenager with a $650 phone.  It's a no-brainer.  My phone is so well protected I feel like I could play catch with it in the front yard.If you drop your phone a lot, you owe it to yourself to get this case.  You won't be sorry you did, unless destroying the sleekness of the iPhone is out of the question for you.  If so, look at the OtterBox Commuter case, which is sleeker, but not nearly as rugged and does not have the built in screen protector.

reviewText: I am one of those guys that will spend hours and even days researching for the perfect case. I read Amazon reviews, blogs, and watch YouTube videos. There obliviously is no perfect case out there, but the Otterbox Defender is the very closest thing I could find to it. I will let you know a few key things that sold me.Defender Vs. CommuterThe Defender offers more protection than the Commuter, but the Commuter is a little thinner. I prefer the rubber on the outside of the case so you can set the phone on a dashboard and it will not slide around. The outer shell on the Commuter is plastic which can allow for a slip in your hand too. The Defender includes a screen protector and the Commuter does not. The whole idea behind the attached screen protector is to keep dust out. One day after having the Otterbox on my phone, I already noticed dust building up under the screen so I put some Goo Gone on it and pulled it off with ease. Any other screen protector that applies to the phone and not the case works much better.Defender Vs. Other CasesWhen I first purchased my Iphone I bought the Neo Hybrid case and I loved the slim fit and lay on the table appeal but a few weeks later one of the other kids in my college class dropped his phone and it shattered his screen. If you YouTube the Defender and any other case in the market you will usually find drop tests. I found it interesting that people on YouTube only do drop test from waist height when testing all of the cases on the market. I am sure that is the height of most of the drops that will occur but what happens if you drop your phone while on the second story balcony? The Otterbox Defender was the only case I could find that people dared to test it from a second, third and even fourth floor of a building.  In case you were wondering, not even one drop test from that amazing height failed. I don’t know how you can ask for anymore protection for your very high dollar phone? It is logical that if any other case was comparable then people would dare drop from such heights too. Not to mention the quality of rubber of the Otterbox cases is superior to all other rubber types in other cases. It is a studier hard rubber. Another positive to the Defender is that it has covers for your ports so dust will not get in. I keep my phone in my pocket and I was amazed at how much dust and lint got into my ports each day. With the Defender there is no worry.Defender Vs. Waterproof caseAs for water protection? This case is not waterproof but a have heard my share of horror stories with the “waterproof” cases. My sister and a co-worker both had Lifeproof case and both had leak issue and a ruined the Iphone.  The cases are a hit and miss and too much of a gamble for the price you pay.In closing, you cannot go wrong with the defender case. If anything happens to your case within the first year you can just take a picture of the damage and send the picture to Otterbox and they will send you a new case. I used to worry about dropping my phone, but now I can say I have absolutely no worry thanks to the Defender. I recommend this case to everyone!
title: iPhone 5S Case- OtterBox Defender Case for iPhone 5/5S- Realtree Camo/Max4 Orange (Retail Packaging)(Works with TouchID)

reviewText: Coming from the iPhone5 with an otter-box defender, I knew that i wanted the same protection around my new iphone. reviewText: I don't usually put a case on my phone at all, unless I'm doing something athletic or outdoor sports.  Generally, I just stick it in my pocket.  But I pay for insurance with my cell phone carrier for all the devices on my plan in case I break them and need them repaired or replaced.  Currently, that's a top of the line iPad, an iPhone 5 (mine), and my wife's iPhone 5S.  I have a good, shock resistant case for my iPad that also looks good, my wife has a decorative case for her iPhone which barely offers any protection, and as I wrote above I usually don't use any case at all for my phone.One person I asked about why they put a bulky case on their phone answered, "I'm protecting my investment."  If a cell phone is an investment, it's the worst kind.  It depreciates rapidly.  Just ask yourself how much you would pay for someone's used 4S or 5 at this point.  Not much of course.But these things cost a lot of money, even if you're getting a discount.  My wife's 32GB 5S on opening day cost me $300 on paper, but there were several additional charges, so let's say it was at least $400 out of pocket.  I would be stupid not to protect this expensive item in some way against damage; but I always purchase the insurance because not only does it protect 'my investments' in terms of damage, but for wear and tear, complete destruction, theft, and just plain losing it somewhere.  Over the last several years, I've had two phones repaired and three replaced, well worth the price of the insurance.OK, but insurance is expensive, right?  That's where you have to consider your options.  This particular case, for this model of phone, only cost about $35 currently, versus fully insuring the phone for $8 a month / $96 per year--you likely spend more on coffee at Starbucks.  So if I'm fairly confident that I will never ever lose my phone and it will never-ever-ever be stolen (I live in New York City, where stealing iPhones is common) then the case seems like a good deal.  But if the case cost $60 or more, then the insurance would be the better option.Aside from cost is the case itself.  Otterbox of course is the most famous for protecting your electronics better than any other brand in terms of impact, dust, and so forth, and some people just plain love the bulky, 'military grade' armor plating because ... because ... because they just do. but I'm a bit mystified by some of the design features--for which I took away one star.If you're going to go this far to protect a cell phone why not go all the way and make it water resistant as well?  There's a plastic window protecting the Apple logo on the back while letting you display it, but no window or gasket door for the camera and flash, so obviously water, dust, and sand can still get in.  There is also no cover for the ports, speaker, and mic on the bottom of the phone, or the home button on the front.  In other words, this case is ONLY impact resistant, where as the Life case for example is also water resistant.On the positive side though, there is no problem working all the buttons on the phone even under this thick armor.  This is a vast improvement over the Commuter case that I had for a previous phone which fit loosely and made using the buttons and accessing the ports difficult.And lastly there is this great holster clip.  While I would never wear something like this on my belt, I love it for my TimBuk2 messenger bag and outdoor sports gear.  I have absolutely no worries about this coming off if I choose to have it hanging out on a strap or even clipped to a pocket--only I would have to slip it inside a ziplock bag if it started to rain.BOTTOM LINE:Consider what it costs you to buy a pricey protective case versus just insuring the phone.  At the current price, this is a good deal and good option if you're reluctant to add another $8 to your wireless bill.The phone couldn't possibly be better protected from impacts and drops, and the holster is so secure that I doubt there any risk of it falling out while maintaining easy access.The only thing that is really inadaquate about the design is it's lack of water, splash, dust, sand, and rain resistance.  I would make sure to carry a ziplock bag with me if there was any chance I would get caught in the rain while using this case on my phone.
