reviewText: For years I've heard my friends rave about their OtterBox cases.  They just love them and I honestly never saw the appeal.  They looked big and bulky and the grippy exterior of the case is something that is certainly not for me.  Most people I know who have an OtterBox Defender case tell me they got it because they've broken a phone in the past because they dropped it and it shattered.  So I can understand why some may feel the need to get a case such as this.In the past couple of months we've had some experience with the OtterBox Defender cases for iPhone 5C, 5S and 4S.  We've found with all three that they're incredibly difficult to put into or take out of the case.  From start to finish it takes several minutes to put a phone in this case.  With this case, the plastic screen protector wasn't attached to the case like it was supposed to be.  Instead it was found floating around in the box.One thing is pretty evident with this case.  If you drop your phone, it is going to be well protected.  So if you're someone who tends to drop your phone all of the time, then you very well might want this case for your phone.Both my husband and I gave this case a try with our phones and we both disliked the bulk as well as the plastic screen protector.  I couldn't get the screen on my phone to respond well with this screen protector.  I like to be able to carry my phone in my back pocket or in my wristlet that has a spot for my phone.  With this case, I couldn't fit the phone in my pocket or in my wristlet, so I lost interest in the phone quickly.  I also didn't like that I can't dock my phone on my Belkin charger with the case on it and I don't have the time or desire to take the case off every time I want to charge my phone.My husband's chief complaints with this case aside from the bulk was the flap that covers the button to turn the sound on and off.  The flap is not only difficult to open, but those with larger fingers may have difficulty actually accessing the switch on the phone.I don't like the case, but I suppose someone who needs a good deal of protection for their iPhone may like it.  If you're like me and don't like added bulk then this case is likely not for you.
title: iPhone 5S Case- OtterBox Defender Case for iPhone 5/5S- Realtree Camo/Max4 Orange (Retail Packaging)(Works with TouchID)

reviewText: This OtterBox features a nice case with a belt holster, which is great for those people who want that extra hand free availability of their device.  The holster itself is made out of plastic, but feels great and highly durable. The clip on the back has a flat area that would touch your belt with small ridges so you wouldn't have to worry at all about it harming your belts material.  The clip itself is both easy to open, and yet feels very secure. When the case is inserted into the holster, you have to bend a little area back to fit the case inside then let go.  Once you've done so the case is snug into the holster, and I had no fear of it coming loose or of me accidentally knocking it out.The actual case is a normal Otterbox case, which means loads of protection. It has two layers, which includes a smooth inner plastic case that snaps open and closed. The front of this case has a screen protector built into it, and the back of the case, were the logo is cut out, has a built in screen protector there also. I, personally, had a little bit of trouble trying to push the side tabs to unsnap the case, but I guess in the end this is a good thing as it tells me my Iphone is not coming out easily. Once you've opened the inner case, you can see a nice slightly padded area in the back where your device rest on.  So don't fear any scratches on your new device in the case!  I've actually had a commuter series OtterBox for an Ipod, and it slid open for easy access.  However, doing that caused a lot of scratches on the back of my device.  But with this one, you don't have to worry at all!  Once you put your phone in (and I do recommend cleaning the back and front of the screen protector before you put your phone in) just snap the case closed all around, and your ready to put on the outer case! This last case is made up of a soft plastic outer lining that encompasses the hard case. It does cover the power button, the volume keys, the audio jack, the dock connector, and even the silent key. The only areas exposed are the speakers, the camera in back, and the camera/small area in front. Now, I will say I do have on another screen protector, and a back screen protector from another case, and I never took them off before slipping them into this new case.  This was just laziness on my part, and curiosity to see if the touch screen would work, and it does wonderfully.  So I think I'll just leave it.  Now, the only part that isn't too secure is the fact the built in screen protector does have a cut out area for the touch sensor home button so we can still use that feature.  I don't necessarily like it as debris is still able to get under that cutout.  Also, and this could be because of my duo screen protectors, there is a little oily gloss here and there on my screen, but it's only noticeable when my phone is off. Other than that great case, and I do recommend it if your prone to dropping your phone!***update***The cutout area for the home button is now my worst enemy.  I've had to literally get my husband to take off the case (as I broke quite a few nails trying to pry it open to no avail), to clean the inside of the screen off.  I'm actually quite thankful I have on a screen protector underneath the built in OtterBox one as debris loves to squeeze it's way inside, especially since I put my phone in a messy purse with all manner of things flying around.  There is a slight gap also where the screen of my phone touches the screen protector so it is very easy for tiny particles to get inside the case.  Once cleaned it's all good, but it only lasted a week or two before it needed to be cleaned again.  The oily spot that was there actually went away, and my screen is pristine.  I've also had the chance to mess around with other high dollar cases, and even though the cutout home button could use work, this case is still one of the best choices out there.  Sure it adds some bulk, but I have no issue hearing people, or people hearing me, the touch screen is highly responsive, and I definitely have great drop protection as I did drop it on tile floor, where it landed face first.  Not a scratch.  So if you can live with the home button/debris issue (which I still vote add a screen protector inside), then I would totally recommend it!

reviewText: Most reviews listed are for the "Defender" so I will write a real commuter review..... This case has thick silicone like the defender and a plastic shell to go over top and side. Happened when I did my wife's, but mine is perfect... Of course....  Once you get it on, it is tough to remove and try again with out jacking it all up, getting finger grease and dust under it.  The rubber stays firm around most of it and you can tell your phone is protected. There is a substantial lip over the front of the glass which is nice. I would bet this is same size as defender but without the built in screen protector everyone complains about bc it has opening at home button.  My only gripe is the bottom which is why I took off a star. If you look at most other iphone commuter versions, there is rubber and plastic in between the ports at the bottom. Usually they have covers that go in the ports.... Not on this one.... There is a huge oval opening at the bottom with nothing holding the rubber from separating if dropped on the edge of something. Yes you can fit any adapter in the headphone or lightning port bc it will just spread apart like Moses did the ocean.... Looseygoosey.... Overall solid but I am picky with my cases. Mine was on sale for $30. I would not pay more than that. I was disappointed it was not any cheaper anywhere else online either...

reviewText: Many people love the supreme protection offered by the OtterBox Defender phone cases.  However, I always found that they took away so much of the sleekness and portability of the phone - unless you work in a dangerous or punishing environment where your phone is constantly at risk of utter destruction, they seemed like overkill.  Enter the OtterBox Commuter - a slimmer case designed to afford protection without adding a tremendous amount of bulk.  However, this generation of the Commuter has a notable change prior versions that severely hamper its performance.The Commuter comes with three pieces:  a standard screen protection film (only one - so the logo on the back of your phone will be exposed to scratching if that matters to you), a rubber sleeve that covers most of the phones edge buttons/switches and provides a bumper lip around the front screen, and a hard plastic shell that snaps around the sleeve and provides (some) shock/drop protection.  The Commuter does not include any sort of holster or clip.The pieces all fit very well on my phone and installation only took a minute or so.  The bumper lip is a good depth for protecting your screen when the phone is face-down.  It is also grippy enough to prevent the phone from sliding away from you, e.g. on a dashboard.  The shell protection on the back adds about 1/8 of an inch to the phone's depth - not too cumbersome but enough to provide good crush protection if you frequently pack your phone or carry it in a messenger bag.The problem is that the hard shell does not extend around the bottom of the phone at all.  The only protection on the bottom is from the rubber sleeve.  Not only does this offer inadequate drop protection on that side, but the thin rubber strip across the bottom eventually begins to stretch and bow ever so slightly after repeatedly tugging on it when pulling your phone out of your pocket or bag (and this is basically unavoidable).Performance-wise, the Commuter does well.  All buttons, switches and jacks are adequately reachable and responsive through the protection.  The bumper lip does crowd the very edge of the touch screen a bit and can get in the way when attempting some pinch/swipe motions near those borders.If only the Commuter had extended the hard shell along the bottom edge of the phone, then this would easily be a five-star review.  I'm glad that OtterBox is working to bring down the bulk of its Defender series, but there is still some design improvement needed in order to make this a can't-miss case.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for iPhone 5c - Retail Packaging Protective Case for iPhone - Black

reviewText: I am a fan of the Otterbox cases and especially the defender series since my blackberry days some years ago. I am therefore doubly disappointed with this purchase of the defender series for Note 3. The holster locks the phone in by clipping over a little recess on the part of the case which covers the device itself. The problem which develops is that the recess itself breaks quickly meaning that the phone will no longer stay in the holster. This appears to be a major design flaw because both of my recesses have now broken and the holster has been rendered completely useless. In my opinion the holster is an integral part of the defender experience and offers some additional protection as well. This flaw makes the defender less than what Otterbox claims. I'm still intending to use the case without the holster, but the damage is unattractive and to be quite honest annoying. The defender series usually offers superior protection to that afforded by the commuter series and to other cases imo, but if having a functioning holster is also a requirement (given the fact that it doubles as a device stand) then I'd skip this and look elsewhere. I hope to get a replacement case from Otterbox, but that isn't looking likely so I'm just sticking with it while I research other options. Disappointing from Otterbox smh.

reviewText: When I first saw it I thought 'huge' but after putting it on,  it's not as much as I thought. It does add bulk but, for such a large phone its not that bad. Every thing is covered,  the home button,  charging connector all have sturdy flaps to keep dirt and debris out; yet everything that needs to be exposed is. The mic, speakers, cameras have perfectly placed openings.  The power and volume buttons are easy and comfortable to use. There is a plastic cover over the screen that I was worried about,  but it works fine, even with the skin screen protector I already had on. There are three parts of the main cover,  the front plastic I mentioned, a rear plastic cover that has a thin soft padding, and the rubber that covers the back, sides, and all the openings.  If you carry extra batteries,  like I do, this case is tough to get off and back on.The separate plastic holster doubles as a stand. You can put the phone in either side,  there are notches that snap the phone into the holster. On the back,  the belt clip turns (rotates) so you can carry the phone either landscape or portrait.  When using it as a stand the phone sits in the bottom corner holders and rests nicely against the back. The viewing angle is not adjustable but it is comfortable. I can set it on my night stand,  plugged into the charger,  and read or view my clock.It seems to offer great protection. The rubber back cover wraps around the front and is raised around the screen for additional front protection. But you do sacrifice the thin, light beauty of the phone.

reviewText: OttorBox produces five product series of four levels of protection. They are Armor, Defender, Commuter, and Relfex/Prefix, with descending level of protection and physical bulk.Compared to the Armor series, the Defender does not protect against water splash nor crushing force, but it is definitely much less bulky.This series also includes a holster, so that the phone can be carried on the outside of body for convenience. For screen protection, it is best to attach the phone to the holster with the screen facing in.Not even the Armor series will protect against forces applied to the glass screen, such as dropping a wrench or hammer onto it. Therefore, it is always a good habit to lay the phone face down when not used.The Defender series does really well in terms of protection against drop and dust.Although I think it is excellent for work environments like construction and package/document delivery service, if your use involves rougher than normal handling of the phone, the Defender is a must.

reviewText: ... I just can't give this a higher review until my Note hits the floor.It's an OtterBox. So, until that moment that incites existential dread, that mysterium tremendum, when my device goes tumbling through the air with me flailing after, that promise goes untested. reviewText: I recently switched from iPhone 5 to Note 3. I am used to having so many choices of cases to pick from and have tried many cases for my iPhone. My only Gripe with this case is the same issues I experienced with my pervious Defender cases, the built-in screen protector isn't the greatest.Like I have done with all my other defender cases, I removed the screen protector because it degrades the quality of the screen. I ended up putting a Zagg HD on my Note 3, but I will soon replace it because it doesn't hold up well against the s pen. I plan on replacing my screen protector with a Speigen Glass screen protector soon. I am worried if the otterbox will fit with a glass protector on the Note 3. I will try it in the next few days and attempt to update this review.Other than the issues I have with the screen, this is a great case for the best protection. The belt clip is a little hard to get on and off, but I like that because it feels very secure.UPDATE: 12/12/2013I got my speigen glass screen protector and installed it with the otterbox defender on it. It fits!!! It did make the phone a bit more heavier, but the clarity is great! I feel this is the best combo.  Glass screen protector from speigen and Otterbox defender is the way to go. The case fits perfectly on the phone with the glass screen protector on it. It feels like I don't have a screen protector on. Every thing is super clear and the touch is smooth. This is way better than the Zagg HD. It works great with the S pen and doesn't leave those annoying marks.

reviewText: This is the first Otterbox case I've had.  I'm absolutely sold.- The size isn't a problem since the phone itself is so much larger than my previous phones.  Either in my hand, or holding it to my ear, it was already big, so the extra bulk, though obviously noticeable, isn't an issue for me at all.- The near complete encasement of the phone is the most important factor in my purchase of this case, and it delivers in that regard.  I have a 9 yr old and a 2 yr old, and they can drop it (which they have), put their sticky fingers all over it (which they have), and it all stays on the outside, along with scratches and whatever else.  The dust accumulation that builds up in openings on previous cases is also not present using this case.- I simply left my glass protector on and also used the included facing that came with the OtterBox, really just because I wasn't sure how the OtterBox would work and didn't want to reinstall the other screen protector if it didn't work out... but everything still works perfectly with essentially two screen protectors.  Touch sensitivity is fine, no glare, no "rainbows", and I probably won't worry about removing the old one.- One thing I'm not sure is if they sell just the front Otterbox screen protector seperate if this one starts getting scratched up, I'll have to check that out.  Again, I like the entire front integration, so I hope I can get the front "frame" + screen protector without buying the whole 3-layer case again.- The belt clip is sturdy, almost too much so... I typically have to use two hands to remove the phone from the holder.  I can release the phone with one hand if I try hard enough, but it's not a quick and easy release, it takes a lot of pressure.  That at least tells me it's solidly attached and I'm OK with being aggressive with it.  : )- The "stand" is actually the belt clip.  I wish the cover itself had a built in stand because sometimes I have the phone in a pocket and without the belt clip I have no way to stand it up.  That's my only minor complaint.All - in - all it's the best case I've ever had and I'm more than satisfied.Highly recommended.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - White/Gray

reviewText: After cracking the screen on my Galaxy Note 3 by dropping it, I decided to go with serious protection. There is no more serious protection than the OtterBox Defender. reviewText: The Defender series is in a class of its own - you don't buy this to make your phone look pretty, you buy it because you work somewhere that is not friendly to your phone. You also don't "pop" your phone in this - it is a decent installation to get your device in this case. You first remove the rubber jacket from the hard shell, then split the shell, then do it all in reverse. You'll need a good 4 to 5 minutes for a good installation.Once in the case, you can click it in the included holster - which works as a belt clip or as a (movie) viewing stand when you pull the belt clip open.There are flaps for the charger port and the headphone jack. It will NOT work with wireless charging. The Samsung charger back is too thick, and the Qi charger accessories that you put behind the original back don't get a good enough signal to work. I also found that NFC is harder to work with.There are openings in the front (for the speaker, LED indicator and camera), the top (for the microphone and IR port) rear (for the camera) and the bottom (for the second mix and speakers). This means it is definitely not a waterproof case, other than perhaps a few drips of rain.Still, with a $749 phone this case is the one investment that should/could keep it from falling apart.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - White/Gray

reviewText: I've debated about Otterbox cases for many of my phones over the years as I always heard of the great protection that they give the phone and that they had a holster belt-clip (my preferred way to carry my phones), so I finally splurged when I got my Galaxy Note 3 and bought one.  The case itself does offer great protection, but it's also a little slick in the hand without any type of grip on the sides and isn't the most attractive case on the market - neither though, would lead me to returning the case.  The ability for me to holster my phone on my belt, on the other hand, is paramount to me and that's where the issue was.  It may have been just my case, but when I snapped the phone into the holster, it would click as it should, but with the slightest pressure, it would pop right out of the clip.  This meant, that whenever I bumped into something slightly, my phone would pop off of the clip.  Now, I was lucky enough to catch the phone before it hit the floor each time that it did this, but this is the complete opposite of why I spent the extra money in the first place on this and after that, I had absolutely zero confidence that my precious Note 3 was going to be safe going forward.  I'm about to return this case and have already bought another holster case to replace it.  I bought the Seidio case/holster combo (their highest protection case - forgot the name) and absolutely love it!  The case itself is ok, but has a design flaw that is well documented online, but the holster is top-notch and includes a spring-loaded clip to keep my phone (in a different case) secure on my belt.  Again, the Otterbox case offers fantastic protection, but the holster wasn't secure enough for me.

reviewText: By way of disclosure, I received a sample of this product for evaluation purposes.I previously had a hybrid Spigen case on my Note 3.  While it looked nice, it added quite a bit to the sides of the phone, which made it even harder to hold.  It also didn't offer much of a ridge around the screen, which made me nervous that I might break the screen if the phone fell on its face.This OtterBox case is narrower around the sides of the phone and offers a larger, rubberized ridge around the screen.The port covers line up well.  I'm not a tremendous fan of them, though, because they put some pressure on whatever connector you're plugging in, which results in lateral pressure on the ports in the phone.  That can't be great.  But they do keep dust out.The side buttons line up well.  I have no difficulties turning the phone off or waking it up, and the volume adjuster works well, too.The case has a plastic shield that attaches over the bulk of the inner case, which has a bit of a rubbery consistency.  The plastic makes it easy to slip the phone in and out of your pocket.I already had a good screen protector on my phone, so I didn't use the included one and cannot comment on it, but OtterBox does provide a small microfiber cloth to help you clean the screen of dust and oils before applying the screen protector, which is a nice thought.Overall, I found this to be a better case than the Spigen case for the way I use the phone.  It isn't ostentatious.  Just functional.  I recommend it without reservation.  I just wish they didn't make the port covers put so much pressure on connectors.

reviewText: Got this case for my new work phone (note 3) and I couldn't be happier with my purchase. At first I didn't want to shell out 40 bucks, but now that I've been using it I'd happily pay twice that. Raised front facing edges keeps the screen off the table. I can easily hold the phone+case in one hand, albeit I do have rather large hands. Good grip on the sides, I don't feel like I'm going to drop it. The back plate is rather slick but looks nice. The rubber is of the best quality,  keeps it's shape after several times taking it on and off. I purposely tried to bend it out of form and it retained it's shape. The rubber over the buttons feels good, the flaps for charging and aux don't press against their respective cables and they lay nice and flat once put back in place. With the case on, the phone slides easily in and out of my pocket. The included screen protector is crystal clear,  easy to put on as long as you clean the screen throughly before hand, and don't allow any particles to settle while applying. Doesn't interfere with the s - pen at ALL. The pen is actually interpreted by an electromagnetic field behind the screen. For example, place an index card or 3 on the screen and try writing something in action memo.Anyways, I just wanted to mention one more time how this thing screams quality. Totally worth it. Go ahead and stop reading all these reviews if you're looking for a note 3 case and just buy this one. -DRL
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - Blue/Navy

I had one for my old iPhone and the glass cracked when I dropped it once, so I have stayed away.  but I have to say that I was impressed with this slim, nicely fitting case.  Is has an inner silicone (?) sleeve that goes over the entire phone and offers protection in the critical areas like the corners.  There is also a lip that keeps he screen safe from hitting the floor in the event you drop it face down.  The hard shell that goes on the outside is extra protection from hard falls.  I also like the accessibility of the ports.  The covers open easily and my headphones and charger fit perfectly.  So far, so good!

reviewText: I am fast becoming an OtterBox fan, they offer great products that you can make sure where thought of with protection and style in mind. reviewText: Ok I'm comparing this to the other case I have, the i-Blason Armadillo (ASIN B00F0R83VG), which I bought on Amazon for $12.99 + free shipping.First off, on both cases, all the holes for speakers & buttons line up perfectly. Don't worry about that.The OtterBox is definitely a great case, but this "mid-grade" Otterbox (Commuter series) seems extremely similar to the iBlason which is 1/4th the price.OtterBox comes with a screen protector which is nice (probably a $3 value), and the hole to access to stylus is a little better on the OtterBox.The iBlason has much more protection on the corners (bump guards), which makes me feel it has better drop protection, but it also makes it a bit more difficult to slide in & out of your pocket.The OtterBox also has a slightly sturdier backing to it. Also, I think the OtterBox tries to leave a small cushion of air between the case and the phone, for extra protection, kindof like bubble wrap.I think the OtterBox is slightly better quality overall than the iBlason, though the iBlason has the corner bump guards which are definitely more protection. I give them both 4.5 or 5 stars, but I'm marking the Otterbox down just due to price. The higher models are probably worth $40-$50, but the Commuter should really be closer to $20-$25.If you feel you need moderate protection for your phone (an occasional mishap or drop), I would probably recommend the ~much~ cheaper iBlason. Personally, I'm keeping the iBlason and giving the OtterBox to my wife.However, if you drop your phone daily, have an extreme work environment, or are really really rough on your phone, get the Defender series for about the same price. Or if you need waterproof, check out the Armor series.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - Blue/Navy

reviewText: Let me start by saying this case does add some weight and size to an already large phone. It is a little harder to get it in my pockets, so understand that before you buy this. If you plan to throw your phone in a bag or your purse, this is a GREAT case. The hard plastic fits the phone perfectly and will protect your phone. I haven't tried a drop test because, frankly, I don't want to risk damaging an expensive phone, but comparing this to my other slimline case, I would worry much less about the phone if something were to happen. That is the point of the commuter series and otterbox is known for making protective cases for travel. If you want something slimline, you should look at something else. I believe they also make a smaller version for the note 3, which isn't quite so bulky.Getting the case on and off was no problem at all. All of the slots for accessing phone features line up perfectly.My only real complaint is the rubber guards they put over the headphone and usb connections. WHY? There are holes for the camera, the s-pen, the mic and speakers, everything. I use my phone to play podcast in the car and having to move the rubber connector out of the way is a little bit of a pain.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - Blue/Navy

reviewText: I've got a lot of co-workers that LOVE their OtterBox phone cases, and I've always been such the bargain shopper that the pricing for the average OtterBox device case has always been a bit off-putting for me, but if the pricing doesn't bother you, and you want a quality, name brand, non-knockoff-made-in-China case (as I typically opt for for a fraction of OtterBox pricing), then I doubt that you'll have any qualms with this case, made for the Samsung Galaxy Note III.I've become fanatical about my Galaxy devices. I'm on to my third model here, with the Note III, and I LOVE it! In light of that fact, and in consideration of the price that these OtterBox cases are sold at, if the pricing is right for you, your device WILL be protected.The case fits my device snugly, and the dual-piece rubber/hard plastic layers provide a cushion against the shock of a drop, while the harder shell protects the device overall. It's a clever design that OtterBox (and others!) have used for many a year, and obviously, it's still in use because it's a design that still works.OtterBox also seems to have expanded their color scheme here with this line, which I appreciate. I'm not so much a boring black kind of girl when it comes to my device case, so I'm glad that there are more offerings here. With a less limited personal budget, I just might buy two or three of these cases, and interchange the rubber layer of one case with the hard shell of another, just so I have a few more options to choose from, color-wise.While this model may not be the watertight, fully-sealed OtterBox case that I've always found myself coveting, these cases ARE well made. My standard cheapie-cheapie Made in China cases cover the bases, but they often prove to be, as with everything, cases of getting what you pay for. They look good at the beginning, but they show wear and tear pretty quickly. After having used this case for a few weeks now, it's held up well, and the occasional time or two that I've dropped my device from two or three feet up (still, *GASP*!!!), my device, and the case, have both come out completely unscathed.Overall, a good protective option, if the price is in your range!
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - Blue/Navy

reviewText: I have had many phones and many Otterbox cases, but always the DEFENDER series, which is Otterbox's Uber-Case. I carried my GN2 in an Otterbox Defender for a year, using the belt holster. I've gradually come to prefer front pocket carry to the belt holster. I found that the Defender case is a bit thick and slightly too tactile for front pocket carry. It's very grippy, and built to be bullet-proof. (Not really, but...)So, when I shuffled the GN2 off to my wife and got the new GN3, I decided to go with a lighter case. But I still wanted the best protection I could get without undue thickness, and something slightly easier to get out of the pocket than the Defender. Went to the Verizon store to swap my wife into my older GN2, and noticed the Otterbox Defender in Surf Blue. I normally buy cases from Amazon, but in this case, being paranoid about the safety of my new GN3, I bought the case at the store and put it on there. Also, I get a deep corporate discount from Verizon on hardware accessories.Long story short, I love the protection provided by the Otterbox Commuter, and the balance between softer grip surfaces and fairly smooth flat surfaces for pocket carry is excellent. I also bought a UAG case in Rust Orange (from Amazon, reviewed separately) because I get bored with cases and need something to switch off to from time to time. In my opinion, the Otterbox provides better drop/impact protection than the UAG case because of the two-piece construction; I feel the full soft inner liner of the Otterbox is superior for this purpose. However, I think the UAG case provides better side grip surface insets, and enhanced corner cushions that are handy for pulling a phone out of a pocket by the top edges. The Otterbox Commuter is slightly thicker than the UAG, but not to the extent that it is uncomfortable in a front pocket. I love the deep screen bezel and camera lens insets of the Otterbox, despite the slight additional thickness of the case this requires. Great protection!Installation is very simple due to the two-piece construction of the case. I had put a Verizon-branded tempered glass screen protector on the GN3, and the case did not interfere with the protector at all. The button pressure required to activate the phone controls is exactly right...not too firm, but not light enough to cause inadvertent pocket activation. As with all Otterbox products that I have come into contact with, the tooling and precision are excellent, as good as it ever gets. The case is flawless in that respect. To me, the charging and earphone port covers (flaps of the interior soft part of the case) are superfluous, since other ports are left uncovered. On the Defender, it makes sense, as that case is designed for extreme conditions. On the Commuter, I don't feel they are needed. To me, they're just in the way.I like this case well enough that I may buy another...maybe Merlot or Berry. Change is good.
title: OtterBox Commuter Series Case for Samsung Galaxy Note 3 - Retail Packaging - Blue/Navy

As expected, a case like this will add some bulk to your device...but not a lot and thus it makes it quite comfortable to slip in to pockets..etc.Not much else to be said. reviewerName: Amazon Customer "Not all who wander are lost-...
reviewText: I have found that if you're in the market for cases for the Verizon LG G2, you're between a rock and a hard place lately.  OtterBox finally came out with a Defender Case, but it was well after the AT&T; and T-Mobile versions.  Maybe we can lay blame on Verizon for making their LG G2 slightly different with button placement.  However, OtterBox delivered with the Defender.  I just like my Incipio case much better.UNBOXING:The OtterBox Defender for Verizon LG G2 came in a small bubble wrapped envelope.  The box is plastic with a plastic sleeve for the actual case to sit in.  It comes with the case, a belt clip/holster, screen film, and instructions.  The case is 5.75" x 3.25" x 0.75", and when using the belt clip is 6" x 3.5" x 1".  The instructions are all pictures, so it's easy to figure out how to use it.REVIEW:The OtterBox Defender for Verizon LG G2 is definitely sturdy.  I have no worries about dropping it and having it survive a fall.  However, this case is just too big for me.  My Incipio is 5.5" x 3" x 0.5" with the LG G2 in it, and it's a dual soft/hard case.  I've dropped it a couple times with no problems.  It also fits better in the hand than the OtterBox, considering that it doesn't make the phone much thicker.  Likewise, the belt clip/holster makes the OtterBox that much bigger/clunkier.  I suppose it's good if you want to make sure you don't lose your brick of a phone, but I'll go for something that looks and feels better over the OtterBox.  Finally, the screen film is not really a film.  It's a clear plastic shield that sits between the face of your LG G2 and the outside rim of the OtterBox case.  It's quite thick, so it probably protects the screen better, but touch sensitivity suffers.  I used the case without the shield and got my own screen film and it works fine.OVERALL:I give the OtterBox Defender a 4 out of 5 stars, because overall it's a great phone case for protection.  However, I can't stand how big it is.  It won't fit in most pockets or women's clutches, and makes the phone clunky to hold (especially if you have small hands).  Likewise, the included screen shield is garbage.  If you like OtterBox, or are into safety over form, go ahead and get this case.  I recommend it, but it's not the case for me.  I'll stick with my Incipio.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for LG G2 (Verizon)- Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: Bought this thinking it was the case for my version of the G2, but it's for the Verizon version (Which I think is dumb that they have their own SLIGHTLY different version). It still fit my Sprint G2, and it does what it was meant to do.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for LG G2 (Verizon)- Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: On the positive side, this is a sturdy case that will probably protect your phone better than just about anything out there.  It fits tightly (not going to come off accidentally), and the clip would be very handy.Unfortunately, there were so many things about this case that I couldn't stand, I couldn't wait to put on my old, flimsy case.* I found this OtterBox to be somewhat difficult to figure out how to put it on.  Actually, the problem was first figuring out how to take it apart.  Once I got that, reassembling it around my phone was pretty easy to figure out.  As other reviewers have noted, the instructions (just illustrations) are not at all helpful.* The screen protector is thick, and it doesn't rest right against the screen.  I found that this made my screen much less responsive than I'm used it.  Worst of all, because the screen protector is built into the case, you don't have the option to use just the case and not the screen protector.  Take off the screen protector, and the whole thing becomes non-functional.* The case is huge.  I guess it needs to be, but this is something to keep in mind.  Add the clip, and you've got some serious luggage on your belt.* The case is difficult to remove.  I broke a few nails trying to pry this thing back open.  And then I noticed that a couple of the snaps were bent out of shape.  So I suspect that repeatedly opening this case could eventually cause the closures to fail.Overall, if you really NEED heavy-duty protection, including for your screen, this might still be a good option for you.  But for the average user who just wants to protect his/her phone from an occasional drop, the negatives will likely outweigh the benefits.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for LG G2 (Verizon)- Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: I picked up an OtterBox when my son got his first iPhone. His phone has been dropped, kicked, sat on, you name it, and there's not a mark on the phone anywhere (though the silicone has torn in a few places and the plastic case itself has a crack). A friend of mine recently picked up the LG G2 and he works in construction, so I knew he needed this. I now have an Otterbox on all my devices, including two iPhones, an iPad Air, and an iPad mini and they have yet to let me down. I won't use anything else until my kiddos are older and can handle these things more carefully. I still cringe a bit when I see my very expensive and very shiny gadget falling to the floor, but it is well protected with the OtterBox Defender. It's been dropped from as high as 4 feet, and though I don't dare do it myself, I've seen video reviews of it being dropped from 3 stories and then being run over by a car with no damage to the phone.Just want to point out, this case is NOT waterproof, but it will protect it from minor spills. My mini has been drenched in apple juice more than once and come out completely dry. The case seems complicated when you first look at it, but it's actually really simple to put on and also to take off, IF you know how to do it, meaning your kids will have no idea how to get it off. Love the built in screen protector also. Keeps moisture out and no annoying bubbles to deal with! Can't recommend enough for all your gadgets.
title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for LG G2 (Verizon)- Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: My son have had the Otterbox for the Verizon LG G2 for several weeks now and he couldn't be happier. First, Though the the screen protector is a bit too far from the phone screen. He has  learned to get used to it and it is not a problem. In fact, it gives me the added security that my device is fully protected. I would not recommend cutting out the screen protector. The touch needs a bit of adjusting to, but it is not a problem at all. Of course you need to clean the screen, probably daily, just as you would do if it was not on there. Also, he love the belt clip. He can carry on conversations with the phone on my belt clip while doing something else with my hands. And the buttons on the back? Genius design by LG. I wouldn't be surprised to see other phone companies copying that soon. Recommended.

reviewText: I have purchased several OtterBox cases and prefer the Defender. I like the confidence it provides to me knowing that it will protect my phone from rough drops. I have dropped my phone on hard surfaces like concrete, tile, pavement several times and the Defender case has always saved it.  The screen protector is built in and unlike the skim type with bubbles. reviewText: The Otterbox Defender Series Case saved my phone! I had just gotten this product for review not two days before I dropped my phone in a parking lot getting into my car. Believe it or not, I hurriedly took the cover off and my screen and phone was intact.Otterbox has designed a case for the Verizon LG G2 and while the case IS bulky and adds weight to your phone, I will take those few ounces over a broken phone anyway.The only downside? title: OtterBox Defender Series Case for LG G2 (Verizon)- Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: This case isn't like the OtterBox cases from a while ago.  The design is fantastic.First: I don't think I've seen a case offer better (non-waterproof) protection.  If I dropped my phone down a flight of stairs I wouldn't even worry.Second: The inner shell snaps on with a perfect fit.  It's actually kind of hard to get off once it's on so make sure you clean that screen protector part really well before you snap it into place.Third: The rubber outer shell is tough but forgiving.  The rubber part clips on to the inner plastic shell all the way around the screen.  On previous OtterBox cases the rubber part only connected to the inner case at specific points which allowed the rubber parts between the attachment points to get saggy and end up looking and feeling like junk.  With the new design the rubber part actually takes some work to remove.Fourth: The entire setup is solid, no creakiness or cheap feels here.All that said there are two down sides to this case.One: The belt clip is massive.  It feels like a TV clipped to your belt.  There really isn't a way around this problem though since the case itself is large.  Anyone buying an Otterbox probably already knows this.  The clip also doubles as a kick stand for the phone.  This doesn't affect my star rating.Two:  The screen protector is kind of janky.  It's the same protector OtterBox has been using for years.  Touch works perfectly through it, but it's not as clear as I'd like it to be and nor does it stick to the screen (it's more of a free floating screen protector).  This allows dust and stuff to get under the screen protector.  Since the case takes some effort to take off the dust problem is mildly infuriating.  I wish they'd stop using this setup and just give you a separate high quality stick on screen protector.  I've already just removed them and moved on with my life.  Again this isn't a big issue, just a personal preference.Overall this case rocks.
title: OtterBox Defender Series for Nokia Lumia Icon - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: This thing is a bit of a pain to get open in the first place if you haven't had one before, like me.  The instructions are just a few drawings.  After peeling the rubber shell, and you start to split the case itself open, there's tabs that they don't show in the drawings.  They make it look like you just pop it open, but while one edge comes apart easily, the second half doesn't, and I nearly broke the small bits of plastic in the middle of the short ends bending it.  Then I saw the little tabs on those short ends, and used a pen to push the tabs in to get it to separate.  Once that was done, I cleaned my screen well (didn't want any gunk stuck between the protective skin and the screen) and put in in place.  It fit perfectly, snugged right in. I popped the plastic top back on, then squeezed it back into the rubber shell.I'll admit, I was ready to dislike this case before it even arrived.  In the first month I owned my Icon, I bought six or seven cases, trying to find one I like.  I have never dropped a phone or any other PDA since I've started using them in the 90's.  In part due to the fact that I always get phone covers that have some grip to them, since most smart phones themselves are slipperier than greased eels with their polished aluminum and glass.  I prefer a small case that's unobtrusive.  I'm not looking for protection in case I drop one, I'm not trying to keep it out of the elements - those are things I deal with on my own simply by being careful.  I just want a case that's light, thin, and lets it not be so slippery.  For me, "protective" cases have always just seemed to be overkill.And now that I've switched away from iPhones again, and am on a phone with a built in inductive charger, my new Jeep has an inductive charger station built into the armrest.  So my cases have needed to fit inside of that.  So I went through a lot of cases to find the right one that fit all my criteria.  This Otterbox doesn't fit any of requirements, other than the fact that it's grippy.  Not just the sides, but the bottom surface as well, so when you set it somewhere, it'll stay there even if it's an inclined surface, or a surface in a moving vehicle.  So I was actually planning to give this the heave-ho when I was done testing simply based on my preconceptions.I had not counted on how well it fit the hand, or how solid and good it felt.  The button covers are pretty much a complete non issue.  They're less intrusive than all but my favorite case.  They cause no problems whatsoever with the button use, they don't add any noticeable required force to operate, they don't feel unnatural and add a bizarre feel as a few of the cases I've tried did.The screen protector gives an odd feeling though to someone who prefers no protectors, only glass.  It's not bad, doesn't really impair use other than feeling like a slightly rougher texture.  In no way did it impede functionality or recognition of any touches, whether in normal phone and data use, or while playing any games.  And I really appreciate the bevel in the front edges that facilitates using the screen.  It allows for that curve in the fingertips so that you can get your fingertip on the very edge of the screen comfortably.  Many are just a straight edge there, and it's awkward and you kind of have to jam your finger into the "corner" created by the edge and the surface of the glass.  No issues like that with these bevels.  But it "floats" so I can see dust between this and the glass becoming a problem down the road.The phone in the case didn't move it far enough away from the inductive charging pad either, it charges fine wirelessly when in this case.  The holster moves it too far though, so it won't charge with that snapped in place as well.The port covers for the headphone jack and charging port are wider rectangles, so there should be no problems with plugs being able to plug into those ports with the cover on.  The default USB charger that comes with the phone fits fine with a surprising amount of space around it.One of the biggest reasons I dislike summer is that it deprives me of the reason to wear a jacket.  I like jackets since I have pockets to carry things.  I've never liked putting a phone in my pockets, even before I got something as big as this one.  So the holster intrigued me.  I haven't had one of these since a very old Motorola windows phone back in the mid to late 90's.  But now that Wisconsin is finally seeing 50's and 60's, the coats will soon be gone, and the holster could really come in handy.  I like how the clasp can be snapped into the holder and become a little kickstand, although I've never had need for one of those either.  I don't use my phone for watching multimedia or anything, so a kickstand isn't something I'd use.  But it's a nice design element regardless.  One nice feature is how the case is designed to snap into place in the holster no matter which way you have it turned.  The long ends of the phone both have the same indents for the holster to grab, so it'll go in no matter what.  It's a bit of a trick to get used to popping it out with one hand only, and doing it without dropping it, but it doesn't take long to get the hang of it.It does add a bit of weight, not much though, you just feel it's more hefty.  And I actually like that, as it makes it feel more secure in your hand somehow, that extra weight.  Maybe it's just because  you grip it a little more when you feel it, but no matter the reason, it just makes the phone feel better.One other thing this helps with is tilting your head to the side when you're just using shoulder and ear to hold it in place.  The surface of the back, plus the added thickness it gives the phone, makes this a much more viable alternative.  Just a couple nights ago I was trying to talk to someone like that while I was on their computer in a remote session helping them with a problem, and I just couldn't do it easily, and ended up calling them from my landline instead.  This case actually would've negated that requirement.The downside is that it doesn't fit in my car's onboard wireless charging pad.  But I've found that I have a habit of forgetting my phone when it's in there, and I'm running around client sites without it until I need it for something, can't find it, then realize I have to hoof it back to my car to get it.  So maybe not being able to charge in there wouldn't be such a bad thing, I can still use the multiple cigarette outlets or even the 120v outlet behind the armrest, and charge it with a cable instead in the built in charger if I really need to.  But since my computer case has three different charging batteries, running out of juice isn't really that big of a concern for me.So here I am, in the position of actually thinking I'm going to keep using this case, the one that I was ready to throw out even before I received it, because they really did a good job of making a solid, protective case that isn't just annoying in most respects.  It's not so bulky that it's a turn off, the protector doesn't impact either the touch or the brightness of the display, the button covers don't really feel like they're there at all...  It's the opposite of most of the more serious cases designed for protection that I've ever seen, and this one may become my daily case, much to my surprise.
title: OtterBox Defender Series for Nokia Lumia Icon - Retail Packaging - Black

reviewText: There is nothing like the feeling of knowing your phone is well protected and will survive the trials of an active life, and because of that, and because I've cracked a few screens in my phone-owning lifetime, I don't think I will never put my phones in anything but an Otterbox case again.This is perfectly formed for a safe secure fit, and the addition of a belt clip attachment which doubles as a stand makes it a no-brainer.The only downside is that it makes the phone very clunky and a little harder to fit into a jeans pocket, but it's worth it, so I'd recommend buying one.
title: OtterBox Defender Series for Nokia Lumia Icon - Retail Packaging - Black
